<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Liberia 1stLd-Writethru a0622 03-22 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Liberia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0622,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Twelve Arrested In Alleged Coup Plot</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with expanded government account
of plot, background. No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MONROVIA, Liberia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested 12 men, including an
opposition party leader, in foiling a plot to overthrow the
government and assassinate President Samuel Doe, Information
Minister Emmanuel Bowier said Tuesday.
   Bowier told a news conference seven plotters were still at
large, including an army captain and two sergeants.
   He said those arrested included Gabriel Kpolleh, leader of the
banned Liberia Unification Party, party lawyer Cephar Mbandi and
four soldiers, .
   The minister said the plot was uncovered on March 16. He said it
was a conspiracy ``to destabilize the government, create internal
strife and overthrow the government by assassinating the president
of Liberia.''
   Bowier said arms, ammunition and military uniforms were found in
a building in the Sinkor district of Monrovia.
   Investigations continued but the situation was under control, he
said.
   Bowier read from a prepared statement and declined to answer
questions. Journalists were warned not to run editorial comments or
cartoons on the plot before the defendants go on trial. The
minister gave no court date.
   The Unification party on Monday released a statement expressing
concern over the arrests of Kpolleh and Mbandi. It said several
properties owned by Kpolleh and his family were destroyed during
investigations by security forces and that his wife narrowly
escaped being raped. It did not elaborate.
   Bowier advised reporters not to believe any press releases
issued by the Unification party, saying it was banned and its
statements had no credibility.
   Doe, who came to power in a bloody April 1980 coup, has been the
target of several assassination attempts. An attempted coup on Nov.
12, 1985, resulted in more than 600 deaths and the destruction of
the village of the ringleader, former Brig. Gen Thomas Quiwonkpa,
who was killed in the attempt.
   Quiwonkpa, who had been living in exile, led the attempt
following elections that opposition leaders and independent
observers said were rigged.
   Liberia, Africa's oldest republic, was founded in 1847 by freed
American slaves. Descendents of the slaves, who were a minority,
controlled the government until Doe, from the Krahn ethnic group,
stormed the presidential mansion in April 1980, killing
then-President William Tolbert.
   The economy declined under the rule of the former army master
sergeant. Major Western creditors suspended aid to Liberia pending
payment of debts. Last year the United States sent 17 financial
experts to Monrovia to oversee operations of the Finance Ministry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
