<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--PershingLaunches     03-22 0138</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Pershing Launches,0142</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pershing 2 Missile Launches Successful</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Army successfully test-fired
five Pershing 2 missiles slated to be banned from deployment under
a treaty with the Soviet Union.
   The treaty, signed Dec. 8 by President Reagan and Soviet leader
Mikhail Gorbachev, does not require either side to withdraw or
destroy missiles until it has been ratified by both governments.
The Senate is expected to approve the pact in late spring.
   The unarmed missiles were successfully fired Monday under
battlefield conditions, the Army said.
   The Pershing is a field missile _ each of which costs $4 million
_ launched from its own assembly that can be carried by a truck.
   The Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces, or INF, treaty, calls for
the destruction of all missiles with a range of 300 to 3,400 miles.
</TEXT>
