<1ST_LINE>r i PM-ExiledLeaders     03-22 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Exiled Leaders,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>United States Has Encouraged Several Leaders to Choose Exile</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has urged Panama's military leader, Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega, to leave the country and live in Spain. The
United State has encouraged other world leaders to give up power
and go into exile. Among them:
   Syngman Rhee _ The South Korean president went into exile in
Hawaii in May, 1960 following widespread political unrest and
allegations that he had rigged the presidential election. He died
in 1965.
   Shah of Iran _ Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi gave up power during
the Islamic revolution and flew to Egypt in his private plane on
Jan. 15, 1979. He was allowed temporary refuge in the United States
for medical treatment, but was not allowed to live in the United
States permanently. He went to Panama and then to Egypt, where he
died in 1980.
   Anastasio Somoza _ The Nicaraguan president fled the country
Jan. 19, 1979 under pressure from the Organization of American
States and after the United States refused to support him. A
Sandinista-led coalition took power. Somoza lived in Paraguay and
was assassinated on Sept. 7, 1980.
   ``Baby Doc'' Duvalier _ Jean-Claude Duvalier and his family fled
Haiti on Feb. 7, 1986 aboard a U.S. Air Force plane following
months of unrest. His departure ended the political dynasty founded
in 1957 by his father, Francois ``Papa Doc'' Duvalier. Duvalier is
in exile in France.
   Ferdinand Marcos _ Fled the Philippines with his family aboard a
U.S. jet on Feb. 26, 1986 in the face of mounting opposition by
political foes and the military. Marcos is in exile in Hawaii.
</TEXT>
