<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 0003EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CBS-Hewitt     03-22 0666</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CBS-Hewitt,0683</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`60 Minutes' Producer Marks 40 Years at CBS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Don Hewitt, who marks his 40th anniversary with
CBS News today, recalls that he landed his first job at the network
after a friend suggested his experience at a newsphoto service
might come in handy.
   ``I said, what does CBS want with picture experience? Radio
doesn't need any pictures. He said, `No _ television.' I said
whata-vision?''
   Today, the 65-year-old outspoken creator and executive producer
of ``60 Minutes'' is looking beyond current television technology,
foreseeing a time when networks are superfluous and television news
is beamed directly into subscribers' homes.
   Hewitt began his career as associate director and later producer
of the network's first television newscast, ``Douglas Edwards With
the News'' and later the ``CBS Evening News'' with Walter Cronkite.
   He remembers covering the coronation of Queen Elizabeth II with
Edward R. Murrow and flying back to the United States aboard a
chartered airliner editing the kinescope that viewers would see on
the news _ no videotapes, no satellite transmissions.
   ``I didn't think there was ever going to be satellites, bounce
signals off a star, are you crazy?,'' he said, laughing. But
Hewitt, who considered buying CBS News a few years ago, thinks it's
feasible to one day broadcast news directly to homes. News services
already are beaming footage to local television stations, so
Hewitt's idea is not so far-fetched.
   ``I think that the network news departments, they might not even
work for a network 10 years from now,'' he said. ``There might not
be any networks because it may be an outmoded delivery system.
   ``I'm not sure you don't have a large newsroom somewhere and you
just have direct broadcast ... feeding news into people's homes,
for a price same way they pay for a newspaper.''
   He also foresees delivering newspapers into home printers by
satellite.
   ``I think about it more than most people, as you can see. And I
wonder how long the networks in their present form will be
around,'' he said.
   Some other samples of Hewitt's opinions:
   _``60 Minutes'': ``I've always said all we do in this broadcast
is shine lights on people in dark corners, and if people in dark
corners are doing things they shouldn't be doing, all we did was
turn the light on.''
   _The importance of pictures on television: ``The accepted wisdom
in television was always you put words to pictures. I don't believe
that. You put pictures to words. You start with the words. The
audio is always more important to me than the video.''
   _Televised presidential debates (Hewitt produced the famous 1960
meeting of Richard Nixon and John F. Kennedy): ``It's still a
terrible format and we shouldn't be doing them. They should have
real debates. ... The Republican candidate and Democratic candidate
should head up a team of two or three debaters who are really good
and can really cross-examine the other side and give them a hard
time, and they ought to do it in front of a joint session of
Congress, and it will produce something other than this sterile
show where what it is is a joint press conference, not really a
debate.''
   _This year's election: ``I don't think there's enough caffeine
in America to keep the electorate awake during a Dukakis-Bush
campaign.''
   _Politicians: ``I don't put politicians on the air if I can help
it, because I instinctively don't believe them. I believe they're
only interested in getting themselves elected, and they only say
what they think will get themselves elected.''
   _Ratings: ``No matter what I think about ratings, and whether
they're accurate and everything, I don't say anything because
they've been awfully good to me.''
   _The future: ``I know where I'll be in nine years. I'm going to
be here. My contract isn't up until I'm 74. Ironclad, nobody gets
out. Now the question is, will there be a CBS? I think so. Some
form. Maybe not this form.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
