<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 0020EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Israel-Media     03-22 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Israel-Media,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Banning Reporters Won't Necessarily Ease Israeli Image Problem</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Banning reporters and photographers from the
West Bank and the Gaza Strip could prove to be a public relations
blunder for Israel and might not be effective anyway, several media
observers say.
   Larry Gross, a professor at The Annenberg School of
Communications at the University of Pennsylvania, said it would be
``bad policy'' for Israel to impose more restrictions on reporters
covering unrest in the occupied territories.
   ``It would be a public relations risk _ one I hope they don't
take,'' Gross said. He said Israel could jeopardize its reputation
as the only true democracy in the Middle East, which U.S. officials
cite in providing millions of dollars to the country each year.
   But the Israelis are obviously watching the situation in South
Africa to determine if the advantages of restricting the press
outweigh the disadvantages, he said.
   South Africa's widely condemned white government has succeeded
in dampening outside interest in that country's racial problems by
banning coverage of any security activities, experts agree. The
order went into effect in June 1986.
   But Gross doubted Israel would be able to ``keep the lid on''
coverage of the occupied territories in a way the South Africans
have virtually halted reporting in black areas.
   Israel's domestic political opposition and a thriving domestic
press could prevent a blackout on coverage of the territories, he
said.
   Local Israeli army commanders already have authority to close
areas in the occupied territories at random, and they have been
doing so with increasing frequency. A parliamentary committee in
Jerusalem is studying whether to ban the media formally from the
territories.
   Yael Dayan, a well-known Israeli peace activist, said during a
recent U.S. visit that tough restrictions on the press would likely
fail, because Israelis demand news and have an aggressive press
corps.
   Eric Goldstein of the Committee to Protect Journalists, a New
York-based group that monitors conditions for journalists
worldwide, said Israel might be able to stave off intense scrutiny
by banning cameras.
   ``But in the long run the greater public interest is served by
allowing the press access,'' he said. The committee opposes
restrictions on reporters.
   Some Americans have joined Israeli government officials in
complaining that reporters, particularly those working for foreign
television networks, have helped incite rock-throwing Palestinians
in the territories.
   New York Mayor Edward Koch has said a television ban would be
justified, and former Secretary of State Henry A. Kissinger
reportedly told prominent American Jews during a meeting that
banning television cameras would be a good idea. Kissinger says his
remarks were distorted.
   Jeff Cohen of Fairness and Accuracy in Reporting criticized a
``censorship lobby'' for supporting restrictions that, in the
United States, would be considered an unacceptable violation of
freedom of the press.
   ``It would be one more comparison with South Africa, and it
would hurt Israel,'' he said. FAIR is a liberal New York group that
examines the media.
   Fred W. Friendly, former president of CBS News and a professor
at Columbia University's School of Journalism, said it would be
wrong to ban reporters from the occupied territories.
   ``That can't be right _ that's what South Africa did,'' he said.
   But Friendly said television coverage, with its time constraints
and powerful pictures, can fail to portray a story accurately.
`What is also wrong is letting the picture run away with the
story,'' he told The New York Times.
   Mortimer Zuckerman, editor-in-chief of U.S. News & World Report,
had the same complaint. ``Television has polluted the public debate
because it is inherently difficult for pictures to give context,
history and meaning to events,'' he recently wrote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
