<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TrainCollision     03-22 0166</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Train Collision,0170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eight Workers Injured In Trail Collision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DIXON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Chicago & Northwestern freight trains
collided head-on Monday, injuring eight workers, three of them
seriously, police said.
   An eastbound train with four engines and about 130 cars collided
with a westbound train consisting of a switch engine and a single
car while both trains were going 20 mph to 30 mph, police said.
Officials were investigating the cause of the accident late Monday.
   The collision occurred about noon in the southwest part of
Dixon, a town of 15,000 in north-central Illinois, and the crash
could be heard up to a mile away, police said.
   Eight employees were on the trains at the time of the accident,
and were taken to Katherine Shaw Bethea Hospital in Dixon.
   Steve Wilkerson, 35, of Rock Falls; and Charles Holdren, 56 and
Robert Fonder, 38, both of Sterling, were listed in serious
condition late Monday, hospital officials said. The other five
workers were treated and released.
</TEXT>
