<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Candidates-Money     03-22 0741</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Candidates-Money,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson Alters Figures on Spending</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential candidate Pat
Robertson, faced with bumping up against the federally-imposed
campaign spending limit, revised some of his state spending figures
downward in his newly filed campaign financial statement.
   The spending allocations for nine states showed lower cumulative
expenditures in the report filed Monday than the figures Robertson
reported a month earlier.
   Robertson's staff did not return a phone call Monday to answer
questions about the revisions.
   In his report filed Monday with the Federal Election Commission,
the former TV evangelist reported he had spent $19 million through
Feb. 29 against the spending cap of $23 million that applies to
expenditures for the entire primary season.
   Even with the downward revisions in some state spending figures,
the total was still more than the $17.6 million in spending against
the cap that he reported through the end of January.
   Candidates who receive federal matching funds must agree to stay
within the spending limit. The reports candidates filed Monday show
new financial activity for the month of February as well as
cumulative totals.
   Robertson's revisions were in figures reported for Califonria,
District of Columbia, Louisiana, Michigan, North Carolina,
Oklahoma, Tennessee, Texas, and Virginia.
   The biggest was in Texas where his previous report showed an
allocation of $1.1 million, but the new report shows an allocation
of $746,514 through February.
   Robertson, who has spent more overall than any other candidate,
also reported he borrowed another $1.9 million in February.
   He has taken out more than $9 million in loans since he began
his campaign last year, and ended February with $8.4 million in
debts and $7.4 million in cash on hand.
   Financial reports filed by his rivals show that Sen. Bob Dole
also has narrowly outspent Vice President George Bush, as Bush has
built a huge lead over both Robertson and Dole in the GOP race.
   Democratic contender Michael Dukakis, the governor of
Massachussetts, continues to raise more money than his rivals, all
of whom have resorted to borrowing.
   Dukakis raised $2.9 million in February, including federal
matching funds, compared with less than $2 million each by Rep.
Richard Gephardt of Missouri, Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois, Sen.
Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee, and Jesse Jackson.
   Gephardt borrowed and repaid $149,000, during February, Simon
borrowed $292,352, and Jackson borrowed $500,000. Gore did not take
out loans in February, which is the month covered by the new
financial statements. But his aides have said he borrowed $1
million before the March 8 Super Tuesday contests in 20 states, and
$300,000 before the Illinois primary March 15.
   Dole's receipts for February were $2 million, giving him $8.8
million for the year, including federal matching funds based on
contributions raised privately. Bush raised $1.5 million during
February, $8.7 for the year, his report shows.
   But despite raising and spending more money through February,
Dole failed to interrupt the Bush push toward the August nominating
convention in New Orleans. Bush has won 788 delegates so far to
Dole's 178, according to The Associated Press delegate count.
   Robertson raised $5 million for the month, including his $1.9
million loan, which brought his total receipts this year to $18.3
million.
   For the month, he spent $3.1 million, to Dole's $5.3 million and
Bush's $4 million.
   Dole has spent $18 million against the spending camp, and Bush
$14.1 million.
   Dole ended February with $836,445 in the bank and $716,107 in
bills. Bush had $6.7 million in cash on hand _ more than any other
candidate in the race _ and had $251,225 in debts.
   Among Democrats, Gephardt ended February with $1 million in
debts and only about half that in available cash.
   Simon was $825,199 in debt, and had $760,755 in cash on hand,
the reports showed.
   Jackson owed $845,857, and had $428,420 on hand.
   Gore had $342,964 in the bank and $91,858 in debts. But that was
before Gore took out $1.3 million in loans during March, according
to capaign aides. Figures detailing those transactions will appear
in the financial reports due next month.
   Candidates who run up debts generally do so in the knowledge
they will be receiving federal matching funds to help pay off the
loans.
   Dukakis had $2.9 million in cash on hand at the end of the
month, and $569,344 in debts.
   Dukakis was the Democrat closest to the spending cap, at $11.4
million.
</TEXT>
