<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ChildSexAbuse     03-22 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Child Sex Abuse,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Says Abuse Occurs More Frequently At Home Than In Day Care</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Widespread publicity about a handful of sexual
abuse cases involving day care centers may have caused parents to
be more worried than necessary about the safety of their children,
researchers say.
   A study released Monday by the Family Research Laboratory of the
University of New Hampshire estimated that substantially more
children are abused at home than in day care settings: 8.9 per
10,000 children at home compared with 5.5 per 10,000 at day care.
   David Finkelhor, who directed the study, said the results are
``a far cry'' from the impression many people have gotten because
of news accounts about a few incidents of child abuse at day care
centers.
   ``We do not think day care centers in general are high risk
areas,'' said Finkelhor.
   However, he emphasized that child abuse does occur at some day
care centers and is particularly hard to ferret out because the
perpetrators do not fit stereotypes.
   Only 8 percent had prior arrest records, 50 percent were college
graduates and 40 percent were women, he said.
   ``We just can't say there is a nice shortcut, a couple of easy
rules to spot places that might be dangerous,'' he said.
   For example, Finkelhor noted, the study found no signficant
differences between the incidence of child abuse in centers with a
high teacher-to-pupil ratio and in less adequately staffed centers.
   However, Finkelhor and two other participants at a news
conference underscored the importance of parents having ready
access to day care center activity and making surprise visits to
see what is going on.
   ``Parents need to go the extra mile to become familiar with the
day care center they choose,'' said David S. Liederman, executive
director of the Child Welfare League of America. ``They should drop
in unannounced and if the center doesn't like it, they should
consider whether that is the kind of place they want their children
to be.''
   Liederman said he agreed with the study's findings and said day
care centers generally ``are safe places for children.''
   Sue Bredekamp, director of the National Academy of Early
Childhood Programs for the National Association for the Education
of Young Children, said the report was the ``most comprehensive,
national study of child sexual abuse in day care to date.''
   ``It is our hope that Dr. Finkelhor's findings ... will be as
widely disseminated and as influential to policy makers as were
reports of several infamous cases of abuse in the past,'' she said.
   The survey examined 270 cases of sexual abuse involving 1,639
children from 1983 to 1985 and made an in-depth study of a random
sample of 43 cases. An estimated 1.5 million children were cared
for in day care centers during that time.
   Finkelhor said there is no evidence the incidence of child abuse
in day care settings was higher during the past two years than
during the 1983-85 period surveyed.
   The study was commissioned by the National Center on Child Abuse
and Neglect, an agency of the Department of Health and Human
Services, and released in conjunction with the Children's Hospital
National Medical Center.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
