<1ST_LINE>r a AM-O'HareSafety     03-22 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-O'Hare Safety,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA to Assign Another Air Traffic Coordinator to O'Hare</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration has decided
to add an additional air traffic coordinator on each shift at
O'Hare International Airport, an FAA spokesman said Monday.
   The decision by William H. Pollard, director of the FAA's Great
Lakes region, was made after a U.S. House subcommittee hearing
Friday on safety problems at the airport, said spokesman Mort
Edelstein.
   Beginning in the near future, Edelstein said, the FAA will
assign two full-time air traffic coordinators both day and night at
O'Hare. Until now, only one full-time coordinator has been in the
O'Hare tower per shift, he said.
   The coordinators help improve the performance of the tower's air
traffic controllers.
   One of those who addressed the subcommittee hearing was James
Burnett, head of the National Transportation Safety Board, who
warned of what he called ``a disturbing number of near-collisions''
at the busy Chicago airport.
   The five-member subcommittee hearing was held at the request of
Rep. Richard J. Durbin, D-Ill.
   Edelstein said he did not know the exact date when the
additional coordinators would be assigned to O'Hare.
</TEXT>
