<1ST_LINE>r p PM-NevadaGOP     03-22 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nevada GOP,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson Forces Will Dominate At Nevada State GOP Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supporters of former television evangelist
Pat Robertson will apparently control the state GOP convention in
Reno next month as a result of weekend county conventions, party
officials said.
   Nevada Republicans use a three-step system of caucuses and
conventions to pick their national convention delegates. The
process began with precinct caucuses last month, at which a straw
poll was conducted.
   In the straw poll, Vice President George Bush led with 27
percent, followed by Bob Dole with 22 percent and Robertson with 15
percent. But Robertson supporters claimed victory by saying most of
the 23 percent undecided voters in the poll actually were Robertson
supporters.
   The straw poll participants were not bound to presidential
candidates, however.
   At the county conventions, held over this past weekend,
delegates were elected to the state convention April 21-23, where
in turn national convention delegates will be elected.
   The delegate breakdown for the state convention won't be known
for several days. But the Robertson forces dominated Republican
conventions in Nevada's two biggest counties, Clark and Washoe.
Party leaders said it appeared Robertson got more than half the 800
state delegates in those two counties alone.
   Robertson also picked up some delegates at the GOP's county
conventions elsewhere in Nevada, although his supporters showed
less strength in the outlying areas, party officials said.
   State GOP Chairwoman Sally Vitkus-McKinney said Monday that
party newcomers _ which most Robertson backers are _ are welcome.
But she added there is frustration because Nevada probably will
wind up with its 20-member delegation to the national convention
committed to somone who won't be the presidential nominee.
   Robertson's state director, Steve Wark, said there's no way he
would encourage the Robertson delegates to switch to Bush at the
state convention level, even though their candidate is clearly far
behind.
   ``Robertson supporters are not about to roll over. They're
making a statement and sticking to their commitment,'' he said.
However, he said Robertson supporters would be prepared to support
Bush at the national Republican convention.
   Robertson, after big losses on Super Tuesday, indicated he
intends to remain in the race, but has virtually given up hope of
getting the nomination. He has talked more at recent appearances
about his role at the convention, his long-term influence on the
party and a possible bid in 1992.
</TEXT>
