<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     03-22 0863</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,860</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Smaller Crop, Higher Demand Mean That Ain't Hay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hay prices nationally have been averaging
around 12 percent higher than a year ago, reflecting a smaller 1987
crop and some increase in demand.
   The Agriculture Department in January revised 1987 hay output
downward to 149.1 million tons from last October's preliminary
forecast of 153.7 million tons.
   A new report by the department's Economic Research Service says
that the U.S. hay area turned out to be about 500,000 acres larger
than estimated in October but that the yield was reduced by 4
percent to 2.46 tons per acre.
   The 1987 hay crop was 6.4 million tons smaller than the record
of 155.5 million tons produced in 1986.
   ``Alfalfa and alfalfa mixture hay production turned out to be
84.6 million tons, down 7 million tons from 1986, and all other hay
production of 64.6 million tons was 600,000 tons above the previous
year's 64 million,'' the report said.
   Acording to USDA production figures for 1987, California was the
leading all-hay state with more than 9 million tons, followed by:
Wisconsin, 8.88 million; Minnesota, 7.8 million; South Dakota, 7.09
million; and Iowa, 6.93 million.
   Last May 1 at the start of the 1987-88 hay crop season, the
inventory on hand was estimated at 32.4 million tons, the most
since 1980. Adding the 1987 crop, that made a total hay supply of
181.5 million tons for the marketing year that runs through April
30, slightly less than the 1986-87 suppply of 182.2 million tons.
   The hay stockpile on Dec. 1 was reported at 119.7 million tons,
meaning that 61.8 million tons had been consumed during the seven
months since May 1. In the same period a year earlier, hay
consumption was 60.5 million tons, the report said.
   Hay prices paid by farmers and ranchers averaged $64.60 per ton
during the May-November period, up $4.74 per ton from a year
earlier. In December and January of this year, prices averaged
$63.75 per ton, up $7.65 from a year earlier.
   According to USDA estimates, the value of hay production in
1987, based on market prices, was more than $9.1 billion, ranking
the crop third among all U.S. farm commodities. Only corn at $12.2
billion and soybeans, $10.4 billion, were valued higher.
   Those value estimates, incidentally, are not sales receipts or
marketings. The USDA estimates are based upon total farm values,
whether a commodity is sold or used by the producer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department has sold Mexico
30,000 metric tons of surplus non-fat dry milk for $1,260 per ton,
about a third less than it cost American taxpayers.
   Acting Undersecretary Richard W. Goldberg said Monday the
surplus powdered milk was sold by the department's Commodity Credit
Corp. to CONASUPO, the Mexican government's food purchasing
authority.
   Goldberg said the sale ``reflects the world market price for
non-fat dry milk at the time the sale was negotiated'' with Mexico.
Deliveries are scheduled through March 1989. In addition, the CCC
provided Mexico with a three-year credit arrangement at commercial
rates of interest, he said.
   According to a recent CCC report, about 454 million pounds of
non-fat dry milk were held in storage, with a value of more than
$385 million, or about 85 cents per pound. There are approximately
2,205 pounds in a metric ton, which translates to a U.S. value of
$1,874 per ton.
   The surplus was acquired by CCC through purchases of cheese,
butter and non-fat dry milk to support the price of milk paid to
dairy farmers.
   Congress in 1985 farm law mandated the export sale of 150,000
tons of dairy products annually for the three fiscal years ending
Sept. 30, 1988. The latest deal with Mexico boosted sales this year
to 77,520 tons, Goldberg said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exporters have sold China an additional
200,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized prices, the
Agriculture Department said.
   The sale, equal to 7.34 million bushels, was handled by
Continental Grain Co. and will be shipped in the 1988-89 wheat
marketing year that will begin on June 1.
   Melvin E. Sims, general sales manager for the department's
Foreign Agricultural Service, said Monday the sales were part of an
authorized 1.2 million tons of wheat announced Feb. 5 under the
Export Enhancement Program, or EEP.
   Although no selling prices or other details were announced,
recent prices of wheat at farm points have averaged around $2.67
per bushel, indicating a U.S. farm value of about $20 million.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels
of wheat.
   China bought more than 4 million tons of wheat under previous
EEP arrangements, which allow exporters to sell commodities at
reduced prices in order to meet foreign competition and then
collect free government surpluses of grain or other commodities as
bonuses, or subsidies.
   Sims said the bonus averaged $24.45 per ton, or about 67 cents
per bushel of wheat. The bonuses will be paid in the form of
surplus commodities owned by the department's Commodity Credit Corp.
   China has 260,000 tons remaining for use under the EEP
initiative announced on Feb. 5, he said.
</TEXT>
