<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DeportationHearing     03-22 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Deportation Hearing,0569</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Family Rallies Around Welshman Who Claims GI Was His
Father</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Old loves and old photographs gave a sentimental
air to the deportation hearing of a Welshman who says he should be
allowed to stay in this country because he is the illegitimate son
of an American soldier.
   The claims of Roger Hobbs, 43, were supported Monday in federal
Immigration Court by the kin of the late Floyd Alexander of Cundy's
Harbor, Maine.
   Alexander, who died in 1970, was an American soldier stationed
in England during World War II.
   Hobbs, a janitor, insists he is the product of a union between
Alexander and Sara Hobbs, of Cardiff, Wales.
   No one has found any legal documents to prove the relationship,
but Alexander's kin say that for many years he talked openly about
his son ``Buddy'' overseas.
   The Immigration and Naturalization Service contends Hobbs hasn't
proved Alexander was his father. It has also said Hobbs has a
criminal record, including attempting to steal a radiator from an
abandoned railway car.
   After Alexander returned from the war, he fathered seven
children in this country and married three different women. About a
dozen members of the Alexander clan came from Maine to stand by the
man they believe is one of them.
   Hobbs also was accompanied by his wife, Anne, 37, and sons,
Richard, 17, Ian, 15, and Wayne, 12. As British citizens, they can
apply for U.S. citizenship if Hobbs wins his case, which is built
on memories, family photos, birth and death certificates and
letters.
   Alexander's first wife, Elsie Van Buren, 60, of Lisbon Falls,
Maine, told Immigration Judge Billino D'Ambrosio that Alexander
wished he could bring Sara Hobbs and her son to this country but
never had the money.
   ``As soon as he met me he told me all about it,'' said Mrs. Van
Buren. ``He told me he lived with her _ and I know he was in love
with her _ and he had a son by her.''
   She said Alexander's mother, Allegra, often wrote to Mrs. Hobbs
and sent clothing and gifts.
   During the hearing, Hobbs sat with head bent at the back of the
small courtroom. He wiped an occasional tear from his eyes. His
burgundy corduroy jacket was emblazoned with the name of his
adopted hometome, Richmond, Maine, and a large American flag patch
was sewn over his heart.
   Mrs. Van Buren said her first husband once told her he signed a
sworn statement that Roger Hobbs was his son. The document hasn't
been found. But she said the documentation of Alexander's blood is
in the face of Roger Hobbs.
   ``I swear by my life on it. (Roger) looked more like my husband
than my children,'' Mrs. Van Buren said.
   Hobbs said he first learned of his relationship with Alexander
in 1968 from his mother, who died 11 years later.
   In October 1984, Hobbs came to this country on a tourist visa
with his family. Their visas expired in 1985 and Hobbs has asserted
his right to citizenship since.
   In 1986, federal rules were changed to give citizenship rights
to foreign children fathered by American men outside marriage.
   Hobbs' family can stay here until the case is settled. A hearing
was continued to July 7.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
