<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf of 1st item, datelined West Springfield, Mass.,
to CORRECT spelling to `Neapolitan,' sted `Neopolitan'; SUBS last
graf of 2nd item datelined Alford, Mass., to CORRECT spelling to
`Audubon,' sted `Audobon'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WEST SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mike Nigro said he was changing
the oil on his truck when he first heard someone coming down the
street singing ``O Sole Mio.'' It was his mailman, Dennis Jordan.
   ``I thought the truck had fallen on me and the angels were
singing to me,'' Nigro said.
   Jordan, a full-time postal worker and a part-time tenor, has
brought music to the ears of his customers along his mail route.
   The 29-year-old letter carrier warms up his voice while on his
route with some easy stuff such as Neapolitan folk songs. He breaks
into arias from ``The Barber of Seville'' after a good lunch.
   ``When I'm in the mood, I'll sing my lungs out,'' he said.
   Jordan has taken formal voice lessons for 12 years and performed
with Project Opera in Northampton and other local groups.
   ``I don't usually sing opera while I'm working,'' he said
recently. ``I'm afraid of using the wrong pitch.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ALFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It might be described as ``Thoreau Meets
the Media Monster.'' Denny Alsop has embarked on a month-long
zigzag canoe trek along 10 Massachusetts rivers _ armed with a jug
of water and a telephone.
   Alsop, 41, says he will use the portable phone to keep in touch
with the media along the way of his trek from the Berkshires to
Boston to draw attention to Massachusetts' water resources.
   ``I think it's wonderful that in the midst of one of the most
densely populated states in the nation, by focusing on an idea and
an element in the environment, I can go and have a great
adventure,'' Alsop told the three dozen environmentalists,
schoolchildren and others gathered at the launch site Monday.
   The 33-day trip, sponsored by the Massachusetts Audubon Society,
includes a planned stop at Walden Pond near Concord, where the
famed 19th century writer Henry David Thoreau lived in an isolated
cabin for more than two years.
</TEXT>
