<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Television     03-22 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Television,0680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Call for Curbs on Media Coverage of IRA Funerals</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Irish, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Horrifying television film of IRA funeral mourners
beating up two British soldiers who were then killed has brought
demands to restrict coverage of such scenes.
   Some lawmakers urged restrictions on funeral coverage or
interviews with leaders of Sinn Fein, the legal political wing of
the outlawed Irish Republican Army. They argue that the cameras'
presence encourages rioting and boosts ``terrorist organizations.''
   ``We're fighting what is in the nature of a war here,'' said
Ivor Stanbrook, senior legislator of the governing Conservative
Party, in urging a ban on interviews with Sinn Fein leaders.
   ``We wouldn't have dreamed during the war of giving currency to
Nazis so I don't see why we should give any credence ... to people
acting as the IRA's propagandists.''
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher has criticized British TV
networks for giving the IRA what she calls the ``oxygen of
publicity.''
   But the Home Office said Monday there were no plans to impose
bans on covering IRA-related news events.
   ``When it comes to covering a demonstration in Britain or a riot
or anything, we can't start saying you go there or you don't go
there or we wouldn't have a free press,'' said spokesman Ian Scott.
   Conservative lawmaker Michael Mates said the publicly funded
British Broadcasting Corp. and commercial Independent Television
News should exercise self-restraint.
   ``I think you have to look very carefully at the question of
whether you would be getting 10,000 people coming to these funerals
if it wasn't for the fact that they are whipped up out there,''
Mates said in a radio interview.
   ``They are paraded by the IRA and Sinn Fein for the TV cameras
so that the world can see that their heroes are being buried with
the total support of the whole population ... they're made to go
along because it's got to be a spectacle.''
   Cameras filmed the initial attack Saturday on the soldiers' car
in Belfast, but were chased off by mourners before the beating
began in earnest, and they did not film the shooting of the men a
few minutes later.
   British newspapers, however, published pictures of the
near-naked bodies the next day.
   ``It was a shocking, brutal event and I was as horrified as
anyone to see things like that on my television screen,'' said
Michael Grade, head of commercial Channel 4.
   ``But you cannot sanitize a story ... The BBC and ITN made
people understand the horror of the situation,'' he told Today
newspaper.
   ``We take great care in what we show,'' said ITN spokeswoman
Geraldine Sharp-Newton. But ``by not showing it we'll not make it
go away.''
   Still, there are inconsistencies. British networks often preface
violent scenes with a warning to viewers, but none preceded the
Belfast footage.
   In the Irish Republic, the state media cannot broadcast
interviews with officials of Sinn Fein, on the grounds that they
speak for an outlawed organization, the IRA.
   South Africa has imposed stringent curbs on reporting in what
are defined as ``unrest areas.'' Offenders face prison, fines or
expulsion.
   The South Africans say violent incidents dropped by 35 percent
immediately after the restrictions were decreed in June 1986.
   International criticism of Israel's handling of Palestinian
unrest has prompted charges that foreign networks distort the
country's image and inflame unrest.
   President Chaim Herzog asked this month whether Israeli
democracy should ``allow this weapon to be turned against my
children and my country.''
   Henry Kissinger, the former U.S. secretary of state, and Mayor
Ed Koch of New York have suggested that Israel ban TV crews
outright from the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Israel has not gone that far, but on March 4 the military for
the first time banned reporters and TV crews from extensive areas
of the occupied lands. They have since renewed the ban repeatedly,
generally on a smaller scale.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
