<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Pope-Gays     03-22 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pope-Gays,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hard Feelings Linger in Gay Community, Six Months after Pope's
Visit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Pope-Costs, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY MARQUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Pope John Paul II arrived here last
fall, homosexuals took to the streets to protest the Vatican's
condemnation of their way of life.
   Roman Catholic officials believe the visit helped heal relations
between homosexuals and the church, but gay activists still recoil
in anger when speaking of John Paul.
   The pope encountered the largest and angriest demonstrations of
his nine-city tour during his 21-hour visit to San Francisco.
Outside Mission Dolores, where the pope met with AIDS victims,
2,000 protesters shouted ``pope, go home'' and ``shame, shame.''
   The Rev. Miles Riley, chief publicist for the Archdiocese of San
Francisco, contends protests were even smaller than reported and
reflected well upon the church's conciliation efforts.
   ``I think there was tremendous healing with the whole gay
community and with AIDS patients,'' Riley said. ``I think much of
the healing took place before he came.''
   The archdiocese and a coalition of gay groups met before the
pope's visit and drafted a joint statement of non-violence.
   Recently, the archdiocese announced the opening of a 40-bed
hospice for homeless AIDS patients.
   Before the pope's visit, the Vatican published a theological
letter that called homosexualtiy an ``intrinsic moral evil.'' While
declaring God's love for homosexuals, the church is opposed to
homosexual relationships.
   ``We are going to be ourselves,'' said John Wahl, an attorney
who coordinated an umbrella group of homosexuals and bisexuals to
oppose the Sept. 17-18 visit. ``We are going to relate to members
of our own sex, just as heterosexual people relate to people of the
opposite sex.
   ``Basically, so long as they insist that same-sex is sinful,
they are our adversaries,'' Wahl said.
   However, confrontations between church and homosexuals have
moved elsewhere. Members of Dignity, made up of Catholic, sexually
active gays, were arrested during demonstrations in March and
February at St. Patrick's Cathedral in New York.
   At one of those services, Cardinal John O'Connor said the
church's teaching against homosexual behavior would not be changed.
``We cannot alter the Gospel,'' he said.
   In January, about 250 Dignity members and supporters held a
candlelight vigil outside St. Joseph's Cathedral in Hartford, Conn.
   During his visit to Mission Dolores, John Paul blessed 62 AIDS
patients.
   One of them, 4-year-old Brendan O'Rourke, suddenly reached out
and touched the pontiff's ear. The startled but pleased pope hugged
the boy, who's believed to have contracted AIDS through a blood
transfusion.
   Riley said the boy is doing well. He said he celebrated Mass at
the boy's home recently when Brendan blurted out: ``I hugged the
pope! I hugged the pope!''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
