<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush-Kean     03-22 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Kean,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Jersey Governor Endorses Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PLAINSBORO, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After picking up Gov. Thomas H. Kean's
backing, Vice President George Bush said he'll carry two messages
stressed by Kean _ the importance of improving education and the
need for Republicans to reach out to voters traditionally aligned
with Democrats.
   ``Tom Kean has done a remarkable job in New Jersey. And it is
reaching out to our fellow Republicans, but it is also going after
those in the Democratic column,'' Bush said.
   ``He has demonstrated that the open-door policy works. His
success is an inspiration of what we can accomplish nationally.''
   Bush made the remarks Monday at a joint appearance in which Kean
and the state's county Republican chairmen abandoned their
neutrality in the presidential race and threw their support to Bush.
   Kean decided to support Bush after the vice president won the
Illinois primary last week.
   New Jersey's county Republican chairmen, who had been waiting
for Kean to act, followed the governor's lead and voted to endorse
Bush at a breakfast meeting Monday morning.
   ``George Bush is our leader, and with the Republican vision of a
stronger America, that offers oppportunity to all regardless of
color or creed, we can not only retain the presidency, but send
(House Speaker) Jim Wright to the back benches for the rest of this
century,'' said Kean.
   After Monday's announcement, Kean left with Bush to help the
vice president campaign in Connecticut, which holds its primary
next Tuesday.
   One GOP county chairman said the endorsements almost assure Bush
will win New Jersey's 64 Republican delegates. The state's primary
is June 7.
   Bush then said he would ``shamelessly steal'' the governor's
message that Republicans must reach out to blacks, unions and
others traditionally aligned with the Democratic Party.
   Kean, who picked up minority and union support in winning
re-election by a landslide in 1985 has been touted as a possible
vice presidential candidate.
</TEXT>
