<1ST_LINE>r w WashingtonInBrief 520   03-22 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>Washington In Brief, 520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North on Leave Pending May 1 Retirement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lt. Col. Oliver North, the fired national
security aide now facing criminal charges from the Iran-Contra
affair, has gone on leave in preparation for retirement from the
Marine Corps in six weeks.
   ``Lt. Col. North began his terminal leave today,'' said Lt. Col.
John Shotwell, a Marine Corps spokesman. ``He had sufficient leave
on the books to cover the period from now until his retirement on
May 1,'' added Shotwell, in Monday's announcement.
   North had been working in a staff position at Marine Corps
headquarters here since President Reagan dismissed him from the
White House staff in November 1986. He announced last Friday _ two
days after his indictment by a federal grand jury _ that he had
decided to leave the corps.
   North, former national security adviser John M. Poindexter and
two others were indicted by a federal grand jury March 16 on
charges they conspired to divert profits from arms sales to Iran to
the Nicaraguan Contra rebels.
   By specifying a May 1 retirement date, the date on which he will
have completed 20 years on active duty, North will be eligible to
retire with a military pension equal to half his monthly base pay
of $3,693.60.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Senate Urges Talks With USSR To Curb `Bandit' Fishing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate is urging the Reagan administration
to open negotiations with the Soviet Union aimed at curbing
uncontrolled ``bandit'' fishing from international waters in the
Bering Sea.
   A 79-0 vote on Monday approved a non-binding,
sense-of-the-Senate resolution which declares that foreign fishing
fleets are using a zone located between the 200-mile fishing limits
established by the United States and the Soviet Union as ``a
staging ground for raids'' into one of the richest fishing grounds
in the world.
   According to the resolution, immediate action to protect Bering
Sea fishery resources is needed because of lack of cooperation by
other high-seas fishing nations under existing agreements.
   The resolution calls for the convening of U.S.-Soviet
negotiations to impose a moratorium on all fishing in the zone, a
ban which would stay in effect until an international fishery
management agreement is negotiated.
   Because of its location, completely surrounded by U.S. and
Soviet territorial waters, the 4,500 square mile area is known
variously as ``the hole in the doughnut'' or ``the doughnut.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Group Demonstrates Against Use Of Animals In Research</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About a dozen people were arrested when they
attempted to block the entrance to the headquarters of the
Department of Health and Human Services in a demonstration against
the use of animals in medical research.
   About 50 people had gathered outside the building on Monday for
the hour-long peaceful protest which featured speeches by several
participants.
   The demonstration was organized by a California-based group,
``In Defense of Animals.''
