<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole Again Challenges Bush To Debate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMERY, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Bob Dole, struggling on against Vice
President George Bush, said he would support whoever turns out to
be the Republican nominee. But he says it could still be him.
   ``There are a lot of people who say the Republican race is over,
we already got our nominee and let's get ready for the
convention,'' he said Monday as he campaigned here. ``And I'll say
this, when we get the nominee, I'll be working for the nominee _
but it's only the second day of spring.''
   Dole renewed his debate challenge to Bush and the acting mayor
of this farming community, Vern Peterson quickly volunteered to
have Amery serve as site for a debate. Bush has declined recent
invitations to debate with Dole, saying they have had enough
debates already.
   Dole searched for support from Democrats as well as Republicans
in Wisconsin's open primary, in which voters are not required to
state party preference.
   ``I want a big, big surprise to happen on April 5. And I think
it can happen in the state of Wisconsin,'' Dole said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dole, Robertson Camps Plan Appeal of Primary Court Challenge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge says he won't upset New York
election law to place delegate slates supporting Pat Robertson or
Sen. Bob Dole on all ballots in next month's state Republican
primary.
   But supporters of the two GOP presidential hopefuls said they
would appeal Monday's ruling by U.S. District Judge Leonard B. Sand
before the April 19 primary.
   The Robertson and Dole supporters are challenging state law
which they claim made it unfairly difficult to get delegate slates
favoring their candidates on the ballot in New York.
   Candidates were required to get the signatures of 1,250
registered Republicans or 5 percent _ whichever was less _ in each
of the state's 34 congressional districts in order to get their
slates on the ballot. The signatures had to be obtained between
Jan. 5 and Feb. 11.
   But only Vice President George Bush's campaign was able to get
the necessary signatures in a majority of the 34 districts.
   ``We feel the judge has made several errors in his ruling. We
will be appealing,'' said Henry Hews of Americans for Robertson.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Poll: Bush Has Commanding New York Lead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush is the
overwhelming favorite going into New York's April 19 primary among
likely Republican voters questioned for a recent statewide poll.
   The Marist College Institute for Public Opinion also reported in
its study released Monday that in theoretical matchups, pitting
Bush against the major Democratic candidates, the vice president is
the choice of New Yorkers except when it comes to Massachusetts
Gov. Michael Dukakis. In that possible contest, Dukakis appeared to
have a slight edge over Bush in New York.
   Of the 292 likely Republican primary voters sampled, 68 percent
said they favored Bush while 22 percent opted for Kansas Sen. Bob
Dole and 3 percent went for Pat Robertson. Less than 1 percent
picked another candidate and 6 percent said they were undecided.
   ``Bush's support is solid across the board, outpolling his
rivals among upstate, New York City and suburban Republicans,''
noted Marist pollster Lee Miringoff.
   The margin of error for the Republican portion of the poll is
plus or minus 6 percent. The poll was based on interviews conducted
for the first four days of last week.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>California Draft Cuomo Campaign Faces Still Another Legal Hurdle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group attempting to place Mario
Cuomo's name on California's presidential primary ballot despite
the New York governor's objections faces still another legal
obstacle.
   Gerald Hill, one of two coordinators of the Draft Cuomo
committee, said Monday that while his group believes it has more
than the 22,500 signatures required statewide on its petitions, it
hasn't met the requirement of filing a minimum of 500 verified
signatures from each of California's 45 congressional districts.
   ``We have to admit we don't have all 45. There are four or five
districts where we didn't make the 500, no question of it,'' Hill
said in a telephone interview.
   ``That's another hurdle, no question of it. But matters like
this have come up numerous times in numerous states, and courts
have (overturned) overly stringent requirements ... if it's too
burdensome.
   Under the law the group is using in its attempt to place Cuomo's
name on California's ballot, the group also must have the consent
of the candidate, something Hill concedes Cuomo has not given.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ohio Primary Too Late, Professor Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ohio's urban problems and those of some
other northeast states, are being left behind in the presidential
primary shuffle because their primaries are held too late, an
elections researcher said.
   Linda L.M. Bennett, a political science professor at Wittenberg
University, also said Ohio should consider holding caucuses,
instead of a popular vote.
   Caucuses allow elected officials and party leaders more say, and
``they're better informed on the issues and they know what it takes
to get elected,'' she said.
   Ohio last year considered moving the May 3 primary to mid-March,
but lawmakers dropped the idea when Gov. Richard Celeste failed to
include it in his budget.
   Ms. Bennett doesn't expect Ohio's Democratic and Republican
leaders to institute major reforms, partly because they like the
long primary season for state and local candidates. She said they
more easily can influence those primaries.
</TEXT>
