<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--FireplaceBan     03-22 0143</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Fireplace Ban,0146</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Committee Recommends Wood-burning Fireplace Ban</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A quasi-governmental panel has recommended that
wood-burning fireplaces be banned by 1994 to cut air pollution, but
the proposal was attacked by home builders.
   ``You can ban woodburning, but you can't ban bricks and
mortar,'' said Arlene Quenan of the Colorado Association of Home
Builders. ``You're going to have real trouble when people say, `I
want a fireplace in my new home.'''
   In its proposal Monday, the Metropolitan Air Quality Council
subcommittee said that within five years all newly installed
fireplaces should be fueled by natural gas and all existing
wood-burning fireplaces be put out of service or converted to gas.
   The council will consider the ban on April 4.
   Colorado last year became the first state to require new
wood-burning stoves to meet air-quality standards for carbon
monoxide and particulates.
</TEXT>
