<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SAfrica-Newspaper     03-22 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Newspaper,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Closes Anti-Apartheid Newspaper</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today shut down
a militant anti-apartheid newspaper for 12 weeks, contending the
church-backed New Nation threatened public safety.
   A special decree issued by Home Affairs Minister Stoffel Botha
said further issues of the black-oriented weekly newspaper are
``totally prohibited'' through June 10.
   He acted a day after the newspaper, published by the Southern
African Catholic Bishops Conference, lost a court appeal seeking to
forestall government action while it challenged state-of-emergency
censorship regulations.
   Technically, the New Nation could resume publication after three
months, but Botha could close it again if its contents dissatisfied
him. The paper's senior staff has not announced whether operations
will be resumed after the suspension.
   With a circulation of 50,000 to 60,000, the 2-year-old newspaper
is the largest in South Africa to devote virtually its entire
content, including sports and entertainment sections, to
politically-related developments.
   The newspaper had a full-time staff of 22 and employed 32
correspondents who covered anti-apartheid activity in the rural
areas where the majority of blacks live. Several employees already
had resigned in anticipation of closure by Botha, who disclosed his
intentions in January.
   The newspaper's editor, Zwelakhe Sisulu, has been detained
without charge for 16 months. He joined the New Nation after a year
as a Niemann fellow at Harvard University.
   Authorities have banned four of the paper's editions and seized
two. Police have raided the paper's offices, and it was the first
of six publications warned by Botha that they could be closed for
three-month periods or censored for publishing material he found
objectionable.
   State-of-emergency regulations give Botha nearly unlimited
powers to deal with newspapers he feels might contribute to unrest.
He does not have to give reasons for his actions.
   The New Nation lost an initial court challenge of the
regulations and intends to pursue its case in an appellate court.
But on Monday, a Supreme Court rejected the newspaper's bid to
prevent closure during the appeal process.
   The New Nation's acting editor, Gabu Tugwana, said closure of
his paper would be ``an action against the whole media.''
   ``There are many more axes hanging in the air that will fall on
many others,'' he said, referring to warnings issued by Botha to
other publications.
   In a warning letter to the New Nation, Botha cited several items
which he said threatened public safety, promoted revolution,
enhanced the image of outlawed organizations or fomented hostility
toward the security forces.
   The items he listed included:
   _A picture of Oliver Tambo, president of the outlawed African
National Congress, opening a new office in Nairobi, Kenya.
   _A story about an arson attack on the offices of the United
Democratic Front, the nation's largest anti-apartheid coalition.
   _A picture of relatives of condemned blacks at a news conference
in which they appealed for clemency for 32 men and women sentenced
to hang.
   _An advertisement quoting a Psalm and urging the government to
abolish torture.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
