<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Poland-Detentions     03-22 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland-Detentions,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Detain Anti-Government Protesters Carrying Jaruzelski
Effigies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police detained scores of people in
anti-government protests in two cities that featured dolls with
dark glasses resembling those worn by Polish leader Gen. Wojciech
Jaruzelski, opposition spokesmen said.
   Opposition activists in the southwest city of Wroclaw said
hundreds of people assembled on a main street Monday demanding
freedom for Waldemar Fydrych, head of the satirical street theater
group, Orange Alternative.
   Police in the port city of Gdansk on Sunday detained 18 members
of a banned peace group who planned to throw an effigy with dark
spectacles into the Baltic Sea, an opposition activist said.
   Participants on Monday chanted ``Spring in, Fydrych out!'' while
carrying three ``Marzanna'' dolls with dark glasses, activists said.
   The dolls were related to the Polish folk custom of drowning
``Marzanna,'' a rag-and-stick figure representing winter, on the
first day of spring.
   Fydrych is serving a two-month jail sentence for organizing
similar demonstrations in the past.
   The demonstration on Monday drew 3,000 spectators, said activist
Barbara Labuda. Police at first checked IDs, but then began hauling
the protesters away, she said.
   Mrs. Labuda and an Orange Alternative member, Krzysztof Albin,
said police later used tear gas and struck people with truncheons.
Another activist, Jozef Pinior, said he could not confirm the
report.
   Pinior said 150 people were detained, most briefly. Mrs. Labuda
and Albin said the number was higher.
   A police duty officer in Wroclaw said he knew nothing about any
demonstrations.
   Janina Wehrstein, a spokeswoman for the Freedom and Peace group
in Gdansk, said the 18 people detained in Wroclaw on Sunday planned
to toss a dark-spectacled doll from a pier into the Baltic on
Monday.
   Five of the 18 were released after a few hours, but the others
were held overnight at a police station, she said.
   Freedom and Peace opposes Poland's universal military draft and
demands alternative civilian service for conscientious objectors.
</TEXT>
