<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 0618EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-East-Appeal     03-22 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-East-Appeal,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>East Dissidents Ask Right To Object To Military Service</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unprecedented number of dissidents and
intellectuals from six East European nations have signed an appeal
for recognition of the right to object to military service.
   The appeal, published Monday in Vienna, was signed by 77
Soviets, including Andrei Sakharov, nuclear physicist and 1975
Nobel Peace laureate.
   The signatories from Hungary, Czechoslovakia, the Soviet Union,
East Germany, Poland and Yugoslavia called for recognition ``of
citizens' right to conscientious objection and alternative
service.''
   The appeal was addressed to the 35-nation Conference on Security
and Cooperation in Europe, which has been meeting in Vienna since
November 1986 to review compliance with the 1975 Helsinki Accords
on military security, economic coopertion and humanitarian issues.
   The appeal asked the delegations to work toward an agreement on
the right not to serve in the military.
   Hungarian dissident writer Miklos Haraszti, who signed the
appeal and helped initiate it, told a news conference Monday that
conscientious objection was one of the main reasons for political
imprisonment in Eastern Europe.
   ``Hundreds of our East European compatriots are sent to prison
because of their non-violent conscientious stands,'' the appeal
said. ``These young men would like to serve the community by caring
for the old and sick instead of performing military service.''
   Haraszti said no country in the Warsaw Pact allows its citizens
the right to object to military service, while NATO countries do.
   ``Eastern Europe punishes people for not wanting to look at
other countries as enemies,'' he said.
   Haraszti said 438 people and groups have signed the appeal so
far.
   The London-based East European Cultural Foundation, which helped
coordinate collecting signatures, said in a news release it was the
first time a large number of Soviet citizens joined a joint East
bloc initiative.
   Haraszti said the appeal, the fourth such joint effort of East
European dissidents, carried the largest number of signatures so
far.
   Peter Uhl, a member of the Czechoslovak human rights group
Charter 77, was invited to come to Vienna for presentation of the
appeal.
   However, in a letter read in part at the news conference and
then distributed, Uhl complained that ``no Czechoslovak citizens,
including those who have passports, could go to Vienna in response
to your invitation.''
   His letter said, ``Internationalization of our demands ... is
also very important because it provides a comparison between the
legal and factual state of affairs prevailing in the individual
East European countries.''
   Dissidents in East bloc countries estimated the total number of
people in prison for objecting to military service at about 300 to
400.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
