<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LeukemiaGirl     03-22 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Leukemia Girl,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Girl Returning Home, Apparently Free Of Cancer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A girl who became the first cancer patient to
receive a bone-marrow transplant through a computerized national
registry apparently is free of leukemia, hospital officials say.
   Brooke Ward, 7, will return home Saturday to Raleigh, N.C.
Recent tests have found no cancer and, at 100 days, her operation
at Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Institute is considered a
success.
   One thing Brooke apparently won't miss is the attention that
accompanied publicity for the National Bone Marrow Donor Registry,
based in Minneapolis-St. Paul.
   ``Mommy,'' Brooke complained, holding out her arms to mother
Margurite Ward as a reporter and photographer approached. ``Not
this again.''
   ``The reason we agreed to the media coverage is that we wanted
people to know about the registry,'' Mrs. Ward said. ``We wanted
people to know a bone marrow transplant could be done with a
non-related donor.''
   The registry located Diane Walters, 49, of Milwaukee, whose
tissue type matched Brooke's. The transplant was performed Dec. 16.
   ``She's doing fine,'' Mrs. Ward said. ``I just feel Brooke is
going to make it. She's already beaten the odds.''
   Another piece of the story is fund-raising _ a tough job without
news coverage.
   Bone-marrow transplants like Brooke's cost an average of
$100,000, and fund-raising for her treatment began even before the
registry match.
   The family is covered by private insurance for 80 percent of the
transplant costs. Fund-raising was still necessary to cover the
expenses of moving to Seattle, loss of income or any further
medical costs.
   ``Without the media coverage it would have been real hard to
raise the money,'' Mrs. Ward said.
   ``There are a lot of people who can't get a transplant because
they can't get funds,'' said Susan Edmonds, a spokeswoman for Fred
Hutchinson. The non-profit cancer center is prohibited from doing
fund-raising for individuals.
</TEXT>
