<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Zimbabwe-Unesco     03-22 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Zimbabwe-Unesco,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNESCO Adopts Austerity Plan In Bid To Lure U.S., U.K. Back</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Nations Educational,
Scientific and Cultural Organization has adopted an austerity
program in a bid to lure the United States and Britain into
rejoining, the general-secretary said.
   The general-secretary, Frederico Mayor, announced the plan
Monday after arriving in Harare on a four-day visit to Zimbabwe.
Mayor, 52, a former Spanish Minister of Education, became UNESCO
chief in November.
   The United States and Britain, once two of the largest
contributors to UNESCO's budget, quit the organization in 1984 and
1985 to protest the organization's alleged anti-Western bias and
squandering of resources.
   Addressing a news conference in Harare, Mayor said the austerity
plan include a 50 percent cut in UNESCO documentation. The number
of meetings was also cut by 25 percent, and other steps were taken
to increase efficiency and create ``less ambiguity'' in the work of
the Paris-based body.
   He did not give further details of the plan, but said he had
written to the United States, Britain and Singapore, which also
quit the organization, asking them to reconsider their membership.
   Mayor will meet with President Robert Mugabe and government
ministers.
</TEXT>
