<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GenerationPoll     03-22 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Generation Poll,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rolling Stone Polls Young Americans on Lives, Country, Leaders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When 18- to 44-year-old Americans were asked
which leaders they admired most in the past 20 years, they picked
two men who were assassinated 20 years ago _ Martin Luther King Jr.
and Robert F. Kennedy.
   Thirty-eight percent of those responding to the poll conducted
for Rolling Stone magazine said they admired King the most, citing
his stand on civil rights.
   The respondents who chose King and the 25 percent who chose
second-place Robert F. Kennedy said they were eloquent leaders who
stood for peace, justice, tolerance and equality.
   The magazine noted that both politicians were assassinated
before realizing their dreams and that their ``blighted legacy'' is
a theme that surfaces throughout the survey.
   President Reagan was also chosen as most admired by 25 percent
of those surveyed, but he also had a high negative rating _ 10
percent picked him as the public figure they respected the least.
   Asked under what circumstances they would enlist for military
service, 60 percent of all respondents and 73 percent of men said
they would enlist if war broke out on the North American continent.
   Only 27 percent said they would enlist if our close European
allies were attacked. Twenty-five percent of all respondents and 15
percent of the men said they would not join the military under any
circumstances.
   Twelve percent said politics was very important in their lives,
41 percent said somewhat important, 30 percent not very important,
16 percent not at all important and one percent were not sure.
   The survey found that 48 percent of respondents believe families
need two incomes in order to survive.
   Results from the poll, conducted last September by Peter D. Hart
Research Associates, appear in the April 7 issue of the magazine
which went on sale today.
   The poll is based on interviews with 816 respondents at their
homes, the magazine said. The margin of error survey is plus or
minus four percent for questions involving all respondents, and
slightly higher for subgroups.
</TEXT>
