<2ND_LINE>PM-Belgium-Hotel Fire,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blaze Kills Four Guests, Injures Seven Others</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pre-dawn fire that apparently started
when a cigarette ignited a mattress swept through part of a
suburban hotel today, killing four guests and injuring seven
others, police said.
   A 7-year-old child and a handicapped man were among the dead at
the four-story Hotel Tivoli in the Brussels suburb of Laken. Of the
seven people injured, two were in serious condition, said a police
official who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The official said the identities of the victims were not yet
known but said three of the victims were Africans.
   Police said the fire was most probably caused when someone's
cigarette ignited a mattress on the second floor.
   A police patrol noticed the fire minutes after it started at
3:30 a.m. and immediately warned emergency services. Police and
neighbors meanwhile rescued people while awaiting the firefighters,
the official said.
   One guest was hospitalized with injuries after jumping from the
second floor. Another guest was found unconscious in his room and
also was hospitalized.
   The fire swept through half of the fully-booked hotel, causing
about $57,000 in damage, police said.
