<HEAD>Sixth-Grader Confesses To Killing Friend, Receives Probation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sixth-grader has admitted
shooting a friend to death and been sentenced to six years of
probation for his manslaughter plea.
   Frank Melo Jr., 13, was indicted on second-degree murder charges
by a Broward County grand jury for the Dec. 26, 1986, shooting of
Steven Mumford of Hollywood.
   Prosecutors offered the youth a plea bargain that was approved
Monday by Broward Circuit Judge M. Daniel Futch, who withheld
adjudication, a formal finding of guilt. If the boy successfully
completes probation, his record will show no conviction.
   Futch warned the teary eyed boy that consequences would be
severe if he violated probation terms, which include receiving
psychological counseling and not using a firearm without court
approval.
   ``If you don't believe that, you ask anybody,'' said Futch,
nicknamed ``Maximum Dan'' because of the stiff sentences he hands
out. ``I'll put you in jail.''
   The shooting occurred when the Mumfords were visiting Melo's
family. The boy said the shooting was an accident, but Stanley
Mumford, the dead boy's father, contended it was not.
   Prosecutor Kelly Hancock said Steven Mumford, 12, had angered
Melo shortly before the shooting.
   Mumford and wife Beverly were ``not that happy with the
disposition,'' Kelly said after the hearing here.
