<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0442 03-22 0750</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0442,0768</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinians and Israelis Call for Tougher Measures Against Each
Other</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 17 grafs to UPDATE with two more Arab deaths.
PICKS up 6th graf, `Also Monday ...' EDITS to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops shot and killed a Palestinian
man in the occupied West Bank during a clash with protesters
hurling rocks, metal bars and bottles, an army spokeswoman said
today.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip, the body of another Palestinian was
found in an orchard in the village of Beit Hanoun, Israel radio
said.
   The army denied involvement in the Gaza death, but a resident of
the village said the man's family believed he had been beaten by
soldiers. His skull was crushed.
   In the West Bank, the army spokeswoman said an Arab's body was
found this morning after a Monday night clash in Tubas, a village
50 miles north of Jerusalem.
   The Arab-owned Palestine Press Service identified the man as
26-year-old Hikmet Drajmeh. The agency said troops shot and wounded
two more protesters, one of them seriously, but the army denied the
report.
   The spokeswoman, who could not be identified under army
regulations, said the clash erupted when hundreds of Palestinians
attacked an army patrol with rocks, metal bars and bottles.
   ``The soldiers shot to extricate themselves from a
life-threatening situation,'' she said.
   The killing brought the Palestinian death toll to 107 in almost
four months of unrest, according to unofficial U.N. figures. One
Israeli soldier has been killed by Arab gunfire.
   In the Gaza Strip, a military spokesman said no troops had been
in Beit Hanoun Monday and so the army could not have been involved.
A resident said the victim's family suspected the army was
responsible because the body was found in an isolated area off
limits to villagers.
   A third Palestinian died today when he was shot from a passing
car in the southern Gaza Strip by assailants assumed to be Arabs,
Israel army radio said. An army spokesman said the motive was
apparently criminal.
   Both Gaza killings were turned over to the police, the army
said. But Gaza police officials were quoted by Israel radio as
saying they were unable to investigate many crimes due to the mass
resignations last week of 380 Arab officers.
   The officers resigned along with most of their Arab colleagues
in the West Bank in accordance with orders issued by underground
leaders of what Palestinians call ``the uprising.''
   In other casualties today, officials at the Ahli Arab hospital
in Gaza City said two men were admitted with injuries inflicted by
Israeli troops.
   In other West Bank unrest, an Israeli driver fired shots near
the Balata refugee camp near Nablus after his car was stoned,
Israel radio reported. There were no injuries.
   In the West Bank, members of two Arab councils resigned today a
day after an underground leaflet called for Israeli-appointed
municipal officials to leave their jobs.
   Palestinian leaders also called for increased attacks with
stones, firebombs and iron bars on Israeli security forces and
Jewish settlers.
   The call came as several center-left Israeli politicians and
writers joined right-wing leaders in demanding tougher measures to
quell the violence in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Also Monday, the army issued a new regulation that will allow
the detention of any security prisoner for up to six months with
less judicial review. The previous edict required a military judge
to review each case within 96 hours.
   Officials said the new regulation would ease the overload on the
military court system that has handled nearly 3,000 cases since the
violent demonstrations began in the occupied lands on Dec. 8.
   And Israeli troops on Monday expanded their search for weapons
in the occupied lands following the fatal shooting Sunday of
Israeli Sgt. Moshe Katz in Bethlehem.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin lifted restrictions barring
soldiers from shooting at rioters throwing firebombs and for the
first time the army destroyed the homes of three Arabs suspected of
throwing such missiles.
   The increasing violence in the occupied lands drew demands for
action from Israelis usually opposed to the measures of the
rightist Likud coalition led by Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir.
   Amnon Lynn, a legislator from the opposition Labor Party, told
Itim on Monday: ``The political echelon must understand we cannot
continue with the policy of restraint. There is a time to hold back
and a time to attack. The time has come for Israel to respond with
force.''
</TEXT>
