<HEAD>Sidney Mittler, Cancer Researcher, Dies of Cancer At Age 70</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DE KALB, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sidney Mittler, a biologist who studied
potential cancer-causing substances, has died of cancer here.
   Mittler, 70, died Sunday shortly after he was admitted to De
Kalb's Kishwaukee Community Hospital, said a spokeswoman at
Northern Illinois University, where he had been a faculty member
since 1960.
   The scientist, who held a doctorate in biology from the
University of Michigan, wrote more than 100 articles and received
more than $3.5 million in research grants to study possible links
between cancer and things such as radio waves, caffeine,
saccharine, hair dyes, food preservatives and various pollutants.
   Mittler is survived by three daughters, his second wife, Judith,
and two step-sons. His first wife is deceased.
