<1ST_LINE>r i PM-IslamicConference     03-22 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Islamic Conference,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Condemned, Iraq Claims Iran Helping Jewish Immigration To
Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN MARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign ministers from Moslem countries
today condemned Israel's ``oppressive measures'' against rioters in
the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The ministers of the 46-member Organization of Islamic
Conference said in a statement that ``all Moslems in the world are
proud of this uprising.''
   They called for political and financial aid for the rebellion. A
Palestine Liberation Organization official, speaking just before a
plenary meeting at which the foreign ministers approved the
statement, hailed the support they were giving to the ``uprising.''
   In another development, Iraqi Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz in a
closed committee session claimed that Iran was facilitating the
emigration of Iranian Jews to Israel. Iran has denied the charge.
   Jordanian Foreign Minister Taher Masri said Iran and Iraq were
unlikely to negotiate on peace during the Amman meeting, in part
because of the low-ranking level of the Iranian delegation.
   The ministers in their statement said the conference ``denounces
the oppressive and criminal measures by the (Israeli) authorities
against our brothers, the people in the occupied territories.''
   ``Members of the organization are concerned to support
Palestinians financially, politically and morally and also to back
their sole legitimate representative, the PLO,'' the statement said.
   It did not elaborate on the form this aid would take.
   Farouk Kaddoumi, head of PLO's political department, the
equivalent of the organization's foreign ministry, said the
ministers' backing was especially valuable ``for the people inside
the territories.''
   He spoke the day after King Hussein, in an opening address at
the conference, called for the Moslem world to support the
``uprising.''
   More than 100 Palestinians have died in the violent protests in
the territories Israel occupied in the 1967 Middle East War. Israel
seized the West Bank from Jordan and the Gaza Strip from Egypt.
   Kaddoumi, who is heading the PLO's delegation at the Islamic
meeting, condemned U.S. moves to close the guerrilla group's office
in New York, accredited to the United Nations.
   ``We will keep the office open until American police come and
seal it off,'' he said. ``Then we will go to the United Nations
(enclave) and live there.''
   Aziz, reading in a closed session a statement that was made
available to The Associated Press by a source close to the
conference, said the alleged help given to Iranian Jews for
emigration to Israel was ``a violation of the rules of the''
organization.
   He did not elaborate, but asked the organization to study this
issue from all sides.
   ``How come Iran, which claims to support the Palestinian issue
and the uprising, is helping Jews to migrate to Israel.''
   He provided no figures on the migration. Iran has already denied
the charge.
</TEXT>
