<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Hawaii-Japanese     03-22 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hawaii-Japanese,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honolulu's Mayor Moves To Crack Down On Japanese Investment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Frank Fasi has proposed legislation to
stop foreign investors from purchasing some kinds of property in
Hawaii, saying the measure would put an end to skyrocketing housing
and real estate costs.
   The mayor on Monday sent a bill to the state Legislature that
would ban the sale of residential, agricultural or preservation
land to non-Americans. The bill does not cover commercial, resort
and industrial properties.
   The mayor's move comes as the state attempts to deal with a
recent wave of foreign investment that has caused property values
to jump in some areas. The investment has been spurred by the fall
of the dollar's value against the Japanese yen.
   ``What has triggered my action is the Japanese buyer with his
cheap dollars,'' Fasi told the Professional Women's Network on
Monday. ``They have been buying homes in several areas of Oahu,
forcing values to unprecedented levels.''
   Fasi said he does not consider his move protectionist.
   ``I believe in free and open trade between most countries,''
Fasi said. ``But I also believe in fairness, and what I see
happening here is not fair to Americans.''
   A spokesman for state Senate President Richard Wong said Fasi's
bill was under review and may be included in the legislative agenda.
   The City Council is considering a number of bills to curb
Japanese investment and ease the property tax burden on Oahu
homeowners.
</TEXT>
