<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SAfrica-Unrest     03-22 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Unrest,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Report Widespread Unrest During Protest Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two blacks were killed, seven
injured and 39 arrested during a nationwide protest strike that
brought the most extensive violence this year, police reported
today.
   Dozens of buses, delivery vans and private cars were stoned or
firebombed on Monday, the 28th anniversary of the Sharpeville
massacre, and in many cases security forces used tear gas, rubber
bullets, birdshot and dogs to disperse rioters, police headquarters
said.
   Police said the two deaths and five of the injuries resulted
from attacks by blacks on blacks. Two blacks were injured by police.
   Several of those arrested were trying to prevent children from
going to school and workers from going to work, police said.
   The protest strike was organized by anti-apartheid activists in
defiance of emergency regulations barring calls for such actions.
Hundreds of thousands of black workers and students stayed away
from jobs and classes, both to mark the anniversary of the 1960
police shootings of 69 blacks in Sharpeville and to protest the
recent bannings of black opposition groups.
   The Department of Education and Training said class boycotts
were reported at 694 of the black schools under its control, 9
percent of the total.
   The Star of Johannesburg, the country's largest daily newspaper,
said protest strikes would continue ``as long as grievances are not
directly addressed.''
   ``Instead of tension being relieved through the extension of
rights and the removal of restrictions, each new round of protests
is met with further clamps which inevitably lead to fresh
protests.''
   Five students from Johannesburg's University of the
Witwatersrand went to local police headquarters today with a bunch
of roses for Rosemary Hunter, the president of the student council
who was detained under state-of-emergency regulations Monday.
   The students said a police lieutenant refused to accept the
bouquet and told them: ``This is a police station, not a hospital.''
   Ms. Hunter, a law student, was taken from her parents' home at
dawn Monday.
   Police have not commented on the detention.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
