<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Patrick Steptoe</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Patrick Steptoe, the gynecologist who
pioneered the test- tube baby technique that made parenthood
possible for thousands of otherwise infertile couples, died Monday
at age 74.
   Steptoe, born June 9, 1913, had been suffering from cancer, his
family said in announcing his death.
   He and his partner, Dr. Robert Edwards, were responsible for the
world's first test-tube baby, Louise Joy Brown, born at Oldham in
northern England on July 25, 1978. The announcement of the birth of
the healthy baby from an embryo fertilized outside her mother's
womb caused shock waves. The technique, known as in vitro
fertilization, has since been used in clinics around the world.
   In the early years of their research in the late 1960s and early
1970s, Steptoe and Edwards were ostracized by much of the medical
establishment. Last year, they were made Commanders of the British
Empire, and Steptoe was made a Fellow of the Royal Society, one of
Britain's highest academic honors.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Gil Evans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gil Evans, a composer, pianist and band leader
considered one of the greatest orchestrators in jazz, died Sunday
in Mexico. He was 75.
   Evans first professional band was taken over by Skinnay Ennis,
but Evans stayed on as arranger. He made his mark in the 1950s and
1960s with innovative arrangements for trumpeter Miles Davis,
particularly three recordings that showcased Davis' cool style:
``Miles Ahead,'' ``Porgy and Bess'' and ``Sketches of Spain.''
   His first recording with his own band, ``The Arranger's Touch,''
used French horn, muted trumpet and bassoon in arrangements marked
by originality. Evans scored the film ``Absolute Beginners'' at age
74.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Edd Roush</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRADENTON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edd Roush, a two-time National League
batting champ for the Cincinnati Reds and a member of the Hall of
Fame, died after suffering an apparent heart attack at a ballpark
Monday. He was 94.
   Roush, who had been the oldest living member of the Hall of
Fame, was inducted into the shrine in 1962 with Jackie Robinson,
Bob Feller and the late Bill McKechnie.
   During his 18-year career, Roush had a .325 lifetime batting
average. In 1929, he batted .324 for the New York Giants, but held
out the entire 1930 season over a contract dispute. He played his
final season for the Reds in 1931 and batted .271.
   Roush, a winter resident of Bradenton for 35 years who also
lived in his hometown of Oakland City, Ind., was at the ball park
for a spring training game between the Pittsburgh Pirates and the
Texas Rangers when he died.
   He began his major league career in the American League with
Chicago in 1913.
   In 1917, in his first full season with the Reds, the left-hander
led the National League with a .341 batting average. He won his
second batting title in 1919, hitting .321 for the Reds.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Sidney Mittler</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DE KALB, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sidney Mittler, a biologist known for his
work investigating potential cancer-causing substances in food,
died Sunday of cancer at age 70.
   Mittler held bachelor's and master's degrees from Wayne State
University in Detroit, where he was born, and a doctorate in
biology from the University of Michigan. He wrote more than 100
articles that were published in scientific journals and received
more than $3.5 million in research grants.
   Many of the grants paid for Mittler's studies on possible links
between cancer and such common substances as radio waves, caffeine,
certain hot dog preservatives, saccharine, hair dyes and various
pollutants.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Sam W. Reynolds</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sam W. Reynolds, a businessman who was
appointed a U.S. senator and served for seven months, died Sunday
of pneumonia. He was 97.
   Reynolds owned and operated Reynolds-Updike Coal Co. for 76
years until retiring in 1984. He also was a partner in Updike
Lumber and Coal.
   Gov. Bob Crosby appointed Reynolds, a Republican, to the Senate
in 1954 after the death of Sen. Hugh Butler. Reynolds did not seek
election to a full term.
   Reynolds was a city councilman in 1956 and 1957 and had been
city civil defense coordinator. He won the Nebraska amateur golf
championship seven times.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>George Lehr</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Missouri State Auditor George Lehr,
credited for helping to clean up the reputedly mob-dominated
Teamsters Union Central States pension fund, died Monday at age 51.
   Lehr, executive director of the fund for the past 6{ years, had
suffered inoperable brain tumors for more than a year.
   Lehr, a Democrat, defeated Republican John Ashcroft, now
Missouri's governor, for state auditor in 1974. Lehr was mentioned
as a candidate for the Democratic nomination for governor in 1976,
but made the surprise announcement that he was resigning as auditor
and leaving politics.
   He became president of the Empire Bank and Trust Co. in Kansas
City and later became chairman and chief executive officer of
Traders Bank there.
   Lehr accepted the pension fund job in 1981 and worked with the
U.S. Labor Department to clean it up. The fund allegedly had been
under mob control. Two years ago, the General Accounting Office
said the fund was being run properly for the first time in its 30
years.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Hester R. McCullough</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRYN MAWR, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hester R. McCullough, once a heroine of
the political right for her 1940s stand against entertainers
associated with communist causes, died Sunday at age 71.
   In the late 1940s, Mrs. McCullough, then living in Greenwich,
Conn., returned a $6 subscription ticket to a performance by dancer
Paul Draper and harmonica player Larry Adler, whom she accused of
being members of communist-front organizations.
   Draper and Adler sued Mrs. McCullough for libel, but decided not
to pursue the case when it ended in a hung jury in 1950. By then,
it had become a cause celebre taken up by conservative columnists
such as Westbrook Pegler.
</TEXT>
