<2ND_LINE>PM-Chemical Fire,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retransmitting a0580 to fix cycle designator</HEAD>
<HEAD>Chemical Company Recalls Gas Cylinders Nationwide In Wake of Blast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY HEIGHTS, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The company that distributed a
cylinder of gas that exploded and killed three at a research
laboratory here last week began recalling hundreds of similar
cylinders nationwide, state officials said.
   Liquid Carbonics Industries Inc., a Chicago-based gas
distributor, is recalling cylinders containing the gas silane
following the blast at the Gollob Analytical Services Plant here
Thursday, said Richard Fulton, a spokesman for the state Department
of Environmental Protection.
   A spokeswoman for the company in Chicago said it was
investigating the origin of the cylinder that exploded but declined
to confirm the recall or comment further.
   The explosion was triggered by a silane cylinder that was
contaminated with nitrous oxide, a highly unstable mixture, Fulton
said.
   The blast killed three people, seriously injured a Liquid
Carbonics employee and forced the evacuation of 1,500 people living
near the plant.
   Fulton said Liquid Carbonics on Monday removed cylinders of
silane from its Harrison, N.J. storage facility. Phone calls to
Liquid Carbonics in Harrison were unanswered.
   Elsewhere, about 1,000 workers were kept from their jobs Monday
in California after canisters containing potentially explosive
chemicals were discovered at semiconductor facilities there.
   Chemical inspectors eventually concluded that four canisters at
Advanced Micro Devices Inc. in Santa Clara and Teledyne
Semiconductor in Mountain View were harmless, and work was
scheduled to resume today.
   Another 150 cylinders stored at a Liquid Carbonics plant in San
Carlos where they are manufactured were expected to be examined
Tuesday, officials said. Company officials feared the canisters
might have come from the same batch as the one that blew up.
   At a Gould Inc. semiconductor plant in Pocatello, Idaho, another
possibly contaminated silane cylinder bought from Liquid Carbonics
was emptied Sunday after employees and residents of a nearby
nursing home were evacuated, said a spokesman at Gould's
headquarters in Chicago.
   New Jersey officials said Monday another potentially dangerous
cylinder of silane that prompted officials to evacuate residents
Friday night continued to burn at the Gollob plant.
   Two other potentially hazardous canisters at the site were
removed Sunday. Fulton said about 200 non-hazardous cylinders of
gas remained at the site.
   State officials have not conducted an inventory of the gutted
Gollob building and were trying to decide whether to let the
flaming cylinder burn itself out, Fulton said.
   Evacuees were allowed to return to their homes Sunday and
businesses near the Gollob plant were allowed to reopen Monday.
</TEXT>
