<1ST_LINE>d i PM-BRF--PalauMovement     03-22 0179</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Palau Movement,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Starts Drive To Have Palau Declared U.S. Commonwealth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KOROR, Palau (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of residents in this western Pacific
island chain have started a drive to have Palau declared a
commonwealth of the United States, citing a need for U.S. law
enforcement agencies.
   The Palau America Association wrote to President Reagan and
lawmakers Monday, informing them of a petition drive aimed at
placing a constitutional amendment on Palau's November election
ballot.
   Palau, the last Pacific territory still under U.S. trusteeship
since World War II, has entered into a compact of free association
with the United States. That measure is still awaiting
implementation in Congress.
   ``This movement is born out of a belated realization by many
Palauans that the future well-being of Palau and a majority of its
people will not be protected under a Compact of Free Association
without the presence of U.S. federal law enforcement agencies,''
said a letter from Francisco T. Uludong, who is working on the
petition drive.
   Volunteers need signatures of 25 percent of the electorate,
about 2,000 people.
</TEXT>
