<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Captives,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Soviets in Captivity, One Missing in Ethiopia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet government announced today that three
Soviet soldiers have been taken prisoner by Eritrean separatists
and another is missing in Ethiopia.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov told reporters
at a news briefing that 13 Soviet military advisers were captured
in Ethiopia last week by forces fighting to establish an Eritrean
state separate from the government of Addis Ababa.
   ``Recently the so-called People's Front for the Liberation of
Eritrea has intensified combat operations,'' Gerasimov said.
   He said nine of the Soviets captured had returned to their
command posts, three had been identified by their captors as
prisoners of war and one remained missing.
   The spokesman said the soldiers were serving as military
advisers in Ethiopia, which has strong political ties to the Soviet
Union.
   Gerasimov had no other details of the incident or the conditions
in which the Soviet captives are being held.
   Eritrea, a former Italian colony on the Red Sea, was
administered by Britain from World War II until 1952 when it was
federated with Ethiopia under a United Nations resolution. Ethiopia
incorporated it as a province in 1962, sparking a rebellion which
seeks independence.
</TEXT>
