<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ArmsTreaty 1stLd-Writethru a0428 03-22 0697</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arms Treaty, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0428,690</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: First 9 grafs new material, picking up 6th graf pvs, Despite
the</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States can have ``great certainty''
that it will spot any Soviet attempts to cheat on the treaty
eliminating medium-range atomic missiles from Europe, the Senate
Intelligence Committee unanimously concluded today.
   The testimony came as the Senate Foreign Relations Committee
began working on the final details of the pact after two months of
testimony on the treaty signed Dec. 8 by President Reagan and
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   The Foreign Relations Committee is reviewing the pact. Senate
Democratic leaders say they expect the treaty will be approved by
the full chamber next month.
   Leaders of both parties have predicted the final tally will show
88 to 90 votes for the treaty, far more than the 67 needed for
ratification.
   As part of the Senate review, the Intelligence Committee looked
at American ability to monitor Soviet compliance through a variety
of means including on-site ground inspection and satellites.
   ``The intelligence community will be able to monitor the
drawdown and elimination of declared Soviet missile launchers and
associated equipment with great certainty,'' said the report, which
was unanimously approved by the committee.
   But Sen. David Boren, D-Okla., chairman of the Intelligence
Committee, told the Foreign Relations Committee that more money
needs to be spent to be sure of finding Soviet attempts to cheat on
a separate treaty making deep cuts in long-range atomic weapons.
That prospective treaty is now being worked on by American and
Soviet negotiators.
   ``The interests of the United States are served by effective,
verifiable limitations on nuclear weapons,'' said Boren. ``Indeed,
such limitations must continue to be pursued vigorously long after
the issue of ratification of the (medium-range missile) treaty has
been been resolved.''
   Sen. William Cohen, R-Maine, vice chairman of the Intelligence
Committee, warned the foreign relations panel that ``no
verification and monitoring regime can be absolutely perfect.''
   Despite the expected outcome, the pact has come under fire from
both Democrats and conservative Republicans.
   Democrats, led by Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., are considering
attaching a legal condition to the treaty which provides that the
interpretation given by administration officials during treaty
hearings is binding on future administrations.
   Democratic officials were working late Monday to agree on some
type of language, but no final proposal had been approved,
according to congressional sources speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   The proposal arises from the ongoing dispute between the Reagan
administration and congressional Democrats over Reagan's assertion
that he has the legal right unilaterally to change the U.S.
interpretation of the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty.
   That change would allow some tests of Reagan's Star Wars
anti-missile defense system, but congressional Democrats have
argued that any alteration in how a treaty is interpreted should
first be approved by the Senate.
   The White House told congressional Democrats last week it
opposed the Democratic-backed effort to attach a condition to the
treaty because the condition would require the executive branch to
adhere to every statement made by administration officials during
the hearings, ``no matter how trivial.''
   The conservative opposition is led by Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C.,
ranking Republican on the Foreign Relations Committee.
   Helms has claimed that the administration made
``misrepresentations'' about the effect of the treaty, a charge
that was flatly denied by Secretary of State George P. Shultz.
   Shultz, who was both the first and last administration witness
to testify to the Foreign Relations panel, said the treaty ``stands
on its merits'' and ``should not be made a vehicle for statements
on other issues.''
   Shultz and other administration officials have consistently
urged the Senate to avoid so-called ``killer amendments'' that
could force a reopening of negotiations with the Soviet Union.
   Administration officials have also argued that rejection of the
treaty would be a deep blow to U.S. prestige and power in the
16-member NATO alliance.
   One condition which will be opposed is being offered by Sen.
Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz.
   The amendment will require Reagan to ``reaffirm to the Soviet
Union the importance Americans place on human rights and
fundamental freedoms in the achievement of lasting peace among
nations.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
