<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lebanon-Americans     03-22 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Americans,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moslem Calls For Kidnapping Americans, Another Says Kidnappings
Ending</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem cleric called
today for extremists to kidnap more Americans because, he claimed,
the United States was responsible for the problems in the Middle
East.
   ``America is the cause of all our calamities,'' Sheik Subhi
Tufaili was quoted as saying in a published interview. ``The
Moslems should chase America's symbols everywhere.''
   Tufaili, a senior leader of the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or
Party of God, was quoted as urging his followers to ``hold
(hostage) all the American regime.''
   Meanwhile, Lebanon's highest ranking Shiite cleric, Sheik
Mohammed Mehdi Shamseddine, said he believed that the kidnapping of
foreigners for political motives ``has reached its end.''
   ``We are inclined to believe that this course of political
action has reached an end,'' Shamseddine told the Lebanese News
Agency, an Arabic-language newsletter. He did not elaborate.
   Shamseddine said he has never approved of kidnappings.
   His remark reflects differences within Lebanon's Shiite
community over the abduction of foreigners.
   Tufaili made his remarks in an interview published by the
Hezbollah-financed weekly magazine Al-Wihda Al-Islamiah, or Islamic
Unity.
   Hezbollah, made up of Shiites loyal to Iran's Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini, is believed to be an umbrella organization for
underground groups holding most of the nine Americans missing in
Lebanon.
   Tufaili also charged that the United Nations Interim Force in
Lebanon was an ``umbrella for many of America's and the West's
spies.''
   The nine-nation 5,800-strong UNIFIL has been deployed in south
Lebanon since March 19, 1978.
   U.S. Marine Lt. Col. William R. Higgins, chief of the 76-member
Observer Group-Lebanon attached to UNIFIL, was kidnapped near the
southern Lebanese port city of Tyre on Feb. 17.
   The pro-Iranian Organization of the Oppressed on Earth, believed
to be a Hezbollah-affiliated group, claimed Higgins' abduction and
claimed he was a spy. U.S. and UNIFIL officials denied the charge.
   In addition to the nine Americans, 13 foreigners are missing
after being kidnapped in Lebanon. They are four Frenchmen, three
Britons, one West German, one Italian, one Irishman, one Indian and
two unidentified foreign men.
   Terry Anderson, 40, chief Middle East Correspondent of The
Associated Press, is the longest-held foreign hostage in Lebanon.
He was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
