<2ND_LINE>PM-Irish, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0545,0720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protestant Charged With Six Murders</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Protestant being charged
with murders. PICKS up 3rd graf, `In Londonderry, ...' EDITS to
tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Protestant who allegedly
killed three Roman Catholics in a gun and grenade attack at an
Irish Republican Army funeral last week will be charged with six
counts of murder, police said today.
   Michael Stone, 33, has been in custody since last Wednesday when
mourners grabbed and beat him as he fled the funeral in Milltown,
firing and hurling grenades.
   Police gave no immediate details of the three other murder
charges against Stone. But police sources have said Stone was also
suspected of being connected with other killings of Catholics in
recent years.
   Meanwhile, the Catholic ghettos of West Belfast braced for a
wave of arrests in the hunt for the killers of two British soldiers
at an IRA funeral Saturday. A crowd, some of whom apparently feared
another Protestant attack, beat and stripped the soldiers who were
then shot dead by IRA gunmen.
   Police sources said up to 30 people may be arrested.
   Earlier today, British troops discoverd and detonated a homemade
bomb outside an apartment building on the outskirts of West Belfast.
   And police reported finding two rifles, grenades and a pistol in
Londonderry's Catholic Shantallow district, the fourth cache found
in the city this week.
   In Londonderry, police sought the men who killed policeman Clive
Graham at a Londonderry police checkpoint Monday. Graham was the
12th victim in two weeks of tension and sectarian violence in
northern Ireland.
   Police Chief Supt. David Turkington said ``someone must have
seen'' the gunmen who held a family hostage, fired on Graham from a
row house and escaped in a hijacked car.
   Britain's two TV networks, the British Broadcasting Corp. and
Independent Television News, said Monday they have refused police
demands to hand over untransmitted film of last Wednesday's funeral
rampage on grounds this would endanger their crews in the future.
   ``This policy is to protect our film crews, to protect the lives
of our staff,'' said a BBC spokeswoman, who declined to be
identified.
   Addressing the House of Commons in London on Monday, Northern
Ireland Secretary Tom King said, ``A massive murder investigation
is under way in which all possible resources are involved to
identify all those responsible.''
   He also announced an immediate review of a policy of not
policing IRA funerals.
   Police introduced the no-policing policy at last Wednesday's
funeral for the three IRA guerrillas killed in Gibraltar under
pressure from Catholic leaders who feared clashes between police
and mourners.
   The latest wave of tension and violence began March 6, when
British commandos shot and killed three unarmed IRA guerrillas in
Gibraltar while they were allegedly planning a bombing attack in
the British colony.
   Stone allegedly killed three people and injured 68 in
Wednesday's funeral in Milltown for the three IRA members.
   At Saturday's funeral for an IRA man killed in the Milltown
attack, IRA gunmen killed two British soldiers, who were in
civilian clothes at the time.
   Asked why police did not immediately order in heavily armed
units on standby nearby, King said it was not clear at first to
police commanders watching the army video that soldiers were being
attacked. He said the authorities believed no security force
personnel were in the area.
   ``The truth is that there will be new depths (of horror) again
as long as this awful and evil campaign of terrorism and revenge
continues,'' King told the Commons on Monday. ``It has got to
stop.''
   There were new calls for another attempt to find agreement
between the province's mainstream Catholic and Protestant political
parties to stop guerrilla groups.
   Seamus Mallon, deputy leader of the moderate Catholic Social
Democratic and Labor Party, said Britain must decide ``whether the
priority is to defeat the IRA, or to find a political solution.''
   At least 2,638 people have died in sectarian violence in Norther
Northern Ireland since 1969. The mainly Catholic IRA is fighting to
end British rule and unite the Protestant-dominated province with
the Catholic Republic of Ireland under a leftist administration.
</TEXT>
