<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ColdSnap 1stLd-Writethru a0559 03-22 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cold Snap, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0559,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Ch-Ch-Chilly Night in the Northeast</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 2nd graf with 1 to include subzero temperatures. INSERTS
one graf after 6th graf, However, many xxx, to update with other
records.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of the Northeast dug out winter overcoats and ski
jackets as unseasonable cold gripped the region today, three days
into spring.
   Temperatures were generally below freezing, with readings in the
teens and single digits over much of the Great Lakes region and
northern Atlantic Coast. Subzero readings were reported at a few
locations in Maine, New York and Pennsylvania.
   ``Somebody left the door open on the north side of the house,''
said Bob Thomas, a forecaster for the National Weather Service in
Albany, N.Y. ``We're getting a strong cold wind right out of
Hudson's Bay.''
   Spring has been in disguise since it began Sunday; the 21-degree
high in Albany on Monday was about 20 degrees below normal.
   ``Some of the early blooming flowers may be negatively affected.
Some of the crocuses may not fare too well,'' said George Good, a
horticulturalist in Ithaca, N.Y.
   However, many flowers may not have poked their shoots out of the
ground yet, Good said. ``For the most part there hasn't been enough
warm weather yet to really get things started.''
   Ten Northeastern cities reported records this morning, including
Allentown, Pa., where the 15 degree low tied the record set in
1965; Mansfield, Ohio, where the 14-degree mark shaved a degree off
the 1965 record; and Syracuse, N.Y., where the 5 degrees cut three
degrees off a record set in 1959.
   A reading of 7 degrees shortly after midnight set a record in
Binghamton, N.Y. The old record low for the date was 8 degrees in
1965.
   Bradford, Pa., was the coldest place in the nation at 2 a.m.
EST, at zero degrees, and it was 18 degrees at 5:30 a.m. in New
York City. Ohio residents looked out on a Lake Erie that was still
mostly ice-covered.
   However, a warming trend was expected to put winter to flight
this afternoon and Wednesday, with temperatures rising into the 40s
and 50s in the mid-Atlantic region.
   Steve Smith, a weather specialist for Environment Canada at
Churchill, Manitoba, on the shores of Hudson's Bay, disavowed
responsibility for the cold.
   Smith said a high-pressure system was driving the cold air from
the north. ``That's why you're getting our weather. So you really
can't blame us,'' he said.
   ``They call us the polar bear capital of the world. While you're
getting our weather, we've got a south wind that's pushing our
temperatures above normal,'' Smith said.
   In Churchill, the high Monday was 10 degrees, seven degrees
above normal. The low was minus 15.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880322-0103 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 1113EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-GulfRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0561 03-22 0814</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Rdp, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0561,0833</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Attacks Tanker, 2 Crewmen Killed; Greek Tanker Reported Hit</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with Iraqi missile hitting
Tehran. PICKS up 4th graf, `Shipping executives ...' SUBS grafs
7-8, bgng, `The escalation ...,' with 2 grafs to UPDATE with
today's missile attack. PICKS up 9th graf, `The Havglimt ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NABILA MEGALLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Iranian gunboat and helicopter
attacked a Norwegian-operated tanker carrying volatile chemicals
through the Persian Gulf at dawn today. A Greek supertanker later
was reported set ablaze in another Iranian raid.
   Two crewmen were killed and four wounded in the first attack, on
the 38,534-ton Havglimt, flying the Singapore flag, shipping
executives reported.
   Iraq fired a missile at Tehran today and mounted air raids on
seven other cities, the Iraqi News Agency reported. The missile was
the 45th aimed at the Iranian capital since the Iran-Iraq ``war of
cities'' resumed March 13.
   Shipping executives said an unidentified U.S. warship patrolling
the gulf picked up 10 seamen, who were floating in a raft after
abandoning the Greek supertanker, the 357,130-ton Stavros G.L.
   The executives said the other 19 Greek crewmen stayed on board
to fight the flames. A salvage tugboat soon joined the effort.
   There were no casualties aboard the Greek vessel, which was
attacked about 1 p.m. only a few miles south of where the Havglimt
was hit in a dawn attack.
   The attacks were the seventh and eighth by Iran on neutral
shipping since Friday. They came as 51 crewmen remained missing and
were presumed dead after an Iraqi raid on two tankers near Iran's
Kharg island oil terminal. Earlier reports had said 54 crewmen were
missing.
   The escalation of the ``tanker war'' came as Iran and Iraq were
locked in a series of missile duels and air raids on each other's
major cities. The two nations have been at war for 7{ years.
   Today's missile attack on Tehran was the 106th such attack since
Feb. 29.
   About 65 Iranian missiles have slammed into Baghdad in that
time. Also Monday, Iran launched an artillery and rocket attack on
Basra, inflicting heavy casualties, Iraq said.
   The Havglimt tanker, carrying ammonia and operated by the
Oslo-based Havtor Co., was hit at dawn about 12 miles northwest of
Dubai, said the gulf-based shipping executives, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   The dead crewmen were identified as Singapore nationals, and the
ship's Norwegian captain was among the wounded. Other members of
the 26-man, multinational crew were mainly treated for inhalation
of ammonia vapors, according to the executives. Four needed
hospitalization.
   The fire in the engine room of the stricken tanker was brought
under control by salvage tugboats, but the flames later reignited
in the crew's quarters, the executives said.
   The British destroyer HMS Exeter, on patrol in the area,
dispatched a helicopter to help rescue the crew, many of whom had
fainted from fumes leaking from blasted cargo holds, the shipping
sources said.
   A navy medical team wore gas masks as they were lowered from the
helicopter onto the tanker to help airlift the seamen.
   The bodies of the dead and the injured crew members were lowered
onto a salvage tugboat, which took them to a hospital at the United
Arab Emirates port of Dubai, the sources said.
   The shipping executive said at least one gunboat raided the
vessel with machine-gun fire and rocket-propelled grenades. Forty
minutes later, a helicopter fired rockets at the tanker.
   ``They went for the accommodation quarters. There were plenty,
plenty of hits all over,'' said Associated Press photographer Greg
English, who flew over the stricken tanker in a helicopter.
   Iraq resumed attacks on Iranian oil shipping lanes on March 8,
after a lull in attacks in the Persian Gulf for about a month.
   On Monday, Iranian gunboats attacked and set ablaze the
10,168-ton Spanish refrigerator ship Iberian Reefer and the
61,762-ton Liberian-registered Fumi with rocket grenades. No
casualties were reported on board either ship.
   At least 51 crewmen remained missing from Iraq's Saturday attack
near Iran's Kharg Island oil terminal. The attack destroyed two
Iranian-owned ships, the 253,837-ton Sanandaj and the 316,379-ton
Avaj.
   The Norwegian Shipping Association reported today that the
number of missing was ``imprecise,'' but the latest figure was 51.
   Earlier, Norwegian officials had said 54 crewmen, mostly
Iranians and Asians, were presumed dead. A Swedish engineer also
was among the missing.
   The Shipping Association said it had no independent confirmation
of the deaths and was working on the basis of gulf sources.
   Both ships were owned by the Iran's National Iranian Tanker Co.,
but the Sanandaj crew was hired by a Norwegian firm, Viking
Engineering, and another Norwegian company, Scanact, had part
interest in the Avaj.
   The maritime insurance firm, Lloyd's of London, said 37 ships
had been damaged in attacks by both Iraq and Iran this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
