<1ST_LINE>r p PM-JewishCongress     03-22 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jewish Congress,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Resolution On Religion And Politics Tabled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delegates to the American Jewish Congress
convention voiced concern today about the role of religious groups
in politics but tabled a resolution urging churches and synagogues
to refrain from active roles in political campaigns.
   The proposed resolution, which will be redrafted, had suggested
it was ``inherently dangerous'' for religious groups to identify
with one candidate or one political party. It reaffirmed the right
of all people, including clergy, to seek political office.
   The resolution is expected to be taken up at a later national
meeting of the group, but leaders did not indicate whether it would
be during the 1988 presidential campaign.
   Discussion centered on whether delegates should take a strong
stand against practices by two religious leaders now running for
president, Pat Robertson and Rev. Jesse Jackson.
   The tabled resolution said ``certain recent practices of both
these candidates are troubling issues,'' citing Robertson's use of
church-owned buses to bring supporters to caucuses and Jackson's
effort during the Super Tuesday primaries to collect contributions
in churches.
   In their nearly unanimous decision to redraft the resolution,
delegates said it could be counterproductive and also should not
refer to any individual.
   On Monday night, an AJC leader urged that a new world Zionist
meeting be convened in Jerusalem in the 1990s to unify Jews
everywhere with Israelis and to heal the division over how to
achieve peace with the Arabs.
   ``We are indeed one people, sharing one destiny, no matter where
we live,'' executive director Henry Siegman told delegates at the
70th anniversary convention.
   Siegman reiterated the AJC's support for a U.S. plan calling for
talks on Palestinian autonomy in the occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip, followed by an international peace conference including
Israel and its Arab neighbors. He also spoke out against Israeli
Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's condemnation of Jews who object to
his opposition to the plan.
   ``The Jewish people everywhere, and not only those who vote in
support of a particular Israeli party, have a right to speak up
when they believe certain policies profoundly violate a legacy that
belongs to the Jewish people collectively, even if finally only the
citizens of Israel will vote and make those decisions on which
their security depends,'' Siegman said.
</TEXT>
