<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Noriega-Hearing     03-22 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Noriega-Hearing,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge: Panamanian Strongman's Attorney May File Position On
Indictment</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge ruled today that Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega's attorney can formally protest the legality of
racketeering and drug trafficking charges, even though the
Panmanian strongman has not appeared in court to answer the
indictment.
   U.S. District Judge William M. Hoeveler granted permission for
Noriega's attorney, Neal Sonnett, to file a ``limited appearance''
on behalf of the embattled strongman.
   ``This limited appearance would be solely for the purpose of
attacking the legality and sufficiency of the indictment,'' said
Sonnett, among a battery of Miami attorneys retained by Noriega.
   The decision came over vehement objections from Assistant U.S.
Attorney Richard Gregorie, who said that Noriega's attorney could
not make any arguments until Noriega responds legally to the U.S.
indictment by making an appearance.
   Gregorie noted that Noriega had not surrendered nor made any
court appearance to answer charges in the sealed indictment
returned by a federal grand jury in Miami Feb. 4, which named
Noriega and 15 other people.
   Gregorie and Sonnett were involved in a heated exchange during
the hearing in Hoeveler's courtroom.
   ``I represent General Noriega,'' Sonnett told the judge.
   ``The government objects. He has no client to represent!''
responded Gregorie.
   ``I have a client and Mr. Gregorie knows that I have a client,''
Sonnett shot back, to which Gregorie responded, ``Then bring him
here!''
   Hoeveler agreed to let Sonnett file by Friday a memorandum of
law setting forth his position. He gave Gregorie until the
following Friday to respond.
   ``You may file your motion; then we'll decide whether you can
argue it,'' Hoeveler told Sonnett.
   Only one of the 16 defendants named in the indictment, Brian
Alden Davidow, was at today's hearing.
   Davidow, 26, the only person to surrender in the case thus far
and be arraigned, has pleaded innocent to the racketeering
conspiracy count and other charges in the indictment. He is free on
$500,000 bond after his family posted 10 percent of that amount
with the court.
   Hoeveler delayed setting a trial date after Davidow made a
formal waiver of his right to a speedy trial.
   Most of the other defendants named in the indictment were in
either Panama or Colombia, Gregorie said.
</TEXT>
