<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Panama 3rdLd-Writethru a0584-0577 03-22 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Panama, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0584-0577,540</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 5 grafs with State Department comment after 5th graf
pvs, ``I'm not</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said today he still hopes
Panamanian strongman Manuel Antonio Noriega will relinquish power
and leave the country.
   But Reagan would not say whether he expects Noriega to do that.
   Asked by reporters if he would be satisfied should Noriega step
down but not leave his Central American country, Reagan said, ``We
feel Noriega should leave Panama.''
   Reagan, questioned as he arrived at the Capitol for talks on the
possibility of resuming U.S. aid to the Contra rebels in Nicaragua,
was asked if he expected Noriega to agree to leave his nation.
   ``I'm not making any predictions,'' the president replied.
   At the State Department, spokesman Charles Redman said that the
Panamanian people clearly have not been deceived by Noriega's
conditional offer to step down by May 1989.
   Redman said Panamanians regard the offer as a ``ploy to buy
time,'' a view shared by the United States.
   ``The message from Panamanians is clear. For the good of Panama,
Noriega should leave,'' Redman said.
   ``His presence is the root cause of continued political and
economic instability,'' Redman added. ``The ongoing general strike
is only the most recent demonstration of the overwhelming
opposition from all segments of Panamanian society to Noriega's
continued rule.''
   On Monday, shortly after Panama's chief of state, Manuel Solis
Palma, told Panamanians of Noriega's offer, State Department press
officer Anita Stockman said, ``We stand by our previous view that
Noriega should go, and the sooner the better for Panama.''
   Solis Palma said Noriega had given his word ``as an officer and
a gentleman'' to step down before Panamanian elections scheduled
for May 1989 if his conditions _ which include talks with
opposition leaders _ are met.
   William G. Walker, deputy assistant secretary of state for
inter-American affairs, said Noriega's offer ``totally ignores the
reality of the situation.''
   ``Almost everyone in Panama wants him out tomorrow and wants him
out of the country,'' said Walker, who was in Panama last week to
discusss terms under which Noriega might step down.
   A State Department statement released by Stockman said:
   ``We believe the offer is little more than one, a ploy to
attempt to legitimize the illegal Solis Palma regime by calling for
negotiations between it and opposition groups and two, an effort on
the part of Noriega to maintain direct or indirect control of the
Panamanian Defense Forces.''
   Noriega is under indictment on federal drug charges in Florida.
The United States has dried up the flow of money to Panama, which
uses the U.S. dollar as its currency, in the effort to force him
out, and the economy is near collapse.
   ``Noriega is the problem, and his preoccupation with remaining
on the scene despite overwhelming domestic opposition will only
insure continued economic and political instability there,'' the
State Department said.
   Noriega put down a coup attempt by dissident officers last week
and rejected a U.S. plan for him to leave Panama and live in Spain.
   Solis Palma replaced Eric Arturo Delvalle, who was dismissed by
the legislature after he tried to fire Noriega. Delvalle, who is
hiding in Panama, is still recognized by the United States as
Panama's president.
</TEXT>
