<DOCNO> AP880322-0114 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 1231EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WarmYears     03-22 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Warm Years,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>1986-87 Were Warmest Years Since 1950s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last two years have been the warmest in
this country in more than three decades, the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration reported Tuesday.
   Both 1986 and 1987 recorded average temperatures for the year of
54.0 degres Fahrenheit over the 48 contiguous states, the agency
said.
   These were the warmest years since 1953, which averaged 54.7 to
tie with 1934 for the warmest year in this century.
   By contrast, records going back to 1895 show the normal annual
average temperature for the 48 states is 52.5 degrees. The coldest
year was 1917, which averaged 50.7.
   Tom Karl of the National Climatic Data Center in Asheville,
N.C., said the combination of the position of the jet stream upper
air currents and the high pressure center located over Bermuda were
contributing factors in the recent warm years.
   ``The more basic thing is why they were in those positions, and
that's more difficult to answer,'' Karl said.
   ``The concern everyone has in the back of their mind is if it's
part of the greenhouse gas effect'' that has been reported on, he
said.
   The greenhouse effect is a prediction of computer models, which
say increasing amounts of carbon dioxide and other gases in the
atmosphere could act much like the glass in a greenhouse, trapping
heat and raising the temperature of the Earth.
   ``It's not clear yet,'' if that is a factor in the warmth of
1986 and 1987, ``but it bears watching,'' Karl said.
   Until 1986 the average temperature of the United States had been
running at or slightly below normal in the 1980s, Karl said, even
though worldwide temperatures seemed to be on the increase.
   In 1986, he said, the spring was particularly warm across the
country. The winter of 1986-87 and the spring of 1987 also were
unusually warm, particularly in the north-central region.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880322-0115 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 1237EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Spain-Haven     03-22 0636</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spain-Haven,0657</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spain's Strong Latin Ties Lead To Asylum Offers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN LINNEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The offer of asylum to Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega of Panama maintains a Spanish tradition of opening its
doors to Latin Americans seeking a place of exile.
   The hospitality stems from historic and cultural ties with Latin
America that transcend Spanish party politics. But the Spain that
is prepared to offer asylum to Noriega is far different from the
country that took in ousted Cuban dictator Fulgencio Batista in
1959.
   During the 36-year rule of Gen. Francisco Franco, Spain became a
haven for Batista, Colombian ruler Gustavo Rojas Pinilla, ousted
Argentine leader Juan D. Peron, toppled Dominican President Juan
Bosch and Venezuelan strongman Marcos Perez Jimenez.
   Rojas Pinilla arrived in 1957 after a stopover in Bermuda,
Batista spent time in Madeira and Lisbon before settling in Madrid
and Peron wandered from Paraguay to Panama to Venezuela after his
1955 ouster before arriving in Seville in 1960.
   Both Perez Jimenez, ousted in 1958, and Bosch, a democratically
elected president toppled in 1963, lived in the United States
before coming to Spain.
   Franco's conditions for receiving all were simple: maintain a
low profile and don't meddle in Spanish or foreign politics.
   In the case of Noriega, Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez says
Spanish policy is to accept requests when asylum could help
maintain or restore democracy in a specific country.
   As conditions for accepting Noriega, Spain requires that he
himself ask for asylum, that the United States agree not to seek
his extradition on drug-trafficking and money-laundering charges
filed against him in U.S. federal courts, and that Washington honor
the 1977 treaty under which control of the Panama Canal will revert
to Panama in 2000.
   Noriega has refused to leave Panama. But he has said he is
willing to step down as military leader prior to the 1989
presidential elections in Panama.
   Santiago Varela Diaz, a Gonzalez spokesman, said since Spain's
transition to democratic government in 1977, the type of political
exile in Spain has changed considerably.
   ``Since then, Spain has taken in many Chileans, Argentines and
Uruguayans fleeing from military dictatorships,'' he said. ``The
case of Panama and Noriega is separate, but it is a concrete
example of our willingness to serve as a support for a democratic
solution to a problem.''
   During the waning years of the Franco regime in the early 1970s,
not all the Latin American exiles in Spain were rightist dictators.
   Former Economics Minister Manuel Ulloa of Peru came to Spain
after the army ousted President Fernando Belaunde Terry in 1968.
Belaunde went to the United States.
   Christian Democratic leader Andres Zaldivar of Chile moved to
Madrid after Gen. Agusto Pinochet overthrew President Salvador
Allende in 1973.
   Most of the Latin American leaders exiled in Spain have lived in
the opulent suburbs north of Madrid.
   Batista died in Madrid of a heart attack in 1973. Perez Jimenez,
74, still lives in a palatial residence in La Moraleja.
   Until his return to Argentina after an 18-year exile, Peron held
court at his 17th of October estate in Puerta de Hierro.
   Franco laid down the law to Peron four years after his arrival
when the Argentine general tried an unsuccessful return to Buenos
Aires in 1964 and threatened him with explusion if he kept up his
politicking.
   But by 1970 Peron was again receiving a steady stream of
visitors and plotting his return to Argentina where he was elected
president in 1973. He died a year later.
   His widow, Maria Estela Martinez de Peron, who succeeded her
husband as the first woman head of state in the Western hemisphere,
lives in quiet exile in Madrid after her overthrow by the military
in 1976 and five years of house arrest in southern Argentina.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
