<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pope-Soviet     03-22 0632</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-Soviet,0648</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vatican Will Send Delegation to Moscow for Christian Millennium</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Ancient name Kievan Rus' is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has invited a Vatican
delegation to help celebrate the 1,000th anniversary of
Christianity in the region, but Pope John Paul II won't be a member
of it, a Vatican official said Tuesday.
   Cardinal Johannes Willebrands made the disclosure at a news
conference at which he presented the pope's letter on the
millennium of Christianity in Kievan Rus', the ancient name of the
Ukraine. The celebrations are scheduled for June.
   The letter stressed Europe's Christian roots and said Christian
unity is essential to peace in Europe and the world.
   Willebrands, president of the Vatican's Secretariat for
Christian Unity, said a representative of the Russian Orthodox
church patriarch made the invitation orally to two officials of his
agency March 18 in Moscow.
   He said John Paul, as head of the Roman Catholic church, was
invited to send a delegation to celebrations in Moscow being
organized by the Russian Orthodox church.
   When an official written invitation is received, the pontiff
will name the delegation for the trip to Moscow, which is expected
to last about 10 days, the Dutch-born cardinal said.
   John Paul often has expressed interest in visiting the Soviet
Union. Willebrands said the pope had not received a personal
invitation to the celebration and had no plans to attend, but that
does not rule out a posssible future visit.
   He said it would not be ``opportune'' for the pope to attend the
observance because ``he cannot make his pastoral visit, which is
destined primarily for Catholics, during celebrations organized by
another church.''
   The pope has said he would visit the Soviet Union if he was
allowed to visit Roman Catholics throughout the country, including
the Ukraine, Lithuania, Latvia, Byelorussia and Kazakhstan.
   Three years ago, he disclosed that Soviet authorities had
refused permission for him to visit Lithuania, a Catholic
stronghold.
   In his 39-page letter to bishops around the world, John Paul
urged the faithful to join in prayer to mark the baptism in 988 of
Prince Vladimir on the banks of the Dnieper in Kiev.
   ``The whole Catholic church turns its gaze to that event and
shares spiritually in the joy of the heirs to that baptism,'' he
said.
   John Paul praised Christians in the region, who he said have
sometimes experienced ``persecution and martyrdom'' in those 1,000
years.
   ``In particular, we join with all the heirs of this baptism,
whatever their religious confession, nationality or dwelling place,
with all our Orthodox and Catholic brothers and sisters,'' the
letter said.
   ``In a special way, we join with all the beloved sons and
daughters of the Russian, Ukrainian and Byelorussian nations. To
those who live in their homeland, as also to those who dwell in
America, Western Europe and other parts of the world.''
   The millennium is ``in a special way the feast'' of the Russian
Orthodox church, which ``remains united to the Catholic church with
very close links,'' the pope wrote.
   ``At this solemn moment in history the Catholic community ...
sends to her 1,000-year-old sister church, through the bishop of
Rome, the kiss of peace as a manifestation of an ardent desire for
that perfect communion.''
   In a plea for Christian unity, John Paul said the Christian
roots of Europe present ``a particularly pressing challenge to the
unity of Christians. ... The desire for unity and peace, the desire
that barriers should be broken down and opposition removed . .. is
becoming an impelling sign of our times.''
   ``True peace can only exist on the basis of a process of
unification in which each people is able to choose, in freedom and
truth, the path of its own development.''
</TEXT>
