<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PUREXShutdown     03-22 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PUREX Shutdown,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hanford Nuclear Reservation Plant Shut Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Hanford nuclear reservation plutonium
processing plant was shut down and two technicians were suspended
in the wake of an incident involving the improper transfer of
chemicals, a Westinghouse Hanford spokesman said today.
   Operations at the Plutonium-Uranium Extraction Plant, or PUREX,
were suspended over the weekend as a precautionary measure, said
spokesman Rudy Cortez.
   The temporary suspension resulted from an incident Friday in
which a valve was left open and a batch of the wrong chemical
solution was transferred to a tank, Cortez said.
   As a consequence, the certifications of two nuclear process
operators were suspended for failing to follow operating
procedures, he said. The event was declared to be an infraction of
a ``criticality prevention specification.''
   A ``criticality'' is an uncontrolled nuclear chain reaction
resulting in a rapid buildup of radiation and heat. It is caused by
such factors as the amount, shape, density and enrichment of
plutonium or uranium and the manner in which they are stored.
   There was no danger of a criticality incident and no danger of a
radioactiuve release to the environment, Cortez said. It has not
been determined how long operations will be suspended, he said.
   The PUREX plant was closed for a time in October 1986 because of
safety concerns over plutonium handling and possible accidents.
Westinghouse Hanford officials who took over operation of the
plants in July 1987 promised to make safety a top priority.
   The chemical transfer incidents were the latest in a series of
safety-related ones at the PUREX facility, which dissolves fuel
rods to remove plutonium and uranium for reprocessing.
   The cause of contamination of two crane operators at the
facility March 14 is still under investigation. Radioactive
contamination was found in one crane operator's home and another
contamination was found on another operator as he prepared to leave
the plant. Both men were decontaminated and returned to work the
next day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880322-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 1308EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DurableGoods     03-22 0638</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Durable Goods,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Durable Goods Orders Decline Again, But Economists Still
Optimistic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders to U.S. factories for ``big ticket''
durable goods fell 1.8 percent in February, but analysts said the
second consecutive monthly decline had not shaken their belief that
manufacturing will be a bright spot in the economy this year.
   The Commerce Department report Tuesday said that orders for
durable goods _ items expected to last three or more years _
totaled a seasonally adjusted $111.4 billion in February, following
an identical 1.8 percent January decline.
   It was the first time since the spring of 1986 that durable
goods orders have fallen for two consecutive months.
   The February decline surprised economists, but they maintained
that manufacturing companies were still enjoying boom times because
the weaker dollar has boosted export demand.
   ``The fundamentals continue to look positive for
manufacturing,'' said Allen Sinai, chief economist of The Boston
Co. ``What we have is a two-month hesitation after some big
increases.''
   Manufacturing is expected to be a major source of strength this
year as businesses step up production to meet rising export demand
and American companies increase orders for capital equipment to
expand their production capabilities.
   The Reagan administration is forecasting that almost half of all
economic growth in 1988 will come from rising export demand.
   Still, analysts said the back-to-back declines did show that
businesses were cutting back on orders in the early part of 1988 in
an effort to get control of bulging inventories. Inventories
swelled at the end of 1987 while consumer demand fell.
   Economists once had feared this combina4hn could be enough to
topple the country into a recession. But brighter statistics this
year, including continue declines in the unemployment rate in
February, have eased those concerns.
   CynthIaXLatta, an economist with Data Resources Ik#-, noted that
while new orders fell in February, the toas no immediate response from
the rebels, who have been
supported by the United States since the start of their fight in
late 1981.
   Negotiators for both sides were optimistic after the first day
of cease-fire talks Monday, the first held since December.
   Also Monday, Nicaragua withdrew its soldiers from the Honduran
border and declared an end to fighting with Contra rebels while the
talks are held in Sapoa. The Honduran military reported Sandinista
soldiers had retreated.
   ``The importance of today was that we listened for the first
time at the highest level their (Contras') proposal, Gen. Humberto
Ortega, Nicaragua's defense minister, told journalists in Sapoa on
Monday.
   Alfredo Cesar, a negotiator for the U.S.-backed rebels, called
the first round a ``step ahead'' and said they discussed a wide
range of issues.
   ``Neither side seeks a military victory over the other,'' Cesar
said.
   Monday's session was held under tight security at the customs
post in this town beside the border with Costa Rica, along the bank
of Lake Nicaragua.
   At stake in the talks, scheduled to resume today, is an end to
the bloodshed that has claimed an estimated 50,000 dead and wounded
and shattered the country's economy.
   The Sandinista proposal to stop the fighting calls for an
``immediate and definitive cease-fire,'' Ortega said. He did not
elaborate.
   The Contra plan calls for a 30-day truce, political amnesty,
press freedom and continued talks to work out a lasting cease-fire,
Cesar said.
   Frank Arana, a rebel spokesman, said the talks went beyond the
bounds earlier established by the Sandinistas and included
political issues and ``concepts of democracy.''
   ``We spoke about everything,'' he said.
   The goal of the Sandinistas is to work out a viable cease-fire
in accordance with the regional peace plan signed last August by
the presidents of the five Central American nations. They had said
the talks would cover only the mechanics of how the Contras would
lay down their arms.
   The rebels said the talks should include discussion of
democratic reforms, also covered in the regional peace plan.
   ``We came here with an open agenda,'' Adolfo Calero, a Contra
leader, told journalists at the border post. ``And that includes
democratization including amnesty. We insisted on speaking about
all the problems facing Nicaragua.''
   Negotiations opened after Ortega, brother of President Daniel
Ortega, said the Sandinistas were suspending military operations
for the duration of the talks and called on the Contras to do the
same.
   Sandinista spokesman Manuel Espinoza told reporters the
``reciprocation of the Contras'' in agreeing to suspend hostilities
and ``the fact that this meeting is taking place are the first
positive steps'' toward a permanent cease-fire.
   President Ortega on Monday signed a document that dealt with a
number of internal problems. The statement called on all political
parties to refrain from violence, a position targeted at the
government supporters who have attacked the opposition.
   It also calls for the media to respect the government, a
reference to the opposition newspaper La Prensa, and the
Sandinistas promised to release more than a dozen recently jailed
labor leaders and review cases of imprisoned opposition
politiciaans.
   The Sandinistas' willingness to comply with the peace plan was
cited by U.S. congressional members as a reason for rejecting
President Reagan's calls for additional military and nonlethal aid
to the rebels. The peace plan also calls for internal dialogue with
the political opposition.
</TEXT>
