<2ND_LINE>AM-Onlooker Stab,0202</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crowd Watches Passively During Downtown Daylight Stabbing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bystanders looked on but no one intervened
while a man was stabbed to death on a crowded downtown sidewalk,
police said.
   ``There were people standing around the incident and watching it
go down,'' police Detective Larry Martinez said of Monday's 10:30
a.m. attack.
   ``It's non-involvement,'' he said. ``It's like a disease. These
people have to live with themselves. I just wish they had a bigger
conscience. It would be easier on us.''
   It was the second such murder to occur in front of crowds near
the busy intersection of Seventh and Spring streets in four months.
On Nov. 17, Roberto Lopez, 23, was knifed to death shortly after
5:30 p.m. in what was believed to be a drug-related case.
   The 32-year-old man killed Monday was knifed several times in
what Martinez said was also possibly drug-related. His identity
still wasn't known Tuesday and police said they had no suspects in
the case.
   Investigators believe the man staggered a short distance after
he was stabbed. An off-duty officer working nearby on a movie
production was alerted about the incident and contacted paramedics
and police.
