<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Pope-Costs     03-22 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-Costs,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Northern California, Unlike Other Hosts, Still Paying For Pope's
Visit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Six months after Pope John Paul II's second U.S. visit, Roman
Catholic leaders in three of the nine cities where he stopped still
have bills to pay.
   The Archdiocese of San Francisco owes as much as $2 million, and
the nearby Diocese of Monterey still has at least $1 million to
repay, church officials say. In Phoenix, Ariz., the church has yet
to pay nearly $165,000 for renting a stadium.
   Church officials say the debts are paid for the pope's stops in
Miami, Columbia, S.C., New Orleans, San Antonio, Texas, Los Angeles
and Detroit.
   ``We knew we would have some deficit, but we didn't think it
would be of this magnitude,'' said Bruce Egnew, director of finance
for the Archdiocese of San Francisco. He said the church has raised
$2 million since the visit, but still owes at least $1.5 million.
   The Rev. Miles Riley, chief publicist for the archdiocese, put
the total at $2 million.
   The Monterey Diocese has a debt of $1.1 million, said spokesman
Ted Elisee.
   To help retire the debt, the San Francisco Archdiocese plans to
sell pieces of the elaborate $500,000, six-tiered stage used for
the Mass at Candlestick Park. There are also plans for collections
in the churches, receptions and direct appeals to the community,
said Egnew.
   ``It's always harder to raise money after the event,'' said
Riley. ``Not a little bit harder, a lot harder.''
   On the plus side, Riley said last week, he had just received a
letter from a man who had been inspired to return to the church
after a 20-year absence. He enclosed a check for $500, Riley said.
   Elisee said the Monterey Diocese spent $2 million and still owed
$1 million to $1.1 million. The diocese plans an appeal to its 45
parishes, which have 145,000 members, and the church has been
selling memorial magazines at $5 each and videotapes for $25.
   In some cities, church officials dipped into reserve funds and
other accounts to cover the difference between costs and
fund-raising efforts. That amounted to $400,000 in Miami, $200,000
in New Orleans and $1.3 million in Detroit, officials in those
cities said.
   In San Antonio, the church came out a bit ahead, raising $2.4
million but spending 2.32 million, said the Rev. Larry Steubben,
chairman of the Texas Papal Visit Committee.
   It was just last week that the Diocese of Phoenix was billed for
$164,765 for the use of Arizona State University's Sun Devil
Stadium. Church officials had said in January that they faced a
deficit, but did not say how much.
   Last week, the Rev. John McMahon, head of the diocese's
papal-visit committee, declined to comment on the debt. ``We just
got the bill from ASU and we want to see where we are,'' he said
last week.
</TEXT>
