<HEAD>AIDS Brochure Intended for Adults Distributed in High School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PAVILION, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A brochure about AIDS intended for
sexually active adults was mistakenly distributed to teen-agers, an
AIDS program director said.
   ``We're sorry it happened,'' said Edward Darstein, executive
director of the Western New York AIDS program. ``But we've done a
lot of good work over the past five years, and we hope this won't
wreck our record.''
   State Sen. Walter J. Floss was not satisfied, and said Monday he
complained to the governor and state health commissioner.
   Floss said he directed his staff to investigate whether state
funds were used to print the brochures. Darstein said his
organization receives about 90 percent of its $198,000 budget from
the state but private donations funded the brochures.
   Darstein said the brochures were handed out March 9 by a
volunteer who spoke at Pavilion Central School and a second place
and left the wrong brochures at the school.
   The brochure rates the risk of acquired immune deficiency
syndrome infection from various forms of sexual activity, both
homosexual and heterosexual.
