<2ND_LINE>AM-Church Ban,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Bars Man From Church</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LITCHFIELD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who allegedly sought romance
rather than religion has been barred by a judge from attending a
church.
   Judge Anne Dranginis issued a temporary restraining order Monday
prohibiting John Steinmann, 78, of Middlebury from attending the
First Congregational Church of Washington.
   ``We believe his motives to worship are not consistent with
promoting the worship of God, but for the purpose of forming
relationships, particularly with women,'' said the Rev. Richard
Sears, pastor of the chruch.
   The judge's order also prohibits Steinmann from harassing or
contacting church members without their permission.
   According to court documents, Steinmann, member of a Middlebury
church, began attending services in rural Washington in an attempt
to maintain a relationship with his former wife.
   The couple has since divorced, the woman moved and Steinmann
used the church to meet other women, church officials said.
   Church officials filed for the court orders Monday, a day after
Steinmann was arrested for the third time on charges of criminal
trespassing at the church.
   Virginia Steinway of Morris, testified Steinmann once sidled up
to her in a pew, grabbed her arm and made lewd and revolting
remarks to her during a hymn. ``I was extremely panicked,'' she
said.
   Steinmann, who represented himself in court, maintained his
actions were consistent with the church's policy of Christian
fellowship.
