<1ST_LINE>r i AM-IslamicConference     03-22 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Islamic Conference,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moslems Back Palestinian Rebellion; No Unity on Iran-Iraq War</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMAL HALABY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem nations were united Tuesday behind
the Palestinian rebellion in Israeli-occupied lands, but Iran and
Iraq traded insults and there was no Islamic accord on the
7{-year-old Persian Gulf war.
   Foreign ministers of the 46-member Organization of the Islamic
Conference issued a statement condemning ``oppressive and criminal
measures by the (Israeli) authorities against our brothers.''
   Tariq Aziz, Iraq's foreign minister, claimed Iran was aiding the
emigration of Iranian Jews to Israel, according to a text of his
remarks.
   In the statement about the rebellion, which began Dec. 8 in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, the ministers said: ``All
Moslems in the world are proud of this uprising.''
   That echoed a speech by King Hussein of Jordan at the opening of
the conference Monday, in which he said the ``blood of martyrs''
was being shed in the territories. More than 100 Arabs have been
killed since the violence began.
   The ministers declared: ``Members of the organization are
concerned to support Palestinians financially, politically and
morally and also to back their sole legitimate representative, the
PLO.''
   No indication was given of what form aid would take, or whether
there would be financial assistance, and the statement did not
elaborate.
   Tajer Masri, Jordan's foreign minister, told reporters: ``We can
only provide support in a political manner, to pressure the world's
nations to get them to pressure Israel and reveal the meaning of
the uprising. I don't remember seeing any request for financial
support.''
   Farouk Kaddoumi, the Palestine Liberation Organization's
equivalent of a foreign minister, said the statement was valuable
to the PLO and especially ``for the people inside the territories.''
   About U.S. plans to close the PLO's U.N. observer mission in New
York under terms of an anti-terrorist law, Kaddoumi said:
   ``We will keep the office open until American police come and
seal it off. Then we will go to the United Nations (headquarters)
and live there.''
   Aziz, the Iraqi foreign minister, said the alleged help given
Iranian Jews to move to Israel was ``a violation of the rules'' of
the Organization of Islamic Conference.''
   ``How come Iran, which claims to support the Palestinian issue
and the uprising, is helping Jews to migrate to Israel?'' There was
no elaboration in a text of his prepared remarks made available to
The Associated Press.
   He gave no figures on the number of alleged emigrants. The
Iranian envoy, Mohammed Ali Taskhiri, denied the claim and accused
Iraq of being ``Zionist.''
   The point is sensitive in the Arab and Moslem world because many
nations do not recognize Israel's right to exist and oppose the
emigration of Jews to the country.
</TEXT>
