<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Mecham 2ndLd-Writethru a0625 03-22 0794</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0625,0813</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Testimony Ends on First Charge in Mecham Impeachment Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs, early-vote motion withdrawn; picks up
10th graf: ``I never...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz.(AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Testimony ended today on the first of three
impeachment charges against Gov. Evan Mecham, but a move for a
quick vote on whether to oust Mecham from office was withdrawn in
the face of vehement opposition.
   ``It would be our everlasting disgrace if we do not consider all
of the evidence from both sides in such a historic and important
case,'' said Republican Sen. Jon Hays.
   After testimony ended on the first impeachment count, a charge
that Mecham tried to thwart an investigation into a death threat,
Democratic state Sen. Carolyn Walker proposed that the Senate
consider voting on that charge alone.
   The Senate had earlier agreed to hear evidence on all three
charges before voting on any one. Conviction on the first count
alone would have ended the trial early with the first term
Republican removed from office.
   ``I would think if Governor Mecham is exonerated he would be
extremely happy to know he has one less article to face,'' she
said. ``And if he is convicted, we should not go on and spend
untold dollars of taxpayers money.''
   In a heated debate, the motion won support from Democrats but
was opposed by Republicans, and Walker finally withdrew it. A
two-thirds vote of the 30-member Senate would have been required to
change the trial rules.
   The prosecution then said it was ready to begin presenting
evidence on the second charge against Mecham _ alleged that he
misused $80,000 from a state fund by loaning it to his auto
dealership.
   The last witness on the obstruction of justice count was
Mecham's lawyer, Fred Craft, who this morning seized the
opportunity to give a lengthy speech in praise of Mecham's
political philsophy. He called Mecham an ``uncommon politician''
who sought no personal aggrandizement and wanted only to improve
the quality of life in Arizona.
   The speech brought an objection from prosecutor Paul Eckstein
and Craft was instructed to stick to answering questions.
   Craft, in an abrupt role change, became a witness Monday and
said Mecham ``didn't know that he was obstructing anything'' when
he told the state's top lawman he would not cooperate with the
attorney general's investigation of the alleged death threat.
   Craft was subpoenaed at the request of the Democratic minority
leader, Sen. Alan Stephens. Craft was a Mecham insider when the
threat against a witness before a grand jury investigating Mecham
was reported to the governor on Nov. 13.
   ``I never heard `felony.' I never heard `death threat' and I
certainly never heard `tampering with a grand jury witness,'''
Craft said Monday. ``I never heard those words, which would have
been an alarm to me.''
   Later, in his cross-examination, Eckstein asked Craft whether he
had ever advised the embattled governor to resign.
   ``We had these meetings and no one could see a political escape
route for the governor,'' Craft said. ``No one was offering the
governor any other political option than to go down with the ship.''
   Thefirst charge alleged that Mecham tried to thwart the
investigation of the alleged death threat against former top Mecham
aide Donna Carlson by Mecham confidant Lee Watkins. At the time,
Ms. Carlson was about to testify before the state grand jury about
Mecham's failure to report a $350,000 campaign loan.
   The next article charges Mecham with misusing $80,000 from the
governor's protocol fund by loaning it to his auto dealership. The
third impeachment article accuses him of concealing the $350,000
campaign loan.
   Craft and co-defense counsel Jerris Leonard said they opposed
taking an early vote. ``We ought to hear all the evidence on all
three articles and then let them vote,'' Leonard said.
   In his testimony, Craft echoed Mecham in contending the governor
was not fully informed that the situation involved a felony and the
possible tampering of a grand jury witness.
   ``Nobody said the house is burning down, we've got a crisis,''
Craft said. ``I didn't know that a crime had been committed.''
   However, Sen. John Mawhinney, a Republican, noted that
then-chief of staff Richard Burke testified that he considered the
matter to be serious and that he assumed the Department of Public
Safety was investigating.
   ``What is mystifying is how two people can sit in the same
meeting'' and come away with different impressions, Mawhinney said.
   A two-thirds vote of the Senate is required to convict Mecham,
the first U.S. governor to be impeached in six decades and the
first ever in Arizona.
   Mecham also faces an April 21 criminal trial on charges of
concealing the $350,000 campaign loan, and a May 17 recall election.
</TEXT>
