<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 1400EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Mormons     03-22 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Mormons,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mormons Receive Permission To Build First Chapel In Poland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have granted Polish Mormons
permission to build their first chapel in this communist country, a
church missionary said Tuesday.
   The only other Soviet bloc country in which there are Mormon
chapels is East Germany, where there are about 5,000 members of the
Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints.
   Although Polish authorities registered the Mormon Church as an
official religious organization in 1977, only recently were there
enough Polish Mormons to warrant building a chapel, said Elder
Juliusz Fussek.
   Fussek, 66, a U.S. citizen of Polish descent, was sent to Poland
to do missionary work by the church headquarters in Salt Lake City.
He is a retired printer.
   There are only about 100 Mormons in this overwhelmingly Roman
Catholic country, but Fussek said he saw ``great prospects'' for
the church's development ``because people are interested in
religion here.''
   ``You need members first before building a chapel ... Because
there is no point having a chapel and it standing empty,'' said
Fussek.
   ``We are very pleased with the cooperation and help we have
received from the government,'' he said.
   At the end of last year, Polish Mormons applied for permission
to build a chapel and cultural-educational center in Warsaw's
western Wola district, Fussek said.
   The local council for Wola approved the project at a meeting
last week and forwarded its decision to the Warsaw city president
for formal approval, he said.
   Fussek said the chapel, expected to open in 1989 or 1990, would
be paid for by donations from Polish Mormons and the church
headquarters in Salt Lake City. He did not have any estimate of the
cost.
   Fussek said there were about 300-400 Mormons, mostly of German
descent, in the country before World War II. The Mormon chapel did
not reopen after the war because most of its members fled the
country when the Communists took power.
   More than 35 religious denominations are active in Poland today.
Ninety percent of Poland's 37 million people are baptized Catholics.
</TEXT>
