<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Pendleton-Rodino 1stLd-Writethru a0670 03-22 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pendleton-Rodino, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0670,250</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: Subs last graf to insert no comment from Rodino press
secretary</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the U.S. Civil Rights
Commission today gave an ``Uncivil Rights Award'' to the mayor of
Newark, N.J., for allegedly pressuring Rep. Peter Rodino into
retirement.
   Yielding to minority constituents, Rodino, who is white and a
Democrat, announced March 14 he would not seek a 21st term in
Congress. Minorities, who make up the bulk of Rodino's district,
have clamored for several years for a minority representative.
   At a news conference, civil rights commission chairman Clarence
Pendleton, who is black, said he was awarding an ``Uncivil Rights
Award'' to Newark Mayor Sharpe James, who is also black and who,
according to Pendleton, worked ``with several other Newark
politicians'' and ``pressured ... Rodino to retire from Congress.''
   ``The notion that Peter Rodino doesn't represent the people in
the 10th District is absurd,'' Pendleton said. ``They have elected
him to Congress 20 times, and continue to support his leading role
on civil rights issues. No matter. The Newark power brokers have
decided that he is not `their' representative _ he's just the wrong
color.''
   Pam Goldstein, a spokeswoman for James, said the mayor had not
been told of the ``award.'' But Ms. Goldstein said she doubted
James' would be bothered by criticism from Pendleton, whose own
civil rights record she termed a ``joke.''
   ``I would say it's an endorsement for what the mayor's doing in
this city,'' Ms. Goldstein said.
   Rodino's press secretary, Larry Spinelli, said he would have no
immediate comment on the matter.
</TEXT>
