<HEAD>Central American Events at a Glance</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS Nicaragua section to update with today's developments.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Central America Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a summary of developments Monday and today involving
Honduras, Nicaragua and the United States:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>HONDURAS:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Nicaragua on Monday withdrew its soldiers from the border but
the frontier remained tense, with Honduran patrols on the lookout
for any booby traps left behind by the Sandinistas.
   President Jose Azcona Hoyo said the 3,200 U.S. troops sent to
Honduras last week, after the Nicaraguan army was accused of
sending 2,000 men across the border in pursuit of Contras, may not
be needed much longer.
   However, the U.S. troops were to begin a new set of joint
maneuvers with the Honduran army today. On Monday, a U.S. Army
transport helicopter crashed while participating in a military
exercise and 10 soldiers were injured. Other helicopters evacuated
the soldiers for medical treatment.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NICARAGUA:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The Sandinista government, in its second day of peace talks with
Contra rebels, today proposed a 30-day truce, and the U.S.-backed
Contras said a cease-fire should last 45 days. The Nicaraguan
government proposal calls for the rebels to lay down their arms,
while the Contras said rebels should move into cease-fire zones
during the truce. On Monday, the two sides agreed to a battlefield
truce during the three days of the peace talks.
</TEXT>
