<HEAD>Police Find Six Missing Children</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs, children found; picks up 3rd graf pvs,
``The youngest child xxx</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ENCINITAS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today found six children
reported missing when the eldest child, a 13-year-old girl, drove
out of a parking lot while their foster parents were inside a
hospital.
   The children had been left in the van Monday while the couple
kept a doctor's appointment in San Diego, San Diego police Lt. Bill
Brown said today. A witness saw the teen-ager drive the van out of
the parking lot, Brown said.
   ``Everybody's safe. Everybody's in good health,'' said police
Sgt. Ron Brown.
   Investigators from the child abuse unit were going to talk with
the children, said police spokesman Bill Robinson.
   A determination will be made if the parents were ``remiss'' in
their actions, and where the children should be placed, Robinson
said. It is unlikely that any action will be taken against the
teen-ager, he said.
   Police Sgt. Roy Stamper said the girl had driven to a friend's
home in Encinitas, a seaside community about 20 miles north of San
Diego, and the younger children spent the night in the van outside
the house.
   The mother of the friend heard a news report about the missing
van and called sheriff's deputies.
   The children's names were not released.
   The youngest child, an 8-month-old baby, was described as
``medically fragile,'' Sgt. Dan Luth said. He did not know details
of the baby's condition.
   Two of the children are age 12. The others are 4 years and 19
months.
   Police alerted authorities in San Diego County to watch for a
yellow, California-registered 1978 Chevrolet van with red, black
and orange stripes. The license number was entered into a national
computer network of stolen cars.
   It was not known if the children had any money, Luth said.
   ``As far as we know, the foster parents took all the kids to
Kaiser Hospital where the father had to see doctor,'' Brown said.
``Apparently the children wanted to stay in the van, found the key,
and drove off.''
   He said it was at first assumed the driver would take the
children to her biological parents' house in Vista, but she did not.
</TEXT>
