<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica     03-22 0628</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa,0647</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Closes Anti-Apartheid Newspaper</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Tuesday shut
down the New Nation, a combative, church-backed anti-apartheid
newspaper, making it the first victim of a campaign to stifle
militant publications.
   The government ``has killed the messenger instead of listening
to the message.'' said Peter Soal, a Parliament member for the
liberal Progessive Federal Party.
   Home Affairs Minister Stoffel Botha, who has state-of-emergency
powers to censor publications singlehandedly, said in a special
decree that further issues of the black-oriented weekly newspaper
are ``totally prohibited'' through June 10.
   Another Cabinet minister, Stoffel van der Merwe, said the New
Nation was closed because it advocated violent overthrow of the
government and supported communism.
   ``It is absolutely astonishing that a publication issued under
the name of a Christian organization should act in this way,'' he
said.
   The closure came a day after the 2-year-old newspaper, published
by the Southern African Catholic Bishops Conference, lost a court
appeal seeking to postpone government action while it challenged
the censorship regulations.
   The New Nation technically could resume publication after three
months, but Botha could close it again if its contents in the
ensuing issues dissatisfied him.
   Bishop Reginald Orsmond, chairman of the newspapers' publishing
board, said the 22-member staff would be retained during the
suspension. He declined to predict would would happen to the paper
if the suspension was extended.
   Orsmond accused the government of ``suppressing the voice of the
people.''
   Authorities have banned four of the New Nation's editions and
seized two. Police have raided the paper's offices, and it was the
first of six publications warned by Botha that they could be closed
or forced to obey an in-house censor if they continued to publish
material he found objectionable.
   Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu, whose stepped-up political
activities in recent weeks have angered the government, described
the New Nation's closure as ``quite scandalous.''
   ``Only a government that is scared or already totalitarian, or
very close to totalitarian, behaves in the kind of way that ours
does,'' Tutu said.
   With a circulation of about 60,000, the New Nation is the
largest newspaper in South Africa to devote virtually its entire
content, including sports and entertainment pages, to politically
related developments.
   One regular feature was a learning section, ``to bridge the
deficiencies of apartheid education.'' In simple language, it told
readers about black activists not covered in school courses and
explained how to apply for a job, feed a baby nutritiously, treat
an injured riot victim or protect oneself from tear gas.
   The newspaper's editor, Zwelakhe Sisulu, has been detained
without charge for 16 months. He joined the New Nation after a year
as a Neiman Fellow at Harvard University.
   Sisulu's father, Walter, former secretary-general of the
now-outlawed African National Congress, is serving a life prison
term along with ANC leader Nelson Mandela for treason and sabotage.
   State-of-emergency regulations give Botha nearly unlimited
powers to deal with newspapers he feels might contribute to unrest.
Under the regulations, he does not have to give reasons for his
actions.
   The New Nation lost an initial court challenge of the
regulations and intends to pursue its case in an appellate court.
But on Monday, a Supreme Court rejected the newspaper's bid to
prevent closure during the appeal process.
   The last edition of the New Nation, on March 17, said the
government was ``bent on destroying what little freedom of
expression is left in a country where the majority are voteless.''
   ``Because the New Nation dared to act as their voice, it has now
been damned to silence,'' the paper said.
   The issue also carried a quotation from President P.W. Botha on
the front page: ``I believe in a free press and in free news
media.''
</TEXT>
