<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea-Corruption,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutors Begin Work in Corruption Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors on Tuesday opened an
investigation into fraud, influence peddling and financial scandals
allegedly involving the brother of former President Chun Doo-hwan.
   The Prosecutor General's Office said at least 10 officials have
been questioned in an investigation of whether Chun Kyung-hwan, a
younger brother of the former president, embezzled funds of the
Saemaul Undong development group.
   Top Saemaul officials are suspected of diverting private and
government subsidies to profit-oriented projects, land speculation
and other illegal activities.
   The former president left office Feb. 25 at the end of a
seven-year term. He left Tuesday on a private visit to the United
States, where he will meet President Reagan on Wednesday.
   President Roh Tae-woo, who succeeded Chun, has pledged to
eradicate abuses of power and corruption under previous
governments. In a recent move to reduce the ex-president's power,
Roh removed some Chun supporters from their posts.
   Some political observers say the Roh government opened the
investigation to disscredit the former president and improve the
current government's image.
   There have been allegations of corruption by the Saemaul group
since the former president seized power with military backing in
1980 and installed his brother as Saemaul head.
   The younger Chun resigned in 1987 after being linked to
gangsters.
   Prosecutor Kang Won-il said government officials also were being
investigated to see if they had assisted or protected corruption.
   ``My investigation team will unearth all malpractices and make
public the results of the probe,'' Kang told reporters.
   Dong-A Ilbo, an influential Seoul newspaper, said the younger
Chun was responsible for a sharp drop in cattle prices in 1983 when
he forced government officials to import cattle from the United
States.
   Saemaul was formed in 1971 to improve rural and urban living
standards, but critics contend the country's authoritarian
governments have used the movement to promote government influence.
   The Party for Peace and Democracy controlled by opposition
leader Kim Dae-jung charged that Roh also aided Saemaul officials
when he was a government minister in 1982.
   The opposition party demanded that Roh and other family members
of the former president be investigated.
</TEXT>
