<HEAD>Some Officials Worry Gang Film Could Lead to Trouble</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Recasts overline to reflect that city attorney saying film
reaction should be monitored, not necessary lead to trouble. Subs
lead to CORRECT by deleting `city.'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Colors,'' a movie about street gangs
starring Sean Penn and Robert Duvall, could prompt more street
warfare, some officials complain.
   ``The violence was certainly graphic, but no more graphic than
on the streets,'' City Attorney James Hahn said Monday, a day after
a private screening for the film, which uses real gang members as
extras and real gang names.
   ``It portrayed the dead end of getting involved in gangs,'' Hahn
said. ``It was a pretty depressing movie from that standpoint.''
   Gang violence has claimed more than 50 lives in Los Angeles
County this year.
   The Orion Pictures movie is scheduled for release April 15, and
anti-gang specialists fear violence could erupt at theaters if
rival gang members go to see it.
   ``It could create some problems,'' Hahn said. ``It's the kind of
thing we need to be concerned about and careful. We're just going
to wait and see and monitor the situation.''
   Sheriff's Sgt. Wes McBride, president of the California Gang
Investigators Association, said ``Colors'' glorified gangs at times.
   ``I'd be surprised if we don't have some people die because of
this movie,'' he said.
