<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 1452EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Scotus-Miranda     03-22 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Miranda,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Hears Case Examining Adequacy of Miranda Warning</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A warning advising suspects that they may
remain silent and are entitled to an attorney is not adequate to
protect their rights under the Constitution, the Supreme Court was
told on Tuesday.
   Donald Honchell, a Cook County, Ill., public defender appealing
the 1983 murder conviction of a gang member, said the ``Miranda
warning'' does protect a person from self-incrimination under the
Fifth Amendment.
   But he argued that, once a suspect is indicted, the warning
alone is not enough to protect the Sixth Amendment guarantee of
legal help.
   The Supreme Court is using the Illinois case to decide whether
the warnings that police have been required to give since 1966 are
adequate to advise suspects of their right to legal aid.
   It ruled in ``Miranda vs. Arizona'' that people accused of
crimes must be informed of their rights to remain silent, to have a
lawyer, to have counsel present during questioning and to receive
free legal assistance if needed.
   Honchell contended that even if a defendant has waived his
rights under Miranda, he has an automatic right to a lawyer as soon
as he is indicted and may not be asked from that point on to submit
to interrogation.
   ``There is a shield around the accused through which the police
cannot get a waiver,'' Honchell said. ``At no time after the
indictment should the police be allowed to go to the defendant,
seek a waiver and begin to question.''
   However, a prosecutor said authorities would be unfairly limited
if they cannot interrogate a defendant who is read his rights and
then agrees to speak without a lawyer present.
   Jack Donatelli, an assistant Cook County prosecutor, also said
the warning is perfectly understandable to defendants.
   ``They have a common-sense meaning that enables defendants to
understand they have both a right to counsel and that things could
go against them if they don't have a lawyer with them when they're
in custody and questioned,'' Donatelli said.
   Honchell said police coerced his client, Tyrone Patterson, 22,
of Evanston, Ill., into making incriminating statements by telling
him he had been indicted. But Donatelli said Patterson understood
his rights and agreed to be questioned anyway.
   Patterson, a member of the Vice Lords street gang, is serving a
24-year sentence at the Pontiac Correction Center for his
conviction in the Aug. 21, 1983 beating death of rival Black
Mobsters gang member James ``Pudge'' Jackson.
   According to court briefs, he was arrested on a misdemeanor
charge following a gang fight, received a ``Miranda warning'' and
signed a statement waiving his right to counsel.
   Two days later, after initially refusing to discuss Jackson's
death, Patterson was told he had been indicted, signed a second
Miranda waiver and agreed to answer questions, the briefs said.
</TEXT>
