<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     03-22 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hoosier taxpayers with a grudge can walk
into Union Station next month, pay a dollar and try to plunge an
Internal Revenue Service manager into the chilly waters of a
charity dunking booth.
   The dunking booth is part of ``Tax Bash,'' scheduled April 11-15
at the downtown train station. Proceeds from the event will benefit
the Muscular Dystrophy Association.
   During the evening hours, dry IRS employees will be on hand to
answer tax questions while their managers are taking the plunge.
H&R Block Inc. representatives will be available to prepare tax
returns, with a portion of the fee going to the MDA, and the U.S.
Postal Service will operate a special tax return drop-off box.
   ``We're billing it as one-stop shopping for taxes,'' Carolyn
Stumpf, IRS public affairs officer, said Tuesday.
   She said it didn't take any arm-twisting to get the IRS involved
in the fund-raiser.
   ``We thought that it's about time we show that we have a sense
of humor, and the fact that we can help another group of
individuals _ besides the tax-paying public _ so much the better,''
she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PARKER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The hot debate between mayoral and council
candidates in Parker is whether to use a 12-acre sodded area for
polo or soccer.
   ``This is the horsiest county in the United States. We have more
horses per person in our community than they do in Kentucky,'' said
Dean Salisbury, 66, mayor of this town of 700 about 15 miles
southeast of Denver.
   Voters will decide April 5 whether to retain Salisbury, the
town's first and only mayor, or replace him with one of two
challengers: Ann Waterman, 43, or Mark Lewis, 36.
   Seven people are running for the four open seats on the town
council, including three of the incumbents and four challengers.
   Salisbury, who has won ribbons as a carriage and sulky race
driver, takes credit for starting a regional park from 150 acres
dedicated to the town by developers, then cultivating about 12
acres into a low-cost ``utility field'' for soccer or softball.
   But he also hopes the grassy field can be used to host an annual
polo match to lure thousands of spectators to Parker as part of a
drive for economic development.
   The challengers say such schemes indicate Salisbury is a better
promoter than mayor and claim he has ignored the town's mundane
recreational needs.
</TEXT>
