<1ST_LINE>r a AM-EthanolDispute     03-22 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ethanol Dispute,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tiny Colorado School Battles Bureaucracy Over Ethanol</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KARVAL, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For years, Gayle E. Culberson has been
teaching kids at Karval High School how to make ethanol in a class
on energy conservation.
   But when the industrial arts teacher got a letter from the
Federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms saying his school
would have to pay $500 a year because it was a fuel alcohol
producer, he became a little upset.
   So Culberson did what ever civics teacher recommends: he wrote
his senator.
   Culberson wrote Sen. William Armstrong that the school could not
afford the tax and could lose its permit to produce fuel alcohol.
His class makes a few quarts a year, he said.
   Without the permit, he said, students in this eastern plains
community would miss an important lesson.
   ``At a time when it seems important to reduce foreign oil
imports, reduce pollution in our states, when education is
struggling to better itself with diminishing budgets, why was there
a tax of this nature levied on fuel alcohol plants and educational
facilities in particular?'' Culberson asked Armstrong.
   Armstrong has responded by drafting an amendment that would
exempt from the tax producers who make less than 10,000 gallons of
fuel alcohol per year.
   ``This is a classic case of the bureaucracy gone berserk,''
Armstrong said.
</TEXT>
