<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BladderCancer     03-22 0179</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bladder Cancer,0175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Experimental Treatment Avoids Surgery for Bladder Cancer
^Eds: For release at 6 p.m. EST, time set by source</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bladder cancer treatment that
avoids surgery has shown promising results in a preliminary study,
a scientist said Tuesday.
   Twenty-one of 36 patients who have completed the
drug-and-radiation therapy were found free of disease for three to
21 months, said George Prout, professor of surgery at Harvard
Medical School.
   Three others showed partial remission, while treatment failed
outright for nine patients. The other three were not evaluable, he
told science writers at a seminar sponsored by the American Cancer
Society.
   The study focused on patients whose cancers had invaded the
bladder muscle, a condition usually treated by surgically removing
the bladder, Prout said.
   If the bladder is removed, the patient must wear a bag to
collect urine for the rest of his life. It also essentially ends
sexual activity.
   The experimental treatment attacks liver cancer with radiation
to the pelvis, plus treatment with a mix of the drugs methotrexate,
velban and cis-platinum.
</TEXT>
