<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LetterTheft     03-22 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Letter Theft,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Post Office Tracks Suspected Thief to Navy Ship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suspected mail thief who changed his
identity was traced to a Navy warship in the Persian Gulf and was
arrested when the ship came home, investigators said.
   Postal Inspector J.A. McDonald obtained a warrant for the arrest
of Luke Lee McCall on July 10, 1986, on a charge that he took a
letter containing a $620 insurance check from someone else's post
office box.
   McCall, who otherwise had a clean record, began using the name
of Andre Darnell Robinson in order to avoid trial, said Stan Hills,
a deputy marshal in Jacksonville. He said McCall returned to
Chicago and enlisted in the Navy.
   After several months in the Persian Gulf on the USS Okinawa,
McCall was arrested Monday in Norfolk, Va., when the vessel docked.
   With no prior record, McCall probably wouldn't have received the
maximum penalty _ five years in prison and a $250,000 fine _ had he
gone to trial in 1986, Hill said.
   McCall, 28, was ordered held on $75,000 bond following his
appearance Monday before a U.S. magistrate in Virginia.
   McCall is scheduled to be arraigned April 4 in Jacksonville on
the federal mail charge, said Assistant U.S. Attorney Teresa
Wright. He also faces additional charges stemming from the use of a
false identity, she said.
   McCall had obtained a copy of Andre Robinson's birth certificate
and was using his Social Security number, officials said. Robinson,
who lives in Jacksonville, was not involved in the scheme.
   Under his assumed name, McCall married a woman in San Diego and
bought a car with a loan from the Navy credit union there, Hills
said.
</TEXT>
