<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Banham     03-22 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Banham,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reyner Banham, Architectural Critic, Dead at 66</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reyner Banham, an influential writer on
architecture and the arts, has died of cancer at the age of 66.
   The burly professor returned to London after more than 10 years
in the United States after developing cancer last year. He died
Saturday in London, his family said.
   Most recently, Banham taught art history at the University of
California for seven years.
   He was educated in Norwich, and at the beginning of World War
II, he began working at the Bristol Aeroplane Co. After the war, he
studied art history at London University's Courtauld Institute
while writing about contemporary architecture for The Architectural
Review.
   In 1959, he joined the staff of the review full-time, but five
years later, left for a teaching post at Bartlett University
College in London, where in 1969 he became professor of the history
of architecture.
   After enthusiastic U.S. reaction to his 1960 book, ``Theory and
Design in the First Machine Age,'' he moved to the United States in
1966 to teach at the University of Buffalo in New York. He moved to
California in 1980.
   He wrote two other widely studied books, ``The New Brutalism''
in 1966 and ``Architecture of the Well-Tempered Environment'' in
1969.
   Banham is survived by his wife, Mary, a son and a daughter.
</TEXT>
