<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Pendleton-Rodino     03-22 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pendleton-Rodino,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Civil Rights Chairman Blasts Newark Mayor's `Uncivil Rights'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the U.S. Civil Rights
Commission announced Tuesday that he was bestowing an ``Uncivil
Rights Award'' on the mayor of Newark, N.J., for pressuring Rep.
Peter Rodino, D-N.J., to retire because he is white.
   Chairman Clarence Pendleton, who is black, said that Rodino
receives the ``Victim of Uncivil Rights Award'' for the way in
which he was treated by ``Newark power brokers'' who have decided
that ``he is not their representative _ he's just the wrong color.''
   At a news conference where he criticized the Civil Rights
Restoration Act and the resignation under pressure of Gallaudet
University President Elisabeth Zinser, Pendleton said he was
instituting his own personal ``Uncivil Rights Award'' program in an
effort to highlight ``the absurdities committed in the name of
civil rights.''
   Pendleton's first recipient was Newark Mayor Sharpe James, who
is black. James has said the courts carved out Rodino's 10th
Congressional District more than 12 years ago to elect a minority
congressman, and that ``it's time to get that done.'' Pendleton
said James worked ``with several other Newark politicians'' in
pressuring Rodino to retire.
   Rodino announced March 14 that he would not seek a 21st term in
Congress. Minorities, who make up the bulk of Rodino's district,
have clamored for several years for a minority representative.
   ``Rodino has been pressured to retire so that a proper _ read
this black _ representative can be elected,'' said Pendleton. ``The
notion that Peter Rodino doesn't represent the people in the 10th
District is absurd. They have elected him to Congress 20 times, and
continue to support his leading role on civil rights issues.''
   James declined to respond to the criticism from Pendleton, said
Pam Goldstein, a spokeswoman for the mayor. ``I will not dignify
his comments with a response,'' she quoted James as saying.
   Rodino also declined comment, said spokesman Larry Spinelli.
   Pendleton said he would bestow his new awards ``as often as they
are properly earned _ perhaps once a month. If the Civil Rights
Restoration Act passes today over the president's veto, I suppose I
will have more than enough material.''
   Pendleton said the Civil Rights Restoration Act represents ``an
unwarranted invasion ... by Big Brother.''
   The statute forbids distribution of federal funds to entire
institutions, state and local government agencies and many
corporations if any part of them practices discrimination. It was
spurred by a 1984 Supreme Court ruling that civil rights laws
applied only to a specific program or activity receiving federal
aid.
   The head of the civil rights panel also said that one of his
candidates for a ``Victim of Uncivil Rights'' Award had been
Zinser, who was named the first woman president in the 124-year
history of Gallaudet University for the deaf, only to resign
following protests over the fact that she was not deaf.
</TEXT>
