<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 1622EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LionInfringement     03-22 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lion Infringement,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Car Dealer's Lions Raises Art Institute Roar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car salesman didn't think he'd be stepping on
any paws when he put a pair of seven-foot lion statues on the roof
of his auto dealership and advertised ``The Car Institute.''
   But a roar of sorts erupted from the Art Institute of Chicago,
which has lions guarding its entrance.
   ``I didn't think people would be confused,'' said Joe Levy Jr.,
the car dealer, who said Tuesday he had agreed to a compromise. ``I
don't know how much of their traffic we've been getting. I think
there's room for both of us.''
   The Art Institute contended ads for the ``Car Institute''
violated a museum trademark.
   ``We agreed to discontinue the `Car Institute,''' Levy said.
``But they've agreed to let us keep the lions'' on the building in
Evanston.
   Robert Mars, the Art Institute's vice president for
administrative affairs, said the advertising was the real problem.
To allow Levy to capitalize on the institution's image might allow
others to do the same, and in an offensive way, Mars said.
   ``I think it maybe sends a signal out to people who
all-too-frequently try to use images from our collection that
aren't terribly appropriate,'' he said.
   Mars said a mistake was made long ago when the museum did not
protect its copyright of the painting ``American Gothic'' by Grant
Wood. ``Now we can no longer say anything about how'' parodies use
the stern-faces farm couple, Mars said.
   Levy said he got the call from the museum attorney about a month
ago. Last week he had his fiberglass lions painted the colors of
nearby Northwestern University ``to help clear up the confusion.''
One is now white, the other purple.
   ``We hope they don't object,'' he said.
   Mars said the lions, even in purple and white, can stay.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
