<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 1630EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Palestinians     03-22 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Palestinians,0175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Palestinians Ordered Expelled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Palestinians who had sought
political asylum in Sweden were ordered expelled Tuesday for
undisclosed security reasons, a government official said.
   The order came after Prime Minister Ingvar Carlsson's government
met in a special session to consider their appeal against a ruling
by police and immigration authorities that they leave the country,
said Erik Lempert, a senior official of the Labor Ministry.
   A fifth Palestinian was granted a resident's visa for
humanitarian reasons, despite objections by the National Security
Police, Lempert said.
   He said the government normally granted asylum to stateless
Palestinians arriving from Lebanon since the 1982 Israeli invasion
of that country, but police objections ``weighed heavier'' in these
cases.
   One of the four was married to a Swedish woman expecting their
child in April.
   Lempert declined to specify the suspicions against the
Palestinians. Lawyers representing them were ordered not to
comment, but the attorneys were quoted by the national news agency
TT as saying they would appeal.
</TEXT>
