<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dole 2ndLd-Writethru a0675 03-22 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dole, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0675,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole Stand on Civil Rights Bill Fuzzy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with new Dole comment, subbing 2 grafs for 3rd graf
pvs, Earlier on</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential hopeful Bob Dole
campaigned in Wisconsin on Tuesday rather than return to Washington
for the Senate override vote of President Reagan's veto of civil
rights legislation, saying ``I wasn't needed.''
   Dole indicated both opposition and support for Reagan's veto of
the civil rights bill in a confusing series of statements.
   On a radio call-in show, Dole said he would vote to override the
veto if he were in Washington. But he added, ``If it were the
deciding vote, I would side with the president.''
   He later elaborated, saying the only reason he would vote to
sustain Reagan's veto would be to ``give (the White House) a chance
to rework the bill.'' In a speech to Milwaukee businessmen, Dole
said, ``That bill is not nearly as bad as advertised.''
   In Washington, his spokeswoman also issued a double-edged
statement. Dale Tate said Dole, Republican leader in the Senate,
``opposes the president on this issue'' and would like to reverse
the Supreme Court ruling that prompted the legislation. But she
said, ``If his vote were needed to sustain the veto, he would.''
   ``In principle he opposes the president,'' she said.
   The Democratic-controlled Senate had more than enough votes to
provide the two-thirds majority needed to override Reagan's veto,
with or without Dole, who was campaigning in Wisconsin in advance
of the state's April 5 Republican presidential primary.
   Vice President George Bush, the faraway front-runner for the GOP
nomination, announced on Monday that he supported Reagan's veto.
``I'm not going to start differing with the president after 7 1@2
years into the vice presidency,'' he said.
   Dole was criticized by Bush earlier in the campaign for failing
to take a clear-cut position on key issues such as tax increases
and arms control.
   And a variety of statements by Dole and allies left a confused
impression on the hotly debated civil rights bill.
   Sen. Alan Simpson, the GOP Senate whip, said he had been
authorized to say on the Senate floor that ``were he (Dole) present
and voting, he would vote to sustain the president's veto.''
   Dole himself issued a statement for the record which did not say
how he would vote.
   ``I have always supported legislation to overturn Grove City to
restore the broad civil rights coverage that existed prior to that
case,'' he said.
   ``At the same time, I recognize that (the Grove City bill) is
not a perfect bill. I am not fully satisfied with it... But the
fact remains that the administration and its congressional allies
had the opportunity to offer amendments and they were voted down.''
   The legislation stems from a 1984 Supreme Court ruling that says
that an organization receiving federal aid must follow
anti-discrimination rules only for the program that receives the
aid, and not for the entire organization or institution.
   The legislation would erase that distinction and require that an
entire organization follow the rules. Dole was absent when the
Senate passed the bill in January. Reagan vetoed the bill, saying
it was too broad and infringed on the activities of religious
groups, small buisnesses and others.
   Civil rights groups have strongly suppored the bill and favor
overriding Reagan's veto.

</TEXT>
