<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Unrest     03-22 0747</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0767</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nominal Legislature Appeals for Calm, Protests Continue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union on Tuesday increased official
pressure on Armenia and Azerbaijan to halt ethnic unrest that has
left at least 32 people dead.
   The Tass news agency said the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet of
the Russian federation, the nation's largest republic, and
equivalent bodies in the Ukraine, Byelorussia, Georgia and
Uzbekistan called on the national parliament to take firm action to
end the tension.
   The moves came amid increasingly negative coverage in the
official press of Armenian demands to annex the predominantly
Armenian Nagorno-Karabakh region, which is part of neighboring
Azerbaijan and the reported arrest of a leading Armenian
nationalist.
   Tamara Grigoryants, wife of Armenian-born dissident Sergei
Grigoryants, said in an interview that Paryur Arikyan was arrested
Tuesday evening by three policemen in central Moscow after meeting
with a Western journalist.
   She said Arikyan was accused of crossing the street illegally,
and that he informed her of his arrest by calling from a pay
telephone as the policemen stood by. Arikyan said Saturday he had
traveled clandestinely to Moscow after his passport was confiscated
in Armenia.
   The government newspaper Izvestia on Tuesday criticized Armenian
activists who it said gathered almost 4,000 people for a meeting in
Yerevan on March 19 to devise strategy to press their demands.
   On Monday the Communist Party newspaper Pravda charged the
Armenians' campaign has a ``clear anti-socialist spirit.''
   Ethnic rioting broke out in Sumgait, a Azerbaijani city, after
Armenians began protesting last month for annexation of
Nagorno-Karabakh. Officials say 32 people were killed, but Armenian
activists say the death toll was much higher and that most of the
dead were Armenians killed by Azerbaijanis.
   The Russian federation expressed ``concern and alarm'' over the
ethnic unrest and asked the Presidium of the national Supreme
Soviet, the country's nominal parliament, to ``adopt resolute
measures aimed at ... uniting in all ways the Soviet peoples.''
   The Soviet constitution says little about the rights of
autonomous regions such as Nagorno-Karabakh, but says the territory
of a republic such as Azerbaijan or Armenia may not be changed
without its consent. That means Azerbaijan would have to approve
the annexation of Nagorno-Karabakh to Armenia.
   Under Soviet law, each of the country's 15 republics is
ostensibly sovereign. But the appeals from the five Soviet
republics about Nagorno-Karabakh seemed designed to serve as a
reason for the national government in Moscow to act on the
simmering territorial dispute.
   The policy-making Central Committee of the Communist Party
rejected the demand for annexation on Feb. 20, but Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev promised on Feb. 26 that the issue would be
considered when the Central Committee holds another meeting to
discuss national disputes.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov told a regular
news briefing that protests continued in Armenia on Sunday and
Monday. A nationalist source said Armenians would gather again in
their capital of Yerevan on Saturday to decide whether to call a
general strike.
   Gerasimov said the situation in Azerbaijan and Armenia still is
too tense to allow foreign journalists to travel there.
   ``A curfew is still in effect in Sumgait, although the situation
there is regarded as absolutely normal,'' Gerasimov said. ``In
Armenia I wouldn't call it normal because there are demonstrations
going on and that's not normal.''
   Arikyan told The Associated Press on Monday that 7,000 people
had gathered in Yerevan to protest the Pravda article published
earlier that day criticizing the movement to annex Nagorno-Karabakh.
   At a Tuesday news conference in Moscow before his reported
arrest, Arikyan, 38, a former political prisoner, read what he said
was the text of a telegram from Armenian journalist Y. Arakyelan to
Pravda Editor Viktor G. Afanasyev.
   According to Arikyan, the correspondent said the article was an
``editor's article expressing the will of the Communist Party
Central Committee,'' rather than the views of those whose names
were attached to it.
   Arikyan, chairman of an Armenian nationalist group called
Alliance for National Determination, said the Pravda article was an
indication that authorities will not agree to unite
Nagorno-Karabakh with Armenia, despite appeals from local Communist
Party and government officials.
   Arikyan once headed an underground Armenian nationalist group
called the National Unification Party, and was jailed for 17 years
beginning in 1969 for his political activities.
   He said Armenian activists in Yerevan claim 78 people were
killed in Sumgait. But, he said, ``I think a worse tragedy than
Sumgait awaits us.''
</TEXT>
