<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Capitalism     03-22 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Capitalism,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Representative in Hong Kong Praises `Modern Capitalism'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist China's chief representative in Hong
Kong was quoted Tuesday as praising modern capitalism as a ``great
creation of human civilization.''
   Xu Jiatun's comments appeared in the pro-Beijing Wen Wei Po
newspaper, which ran the text of an interview he gave with a
Chinese magazine, and appeared aimed at boosting confidence in Hong
Kong after 1997, when China takes over the capitalist territory.
   ``We have some comrades who always fear capitalism, but in fact
they don't understand that the modern capitalist system is a great
creation of human civilization,'' said Xu, who as head of the
Xinhua News Agency branch is China's chief representative in Hong
Kong.
   The Xinhua official was quoted as saying China ``should
systematically absorb the beneficial experience and knowledge from
modern capitalism,'' which he praised for guaranteeing an
enivronment of free competition, allowing production forces to
develop, and creating a good legal system.
   ``In the past, we believed capitalism would quickly die out,''
Xu was quoted as saying. ``Looking from today's perspective, modern
capitalism has a lot of room to develop.''
   China's Communist Party last year reaffirmed its commitment to
opening up the country and pushing market-oriented reforms to
stimulate the economy.
   Xu's comments not only indicated strong support for reform but
also appeared designed to allay fears about what will happen to
this bastion of capitalism after China takes over in 1997.
   Much of Hong Kong's well-educated middle class are seeking to
move overseas before the territory reverts to Chinese rule, even
though Beijing has promised the territory can retain its capitalist
economic system and enjoy ``a high degree of autonomy.''
   But many of Hong Kong's 5.7 million people are refugees from
political campaigns in Communist China and remain pessimistic. Xu
acknowledged they have ``a kind of distrust of the Communist Party,
which is completely understandable.''
   He said residents will be allowed to criticize the Communist
Party and socialism after 1997, but will be asked to ``love China
and love Hong Kong.''
   ``This is what we call `one country, two systems,''' Xu was
quoted as saying. ``This will benefit China's cooperation with
every circle of people in Hong Kong, especially the middle class.''
</TEXT>
