<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--President Expenses,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel Approves Funds For Reagan And President-Elect</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bill authorizing $3.5 million in
transitional expenses for President Reagan's successor and $1
million for Reagan to move to retirement in California next January
was approved Tuesday by the House Government Operations Committee.
   The Democratic-controlled committee rejected a Republican move
to increase the expense allowance for the outgoing president to
$1.5 million from $1 million, the level in effect since 1976, to
offset the effects of inflation.
   The proposed boost was opposed by Rep. Jack Brooks, D-Texas, the
panel's chairman, who said the budget squeeze requires Congress to
``make some hard choices'' on spending cuts.
   The panel approved raising the president-elect's allowance for
transitional expenses to $3.5 million from $2 million, the level in
effect for the past 12 years. It also rejected, 24-9, a move by
Rep. Robert S. Walker, R-Pa., to forbid the president-elect from
accepting private donations to supplement federal transitional
funds.
   The $1 million for Reagan's initial retirement expenses, if
approved by the House and Senate, would cover his moving expenses
from the White House to California and the costs of establishing an
office for six months, until funds for former presidents become
available under a separate law.
</TEXT>
