<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MilitaryRecruiting     03-22 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Military Recruiting,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Concerned by Dip in Reinlistments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military services had no problem meeting
their recruiting goals last last year, but there were ``some
adverse signs'' for the future in lower re-enlistment results, the
Pentagon said Tuesday.
   Releasing its latest quarterly report, the Defense Department
said the Army, Navy, Air Force and Marine Corps signed up 66,300
recruits during the first quarter of fiscal 1988, which ended Dec.
31.
   That compares with a combined goal of 65,400, and all four
services met or exceeded their individual quarterly objectives, the
Pentagon said.
   Moreover, the percentage of first-time enlistees with a high
school diploma actually increased slightly _ from 92 percent during
the period in fiscal 1987 to 93 percent in fiscal 1988.
   ``Retention (re-enlistment) results for the first quarter of
fiscal 1988 were also satisfactory, but with some adverse signs,''
Grant S. Green Jr., assistant defense secretary for manpower, said
in a statement.
   ``First-term re-enlistment rates trailed comparable fiscal 1987
statistics for three of the four services. And while overall career
retention rates showed some improvement over fiscal 1987, retention
among second-term and career Navy petty officers continued to
decline after falling short of objectives last year.''
   The Pentagon pays particular attention to the percentage of men
and women willing to re-enlist after completing their initial
obligation, viewing it as a measure not only of military readiness
and experience in the force but also job satisfaction.
   According to the latest report, 46 percent of military personnel
eligible to re-enlist for the first time during the period did so _
down from 49 percent during the comparable period in fiscal 1987.
   Some of the individual service declines, however, were much more
precipitous. For example, the Air Force's first term re-enlistment
rate dropped from 74 percent to 62 percent over the year.
   The Marine Corps' rate dropped from 24 percent to 18 percent,
and the Navy's rate fell from 56 percent to 51 percent. The Army
managed to buck the trend with a small increase, from 40 percent in
fiscal 1987 to 43 percent this fiscal year.
   Green noted that various re-enlistment bonus programs had been
suspended for 65 days during the period awaiting congressional
action.
   ``But most retention measures have fallen several percentage
points below their 1983-84 peaks, and this trend has been
particularly noticeable among personnel in higher-technology skills
that are in particular demand in the private sector,'' he added.
   Meanwhile, Dan Howard, the Pentagon's chief spokesman, restated
the administration's strong opposition to a cut in the 4.3 percent
pay raise proposed for military personnel in fiscal 1989, which
begins Oct. 1.
   The 4.3 percent hike exceeds the 2 percent proposed for civilian
government workers and some congressional leaders are now arguing
military and civilian workers should be treated the same.
   ``The comparability studies ... show an 11 percent gap between
military and civilian pay,'' Howard said. ``The 4.3 percent pay
raise is fully justified unless we want to return to the situation
that we saw in the past where the disparity was so great that good
people couldn't afford to stay in the military.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880322-0173 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 1628EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-LiverCancer 1stLd-Writethru a0705 03-22 0608</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Liver Cancer, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0705,0617</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plant May Reduce Liver Cancer in Hepatitis Virus Carriers, Study
Suggests^
^Eds: Subs 2nd graf bgng ``The trends'' to explain why woodchucks
used in study.</HEAD>
<NOTE>For release at 6 p.m. EST.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Extracts of a tropical plant appeared
to reduce levels of hepatitis virus and liver cancer rates in
woodchucks, a hopeful sign for the world's 200 million human
virus-carriers at risk for the cancer, a scientist said Tuesday.
   The trends emerged in analysis of data on about 60 animals that
had become infected with the woodchuck version of the hepatitis B
virus, said Baruch Blumberg of the Fox Chase Cancer Center in
Philadelphia. Woodchucks are used in hepatitis research because the
virus they carry so closely resembles the human hepatitis B virus.
   Blumberg stressed that the results are only suggestive, and a
prelude to a formal study of the plant extract's effects.
   ``Even if it doesn't get rid of the virus altogether, it may
still be useful,'' he said after speaking to science writers at a
seminar sponsored by the American Cancer Society.
   That is because the virus now can lie dormant for decades after
infection, and if the extract can extend that period, it may
essentially block the progression to liver cancer until after a
person has died of something else, he said.
   Infection with hepatitis virus B has long been linked to later
development of cancer originating in the liver, as opposed to
cancer that starts elsewhere in the body and spreads to the liver.
   Studies in Taiwan have found that male carriers of the virus run
more than 200 times the risk of developing liver cancer than
non-carriers, giving them a 40 percent chance of dying from the
disease, Blumberg said.
   The cancer is particularly common in Asia and sub-Saharan
Africa, he said. In the United States, the cancer society expects
about 6,000 new cancers of the liver this year.
   The best way to deal with the problem is vaccination at birth
for people at risk of the disease, Blumberg said. Such a vaccine is
not recommended for the American population generally because the
overall risk is so low, he said.
   China and Taiwan have programs for vaccinating newborn children,
he said. His institution has established a vaccine program in
Philadelphia directed at newborn children of carrier mothers and
others in their household. He said he hopes other such programs
will be established.
   But the world already has about 200 million carriers of the
virus, and more will be added every day until vaccination programs
become fully effective, he said.
   The plant, called Phyllanthus ammarus, grows in India and
throughout the tropical world, Blumberg said. It can be grown in
the United States, he said.
   The extract of the plant appears to fight the virus by blocking
a substance called DNA polymerase that the virus needs to reproduce
itself, he said.
   When the extract was injected into the bellies of woodchucks
infected for a month, evidence of the virus disappeared, he said.
Those infected longer showed decreases in the amount of virus in
their blood.
   Treated animals also developed significantly fewer liver cancers
than others, Blumberg said.
   Limited studies in animals suggest the extract does not cause
significant side effects, he said. Scientists are trying to isolate
the portion of the extract that fights the virus, he said.
   Raymond Koff, a liver disease specialist and professor of
medicine at Boston University, said the work should be followed up
with more study. ``Innovative, exciting stuff has to be looked
at,'' he said in a telephone interview.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880322-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 1741EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChemicalFire     03-22 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chemical Fire,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gas Distributor In Fatal Explosion Issues Nationwide Warning</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY HEIGHTS, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gas distribution company has
warned customers nationwide that cylinders of silane gas may have
been contaminated the same way as one that exploded, killing three
people, officials said Tuesday.
   Liquid Carbonic Industries Corp. of Chicago issued the warning
Monday that the cylinders of silane may have been contaminated with
an unstable oxidizer, said Dewey Erzinger, the company's director
of public relations.
   Erzinger said he could not estimate the number Liquid Carbonic
customers across the country, but said most are in the electronics
industry. The company manufactures industrial and medical gases,
such as silane, which is widely used to coat silicon wafers.
   Erzinger said company officials are investigating the origin of
the cylinder that exploded Thursday at the Gollob Analytical
Services plant, killing three people and seriously injuring a
fourth.
   The state Department of Environmental Protection has tentatively
traced the cylinder _ believed to contain a volatile mixture of
nitrous oxide and silane _ through three states before it reached
Berkeley Heights.
   The exact cause of the blast remains unknown, say officials with
the DEP and Liquid Carbonics.
   In its note to its customers, Liquid Carbonic said the explosion
may have been caused by some kind of oxidizer being drawn back into
the cylinder.
   ``If your process utilizes silane gas product in conjunction
with oxidizers, such as nitrous oxide or oxygen, you are urged to
make certain that oxidizers cannot be drawn back into your silane
gas container,'' the notice said.
   Meanwhile Tuesday, Liquid Carbonic completed removal of 300
cylinders of silane from its Harrison plant, Erzinger said. He said
the company may conduct similar removals at other plants around the
country.
   On Monday, nearly 1,000 workers were held off their jobs on the
San Francisco Peninsula after canisters containing potentially
explosive chemicals were discovered at semiconductor facilities
there.
   Chemical inspectors eventually concluded that the four canisters
at Advanced Micro Devices Inc. in Santa Clara and Teledyne
Semiconductor in Mountain View were harmless.
   A similar precautionary evacuation took place Sunday in
Pocatello, Idaho, when officials of the Gould Inc.'s semiconductor
plant examined silane cylinders belonging to Liquid Carbonic.
   One of the men killed in Thursday's blast, Dennis Feeney, was a
regional manager for Liquid Carbonic at the company's Harrison
facility. The two others killed were Gollob employees.
   A Liquid Carbonic deliveryman, James Diemer, lost a leg and
suffered shrapnel wounds. He was in fair condition Tuesday in the
plastic surgery ward of Bellevue Hospital Center in Manhattan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
