<2ND_LINE>AM-Gore, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0708,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore Finally Gets Visit With Cuomo</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: ADDS 6 grafs to UPDATE with Gore in Connecticut</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOEL STASHENKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr. got the meeting he'd
sought with New York Gov. Mario Cuomo on Monday, but he got no
endorsement for his presidential bid despite complimentary words
from the governor.
   ``He's very bright,'' Cuomo said of Gore. ``He's very deep in
his knowledge of government. ... He has a particular kind of appeal
that's especially attractive to the Democratic Party at this
moment.''
   But Cuomo said he and Lt. Gov. Stan Lundine are not ready to
publicly back a candidate. He said of Gore, ``It was nice of him to
come by.'' But he added that during their private meeting at the
state Capitol, ``Sen. Gore said nothing that I haven't heard him
say before.''
   Gore had tried to arrange a meeting with Cuomo early last month
in Albany but couldn't. Cuomo said Gore had asked to stop at the
Capitol again Monday as part of a campaign trip through New York in
advance of the state's April 19 primary. Gore also campaigned in
Connecticut Monday.
   ``Of course, I asked for his support and we talked about his
desire to play the most constructive role possible in helping the
country and helping the Democratic party win a victory in
November,'' Gore said. The Tennessee senator said they also
discussed problems New York and other states are wrestling with
such as housing, the homeless and AIDS.
   Gore rose to third place in the battle for nominating delegates
by winning five Southern states in the Super Tuesday primaries on
March 8.
   Cuomo said the Democratic race between front-runners Michael
Dukakis, Jesse Jackson and Gore has created a ``confused picture
politically.''
   ``We're _ Stan Lundine and I _ now accelerating the process of
trying to determine how best to be useful to the Democratic
Party,'' Cuomo said. ``Maybe we'll go beyond that and endorse
somebody. We'll know within a couple of weeks.''
   The fact that Cuomo has yet to endorse any Democratic candidate,
coupled with his refusal to rule out accepting a draft for the
nomination if there should be a deadlocked national convention, has
kept alive the speculation that he might be angling for the
nomination. Howver, Cuomo says he is not a candidate for president
this year.
   Later Gore, in a quick swing through Connecticut, predicted he
would do well in the state's Democratic presidential primary next
Tuesday despite Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis' strong regional
appeal here.
   ``I'm extremely optimistic that we're going to do very well
here, in spite of the fact that it's in the backyard of one of my
opponents,'' Gore said during a brief stop at an office building
construction site outside of Hartford.
   ``We're going to surprise some people here,'' Gore said.
   Gore expressed hope that Connecticut Gov. William A. O'Neill
would make an endorsement soon, rather than remaining uncommitted
until the Democratic convention in Atlanta in July.
   ``I'd love to have the governor's endorsement and I've asked him
for his support,'' Gore said. ``But I certainly understand why he
wants to take a close look at the race and think about it some
more.''
   Gore praised O'Neill lavishly, calling him ``a tremendous
leader'' who's done ``an outstanding job as governor.''
</TEXT>
