<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Iran-Contra-Pardons     03-22 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra-Pardons,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Refuses To Discuss North Pardon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan refused Monday to discuss a
possible pardon for former White House aide Oliver North, and a
presidential spokesman said North's lawyer had not contacted the
administration about the matter.
   In response to a reporter's question at the end of a ceremony to
sign an Afghanistan Day proclamation, Reagan replied, ``Not going
to discuss that now.''
   Separately, presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater repeated the
administration's oft-stated position that ``there's been no
discussions of pardons.''
   He also said that the administration has not been contacted by
North's attorney, Brendan Sullivan, who has been saying publicly
that testimony may be sought from the highest officials of
government.
   ``The president will cooperate but we'll just have to wait and
see what the format takes,'' Fitzwater said.
   North was indicted last week by a federal grand jury on charges
he conspired to divert Iranian arms sales profits to the Nicaraguan
Contra rebels.
   Earlier Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, said Reagan should pardon
North. He said North had been guilty of misleading Congress but did
not intend to break the law.
   ``I continually ask the question, where's the venality, where's
the corruption, where's the criminal intent?'' Hatch said on ``CBS
This Morning.'' ``I don't think anybody who watched Oliver North
believes that he intended to break the law or that he intended to
be a criminal.''
   Asked if North had misled Congress, Hatch said, ``That's true.
But keep in mind Oliver North saw his buddies get killed in
Lebanon. He found the terrorists who had killed them through leaks.
... He was the fellow who helped plan the the Grenada invasion. He
was the fellow who captured the Achille Lauro terrorists through
leaks.''
   ``You go on right down the line. ... I think that he was a hero
then, he's a hero today and I think we ought to get this behind us
and I think a pardon would be the appropriate way to do that,''
Hatch said.
   However, Rep. Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., who also served on the
committees that investigated the Iran-Contra affair, said the
courts should decide the guilt or innocence of North and former
national security adviser John M. Poindexter, who also was indicted.
   ``For the president to pre-emptively pardon them in advance I
think would send a terrible signal to the country about the
even-handedness and objectivity of our legal system. Remember they
are all assumed innocent,'' Foley said on the CBS program.
</TEXT>
