<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RacialCase     03-22 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Racial Case,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two May Avoid Prison in Federal Civil Rights Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men have been given a chance to avoid
federal prison terms for their role in a racially motivated fight
that resulted in the death of a Mexican-American farm worker five
years ago.
   Walter Pringle, 35, who faced a maximum 15-year federal prison
term, was sentenced Monday to 33 months in prison and assessed
$4,450 in fines, costs and restitution. Federal Judge G. Kendall
Sharp said Pringle would not have to go to prison if he can pay the
money by Sept. 1.
   Pringle was found guilty in January of violating the civil
rights of Joseph Ozuna, 26, by beating him unconscious near
Seville, a town of about 650 residents 60 miles north of here.
   Sharp also sentenced Mark Miller, 25, to 12 months in prison.
Sharp said he would suspend that sentence if Miller could pay
$1,500 in fines and restitution by Sept. 1. Miller had pleaded
guilty to conspiracy and testified for the government in the
January trial.
   Both he and Miller said later they would raise the money for the
fines and stay out of prison.
   A federal jury acquitted Pringle's ex-girlfriend, Paula Hires
Smith, 29, of violating the civil rights of Gilberto Garza, 17, by
shooting him to death in the same fight.
   The 1983 case triggered controversy when Pringle received a
six-month jail sentence, a $15 fine and five years probation after
pleading no contest to aggravated assault and battery, and Ms.
Smith was given 10 years probation for her no-contest plea to
manslaughter.
   Outrage over what were considered to be light sentences in the
state circuit court criminal case led to a federal investigation
and the January trial on civil rights charges in U.S. District
Court in Orlando.
   According to the federal indictment and information from Miller,
Pringle and Ms. Smith pursued cousins Ozuna and Garza into the
countryside. While Pringle was beating up Ozuna, Ms. Smith shot
Garza in the face with a rifle.
   ``I have been handing down sentences for 10 years, and I think
without doubt this is the most difficult case I ever had in terms
of meting out a sentence,'' Sharp told Pringle.
   But, the judge said, ``I am convinced that you will never do
anything like this again.''
   Pringle had contended that drinking got him into fights, and the
judge agreed, adding that only Pringle knows whether he is really
prejudiced against Mexican-Americans.
</TEXT>
