<HEAD>Four Killed in Fire Started by Children Playing with Matches</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three children and their mother died
Tuesday morning when the children set fire to their house while
playing with matches, authorities said.
   The deaths follow a rash of similar fires here in recent months.
   Kevin Reardon, who heads a program aimed at preventing children
from starting fires, said 11 children have been killed in the last
four months in fires they started.
   Fire Battalion Chief David Zwayer identified the victims of
Tuesday's fire as Patty Compton, 36, and three of her children:
Joshua, 1, Jennifer, 4, and Cassandra, 5. All were dead at the
scene, officials said.
   A fourth child, Tanya Compton, 7, and a woman identified as a
family friend, Dorleen Wilson, 32, escaped the fire, Zwayer said.
   Police said the children were lighting matches and set fire to a
couch. According to witnesses, Ms. Compton went outside, but
returned to the house in an attempt to save her children.
   ``You (could) hear them crying and calling for their mom, and
then their mom went into the house,'' said witness Lakisha Glasco,
12.
   On Sunday, four children ages 10 and younger were killed when
fire struck their home. A fifth child survived and was in poor
condition Tuesday in Children's Hospital.
   Fire officials said they believe that fire also was caused by a
child playing with matches.
