<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CoastGuardCuts     03-22 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Coast Guard Cuts,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yost Warns of More Coast Guard Closings Without Increased Funds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More Coast Guard installations would be forced
to close next year if Congress fails to increase the agency's
budget by $300 million, the head of the Coast Guard said Tuesday.
   ``These are not intended as threats or scare stories; these are
the real choices that we face,'' Adm. Paul A. Yost Jr., commandant
of the Coast Guard, told a House subcommittee.
   Yost said the Reagan administration's proposed fiscal 1989
funding level of $2.98 billion would not enable the Coast Guard to
reopen any of the nearly 30 stations and offices closed in February
because of a $103 million shortfall in the current budget.
   But Yost said the administration's proposal would allow the
remaining stations to stay open. In addition, it would restore to
full levels drug patrols, which were reduced by 55 percent last
month, and routine search and rescue patrols, which were eliminated.
   If Congress approved a budget with only modest increases from
1988, the agency would have a $171 million shortfall next year that
would trigger a more serious round of station closings, Yost said.
   ``I can't even come up with a list of Coast Guard (facilities)
that could be closed,'' he said.
   Rep. Earl Hutto, D-Fla., chairman of the House Merchant Marine
and Fisheries subcommittee on the Coast Guard and navigation,
embraced the administration's budget proposal as ``the minimum
necessary for the Coast Guard to continue to function in the manner
expected of it by the Congress and the American public.''
   Hutto and Yost said while the 1989 budget request is a big jump
from current spending levels, it really would just be bringing the
Coast Guard up to past levels.
   When adjusted for inflation, the budget request for the next
fiscal year is about the same as the 1983 spending levels. However,
the Coast Guard since has increased its drug interdiction
activities substantially.
   The congressional General Accounting Office found that from 1980
to 1987, the proportion of Coast Guard operating expenses devoted
to drug operations more than tripled _ from 7 percent to 22 percent.
   Meanwhile, the percentage devoted to more traditional Coast
Guard duties, such as search and rescue patrols and marine safety,
has been sliced from 60 percent to 51 percent, the GAO said.
   Last week, Yost unveiled an administration plan to transer $60
million from other Transportation Department accounts to the Coast
Guard to immediately upgrade patrol levels to last year's levels.
</TEXT>
