<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ForeignCrews     03-22 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Foreign Crews,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Bars Foreign Transportation Workers During Strikes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreigners would be barred from working as
crew members aboard U.S. aircraft and ships during strikes against
the carriers, under legislation approved, 302-114, by the House on
Tuesday.
   The restrictions would apply only to American-owned planes or
ships that are entering or leaving the United States.
   Supporters of the legislation said the measure would protect the
rights of striking American workers by preventing companies from
hiring foreigners to replace them.
   ``Aliens should not be allowed to hurt American employees by
working in their jobs as strike-breakers,'' said Rep. Marge
Roukema, R-N.J., the measure's sponsor.
   Opponents said the bill would hurt carriers by forcing them to
release foreign employees in the event of a labor walkout, and
would invite retaliation by other countries.
   ``It is easy to be against foreign nationals,'' said Rep. Steve
Bartlett, R-Texas.
   The legislation was written in response to a 1986 strike against
Trans World Airlines Inc. by its flight attendants in which the
workers accused TWA of using foreigners to serve on trans-Atlantic
flights.
   The bill was sent to the Senate.
</TEXT>
