<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 1944EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AIDS-GovernmentWorkers     03-22 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS-Government Workers,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Calls New Guidelines `Reasonable'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newly issued guidelines for dealing with
federal employees infected with the AIDS virus are in line with the
general anti-discrimination recommendations of the government's
health department.
   ``We worked very closely with the Office of Personnel Managment
in developing them,'' Dr. Robert Windom said Tuesday. ``The
regulations are reasonable and reflect PHS concerns.''
   Windom, No. 2 official of the Department of Health and Human
Services, heads the seven-agency Public Health Service that
includes the Centers for Disease Control, Food and Drug
Administration and National Institutes of Health.
   Windom will review the guidelines Thursday with personnel
officers from about 30 major federal agencies.
   ``The federal government, as an enlightened and compassionate
employer concerned with the health and welfare of its employees,
has an obligation to show the way in addressing the realities of
the AIDS epidemic,'' Constance Horner, director of the Office of
Personnel Management, said in a memo accompanying the guidelines'
initial distribution this week.
   Quoting from CDC statements on AIDS in the workplace, the
personnel office memo says, ``The kind of nonsexual
person-to-person contact that generally occurs among workers and
clients or consumers in the workplace does not pose a risk for
transmission of AIDS.''
   The guidelines instruct federal agencies to treat AIDS-infected
employees ``in the same manner as employees who suffer from other
serious illnesses'' and say there is ``no medical basis for
employees refusing to work with such fellow employees or agency
clients.'
   Fellow employes who disrupt agency functions by refusing to work
with an AIDS-infected person could be subject to ``appropriate
corrective or disciplinary action'' under the guidelines.
   AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is a contagious
disease that attacks the body's immune system, rendering it
incapable of resisting other diseases and infections.
</TEXT>
