<DOCNO> AP880322-0183 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 1919EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SubwaySale     03-22 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Subway Sale,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Free Market Flourishes Fleetingly In Brooklyn</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For a few fleeting weeks, free enterprise
thrived in Brooklyn.
   That was back in the good old days, about two months ago, when a
thrifty commuter entering the Greenpoint Avenue subway station in
the morning could buy a $1 subway ride for 50 cents.
   The bargain was offered by three crafty entrepreneurs, who
discovered the key to a padlocked gate next to a turnstile. They
unlocked the gate, put the padlock on the turnstile and went into
competition with the New York City Transit Authority.
   From about 5 a.m. to 7 a.m. weekdays, the subway station was
turned into a bargain basement, according to an account in
Tuesday's New York Newsday.
   And then the police found out.
   ``AS OF 2-15 FARE FOR RIDER WILL BE 55 CENTS PER PERSON,'' read
a flyer handed to riders shortly after the police crackdown. ``AND
NO PENNIES WILL NOT BE ACCEPTED NO MORE. ... PEOPLE WE HAD RUN IN
WITH TRANSIT POLICE SO THAT WHY WE RAISE IT. WE COULDN'T AFFORD OF
GETTING BUSTED.''
   The flyer ended on a promotional note: ``CATCH THAT FARE
SPECIAL.''
   ``It became amusing,'' observed Transit Police Sgt. Tom
Sullivan, still slightly astonished by this flowering of the
entrepreneurial spirit. ``Because we arrested them, they increased
the fare.''
   The police had been notified by an irate token clerk, who
arrived with a uniformed police officer each morning at 7 a.m. to
find her competitors fully engaged in business.
   The token booth was staffed only at rush hour. The rest of the
day, patrons without tokens had to go to the main station entrance
two blocks away; those with tokens could go through the cage-like
turnstile _ until the discounters arrived.
   At first, the men scattered when the token clerk arrived. But
after a while, Sullivan said, ``They were being so brazen that they
would just retreat to the stairwell and wait for the uniformed cop
to leave.''
   Then they'd return to business, in full sight of the token
clerk, whose business dwindled. About 100 riders a day were taking
advantage of the reduced fare, plunking their money into a bucket
beside the swinging gate.
   ``This really infuriated the railroad clerk,'' said Sullivan.
   Her complaints eventually led to undercover operations that
resulted in the first arrests on Jan. 29. And the second arrests on
Feb. 1. Each time, the men were issued desk appearance tickets and
released. And each time, they went right back to work.
   On Feb. 16, the police raised the stakes against Paul Franklin,
35, Kenneth Norris, 36, and Willie Brown, 22. This time they went
to jail on charges including disorderly conduct, petty larceny,
criminal tampering and other crimes.
   So far, Franklin, who, like Brown, lived in an apartment near
the station, has pleaded guilty to disorderly conduct and served
eight days in jail. Norris, who lived in a homeless shelter, has
pleaded guilty to petty larceny and been sentenced to 70 hours of
community service _ including washing subway stations.
   ``Even as we made the arrests, we had one guy in handcuffs and
people were still walking up to him and trying to hand him money,''
Sullivan said. ``They were pretty slick in their operation. They
thought they had all ends covered.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880322-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 1949EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-JapanConstruction     03-22 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan Construction,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Verity Appeals for Quick Resolution of U.S.-Japanese Trade
Differences</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commerce Secretary C. William Verity opened a
new round of Japanese trade negotiations on Tuesday with an appeal
for fast resolution of the differences separating the two sides.
   The negotiations involve U.S. demands that Japan allow American
and other foreign construction companies to compete for an
estimated $60 billion in public works projects planned in Japan
over the next decade.
   Verity announced that the American team would be headed by
Deputy U.S. Trade Representative Michael B. Smith, who is taking
over from J. Michael Farren, a deputy commerce undersecretary who
is leaving the department because he was passed over for promotion.
   ``I trust that everyone in this room shares my feeling that
these negotiations on construction have gone on for too long
already and that the time has come to bring them to a close,''
Verity said in opening remarks.
   Last week, President Reagan's Cabinet-level Economic Policy
Council set a two-week deadline for resolving the construction
dispute. If the issue is not settled by the deadline,
administration officials have indicated they will recommend that
the president bring a trade complaint against Japan, a process
which could lead to U.S. trade retaliation against Japan.
   The Japanese have offered to allow U.S. companies access to
seven public works projects. U.S. negotiators have contended in the
past that this offer was too small and omitted sophisticated
engineering jobs.
   But Verity, in his remarks, indicated a willingness to consider
the Japanese proposal as a starting point.
   ``The Japanese side has suggested that contracts worth $30
billion in seven major projects could be opened to bidding by our
firms,'' he said. ``Very well, then, we simply ask that you open
them, and that, over time, you add additional projects until the
Japanese construction market is open.''
   Verity called on the Japanese to open up ``the broadest spectrum
of contract work'' to U.S. bidding.
   ``Earthmoving and runway construction are not enough,'' he said.
</TEXT>
