<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HotelID     03-22 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hotel ID,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Council Votes To Make Hotel Guests Show ID</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARWICK, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The City Council has approved an ordinance
requiring guests checking into the city's 11 hotels and motels to
show identification.
   The measure was proposed in January following the discovery of
the bodies of two women in different hotel rooms. The deaths, one
attributed to strangulation and the other to drowning, were not
related, authorities said.
   Mayor Francis X. Flaherty was expected to sign the ordinance in
a couple of days, said mayoral spokeswoman Anne Turner. It would go
into effect 20 days later, she said.
   Councilman Lincoln D. Chafee, the only one of the seven council
members to vote against the ordinance Monday night, called the
measure ``loose and vague'' and cautioned the council against
``stampeding to enact a bad bill.''
   The ordinance was amended to say that information from a hotel
registrant will be used only for emergencies or during criminal
investigations. The American Civil Liberties Union had complained
that the original version violated the rights of individuals.
   The guest who pays for a hotel room would be required to show a
driver's license, major credit card, state identification card,
military identification card, passport, vehicle registration or
vehicle title documents.
   Councilman C. Kenneth Wild Jr., who proposed the ordinance in
January, said it would help police investigate cases such as those
of the two women. Identification would not be required of people
other than the person signing for the room.
   Neither woman had paid for the room where she was found dead. In
the drowning, two people were charged with leaving the scene of a
death, but no one has been arrested in the strangulation, police
said.
</TEXT>
