<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PreacherQuits     03-22 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Preacher Quits,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Orange County Evangelist Quits Church, Subject Of Lawsuits And
Police Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>IRVINE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A television evangelist who resigned as
pastor of the Orange County church he started is the target of a
police investigation and lawsuits claiming he owes tens of
thousands of dollars.
   Richard Hogue, who came here from Oklahoma one year ago after
facing financial difficulties in that state, said in a television
interview Tuesday he resigned as pastor of Metrochurch Sunday to
concentrate on paying his debts.
   ``I'm just having to knuckle down and go back to work and take
my time and try to work myself back out of this debt,'' Hogue said
in a telephone interview with station KOCO in Oklahoma City.
   Hogue was interviewed from Miami, where he said he is ``looking
to put together a major opportunity which could mean I could maybe
be out of debt very soon.''
   Hogue frequently appeared on ``Richard Hogue Weekdays'' on the
PTL Network formerly run by defrocked minister Jim Bakker and his
wife Tammy. He also occasionally hosted a show on Trinity
Broadcasting Network called ``Praise the Lord.''
   Trinity discontinued using Hogue as a host three weeks ago.
   ``The red lights went off when we learned his board has
resigned,'' TBN attorney Norman Juggert said.
   Former Metrochurch members June and David Muehlberger of Palm
Springs filed suit in Orange County Superior Court on Dec. 16,
1987, against Metrochurch and Hogue, alleging he repaid just $2,000
of a $126,000 they loaned him to buy pews.
   Irvine police said Monday they are investigating allegations of
embezzlement as a result of the Muehlbergers' complaint.
   ``We don't know if it's a civil problem or a criminal problem,''
Sgt. Scott Cabe said. ``It just popped up in the last two or three
days.''
   In 1985, Hogue resigned from his church in Oklahoma, where he
was a well-known pastor and TV personality.
   The Los Angeles Times reported Tuesday that Hogue's former
Oklahoma attorneys are seeking $18,426 they claim he owes for legal
services.
   ``We've been trying to catch the guy for two years,'' David
Livingston, attorney for the Oklahoma law firm of Mosburg, Sears,
Kunzman and Bollinger, was quoted as saying.
   The Times also reported that an Oklahoma couple sued Hogue and
alleged he failed to repay $142,000 on a $160,000 note for a
157-acre horse ranch. The newspaper also reported that Hogue's
Oklahoma house was foreclosed for a $228,000 debt he owed GMAC
Mortgage Corp. of Iowa.
   Separately, Hogue's assistant, Mike Maggard, said Monday ``It
appears that Pastor Hogue and (his wife) Marilyn may be
separating.''
</TEXT>
