<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChagraParoled     03-22 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chagra Paroled,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Joe Chagra Freed After Nearly 6 Years Prison for Wood Slaying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joe Chagra, a former lawyer who spent
nearly six years in prison for plotting the assassination of a
federal judge, says it feels good to be free of prison and free of
drugs.
   Chagra, 41, was released on parole Friday from a federal prison
in Stafford, Ariz.
   ``For all the sadness and the pain that you go through, walking
out of that gate has to be the all-time high in life,'' he told the
El Paso Times. ``I can't really tell you how good I feel.''
   Chagra pleaded guilty in 1982 of conspiring to kill U.S.
District Judge John H. Wood Jr., who had been scheduled to preside
over the drug trial of Joe's older brother, Jimmy.
   Wood, known as ``Maximum John'' because of his tough sentencing
of drug dealers, was murdered outside his San Antonio home in 1979.
   Jimmy Chagra, who along with Joe was accused of hiring Charles
Harrelson to kill Wood, was acquitted on a murder conspiracy charge
and is imprisoned on a drug conviction. Harrelson was sentenced to
two life terms.
   Joe Chagra blamed his problems on a heavy cocaine habit and the
influence of his two older brothers, Jimmy and Lee.
   ``Now we know what a seductive drug cocaine is,'' said Chagra,
who said he is a convert to health foods and exercise. ``I'm sorry
that (drug use) happened. It did. I can't change it. ... I don't
anticipate any more problems in my life.''
   Lee Chagra, the eldest brother, gained notoriety by successfully
defending alleged drug dealers. He was gunned down in his office in
December 1978.
   Both Lee and Jimmy Chagra lived flamboyantly, gambling huge
amounts of money and using drugs. Jimmy Chagra once paid off a Las
Vegas casino debt of more than $900,000 in cash, and he lost a
$580,000 golf match.
   Joe Chagra, who has been disbarred, returned to El Paso Friday
but declined to discuss what he plans to do.
   ``The only thing I won't do is make any hasty decisions,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
