<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Nofziger-Hickel     03-22 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nofziger-Hickel,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nofziger Tried To Use Hickel As Go-Between With Student Protesters</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nixon-Fed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lyn Nofziger tried unsuccessfully to make
then-Interior Secretary Walter Hickel an emissary to protesting
students after Hickel's famous protest letter to President Nixon in
1970, according to newly released White House documents.
   Nofziger, a long-time political aide to President Reagan who was
convicted of illegal lobbying last month, was working in the White
House congressional relations office at the time.
   A memorandum from Nofziger to H.R. Haldemann, Nixon's chief of
staff, turned up in the latest batch of Nixon White House files
opened by the National Archives on Tuesday.
   Hickel wrote Nixon on May 6, 1970, after the invasion of
Cambodia by U.S. forces in Vietnam had set off a storm of protest
on the nation's campuses. He said that attacks on the protesters by
Vice President Spiro T. Agnew were creating an impression of a lack
of concern for ``the attitude of a great mass of Americans _ our
young people.''
   The letter, whose prompt appearance in newspapers dismayed the
White House, said Nixon should, among other things, talk with
members of the Cabinet from time to time. Hickel was quoted in news
accounts as saying he had had only two personal meetings with Nixon
since becoming secretary more than a year before.
   Nofziger's memo, dated May 8, 1970, said: ``Whether we like it
or not, Wally Hickel is the kids' new hero. Suggest we use him.
Suggest he meet with the president Saturday and then send him out
to talk to the kids.
   ``Why not have the president meet with a group of kids tomorrow
at mid-morning to take some of the steam out of the demonstration
and give us some favorable publicity?''
   The Nofziger memo was directed, apparently by Haldemann's
office, to Dwight Chapin, Nixon's appointments secretary. Chapin
seems to have sent it back to Ken Cole, Haldemann's assistant, with
the handwritten notation: ``Ken Cole _ good idea? _ C''.
   After that appeared the one word, unattributed: ``No.''
   Nixon did meet with protesting students, on his own without
staff preparation, at 5 a.m. at the Lincoln Memorial. That meeting
garnered much publicity, most of it in a tone of astonishment.
   Hickel and Nixon defended each other in public appearances
immediately after that, but Hickel did not get to see Nixon and the
president fired him on November 25 _ in a personal meeting.
   Hickel was traveling Tuesday and could not be reached, said his
office in Anchorage, Alaska. Nofziger had left for the day and also
could not be reached, according to his Washington office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880322-0193 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 2020EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Asylum     03-22 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Asylum,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Likes Soviet Life</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ERIE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Pennsylvania man who received political
asylum in the Soviet Union says the socialist life suits him just
fine.
   ``We have found this country to be free, with all freedoms you
find in America. You may also attend the church of your choice.
People also speak freely,'' Theodore Branch said in a letter from
Moscow to George Sharrer of Erie.
   Branch, 43, and his wife, Cheryle Hoffman Branch, 40, left the
United States with a tour group in November. On Jan. 19, Soviet
Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov announced that the
Branches had been granted political asylum and would be given jobs
and an apartment.
   ``In the USSR there is no unemployment and no homeless people.
Also, medical care is free. This is also true in most cases for
visitors. Each employee receives one month's paid vacation each
year,'' Branch wrote in a letter Sharrer said he received Saturday.
   The Branches lost their jobs at a Florida radio station when it
went off the air in 1986, and were unable to collect back pay of
$6,500 which was awarded by a court.
   Sharrer, an Erie Metropolitan Transit Authority driver for 11
years, said he talked with Branch when the man rode home from his
job as a janitor at an Erie department store.
   ``I never heard anything from him about ideology,'' he told the
Erie Daily Times. ``He got disgusted with not being able to find a
job. He kept saying he couldn't make ends meet with a minimum-wage
job.''
   The two sometimes ate together on the bus during a scheduled
layover at the Millcreek Mall, Sharrer said.
   ``One day, he told me he had been in Washington and that he'd
been approached by someone in the Soviet Embassy. He said he was
offered a job working at a radio station. He said he was going to
go over and see if he liked the job. He asked me for my address and
said he'd write me and tell me how it was going,'' Sharrer said.
   Sharrer, a member of the Naval Reserve, gave a copy of Branch's
letter to his commanding officer and notified the FBI.
   ``I'm afraid to write him back because of my security
clearance'' as a computer operator, Sharrer said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880322-0194 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 1753EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-France-Mitterrand     03-22 0660</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Mitterrand,0684</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mitterrand Announces He Will Seek Second Term</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Francois Mitterrand ended months of
speculation on Tuesday by announcing that he will seek a second
term.
   Opinion polls have put the 71-year-old Socialist in the lead for
the two-stage election, beginning April 24, although he was not
formally in the race.
   On Tuesday, Mitterrand appeared on the nationwide evening
newscast of state-owned Antenne 2 television. When asked if he
would run, Mitterrand paused dramatically, clearly relishing the
moment, and answered with a single word: ``Oui.'' Yes.
   In reply to follow-up questions, the president said he decided
to run because he thinks disunity threatened ``to tear the social
fabric'' of France.
   ``I saw a risk that the country might fall again into the
quarrels and divisions that have hampered it so often. I want
France to be united ... not be taken in hand by the spirit of
intolerance, by parties who want everything, by clans, by
cliques,'' he said.
   As soon as Mitterrand declared, Michel Rocard, until now the
Socialist Party's only candidate, withdrew from the race and gave
the president his full support.
   Mitterrand's plans had been the subject of intense speculation.
On some occassions he had indicated that he would preferred to
retire and at other times hinted he would run because of a sense of
duty.
   In the end, with four weeks remaining before voters go to the
polls, duty called.
   The main conservative candidates, Premier Jacques Chirac and
former Premier Raymond Barre, had criticized Mitterrand for being
coy and cutting short the democratic debate.
   Mitterrand justified his silence by saying that with the premier
campaigning it was up to the president to look after the nation's
affairs in a non-partisan way.
   The conservatives hope to end what the French call
``cohabitation,'' created when the conservatives ousted the
Socialists from control of the National Assembly in March 1986, but
were left with a Socialist president with two years to go in his
term.
   The president is chief of state and has major duties in defense
and foreign affairs. He appoints a prime minister who must be
backed by a majority of the National Assembly. The premier then
names his Cabinet and runs the government.
   Mitterrand said Tuesday that after watching the campaign, he
feared opposing candidates were bringing on France disputes that
threatened to damage the country.
   ``We need social peace,'' he said. ``Someone has to face up to
this, and I shall do it.''
   Chirac heads the neo-Gaullist Rally for the Republic and Barre
the center-right Union for French Democracy.
   In a statement issued by Chirac's campaign committee, the
premier said: ``The stakes are now clear. There is on one side the
Socialist Party which wants to retake power to lead a Socialist
policy and its candidate casts aspersion on all the others.''
   There was no immediate reaction from Barre.
   National polls consistently placed Mitterrand ahead of Barre and
Chirac in a campaign that has been more a contest of styles than
policies.
   A handful of minor-party contenders, including Andre Lejoinie of
the once-powerful Communists, are expected to draw a combined total
of 5 percent of the vote or less. Jean-Marie Le Pen of the
extreme-right National Front could get about 10 percent of the vote.
   A poll published in the Journal du Dimanche newspaper Sunday
indicated 55 percent of the 1,813 people polled were satisfied with
Mitterrand. Forty-eight percent were satisfied with Chirac as
premier.
   Another recent poll, however, indicated 30 percent of those
queried were undecided.
   Mitterrand told the TV audience Tuesday night that he would
pursue the programs and policies of the last seven years.
   ``I have maintained the confidence of the French people,'' he
said.
   He suggested that if he won, he might dissolve the National
Assembly and call for new parliamentary elections.
   The first round of the elections is to be held April 24 with a
run-off between the top two candidates scheduled for May 8.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
