<1ST_LINE>u w AM-TVA-Nuclear     03-22 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-TVA-Nuclear,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NRC Clears Way For Restart Of Sequoyah Unit 2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tennessee Valley Authority, bidding to
recover from the 1985 shutdown of its entire nuclear power system,
won permission from the government on Tuesday to restart the
Sequoyah Unit 2 reactor near Chattanooga, Tenn.
   The 5-0 vote by the Nuclear Regulatory Commission clears the way
for the Sequoyah plant to become the first of five licensed TVA
reactors to resume production of power. The approval was
conditioned, however, on TVA resolving a last-minute problem
involving temperature detectors in the plant's pressurizer system.
   The unanimous vote also provided a clear indication that the NRC
is not seriously concerned _ at least from a safety standpoint _
about allegations involving the TVA's nuclear chief, Steven A.
White.
   In a case referred to the Justice Department last year, NRC
investigators questioned White's veracity when he certified in
writing that another TVA nuclear plant, Watts Bar, met federal
quality assurance standards. White has denied any wrongdoing.
   NRC Chairman Lando Zech said the commissioners had reviewed the
case, still pending at the Justice Department, and ``we have
concluded ... that there is no presently known regulatory reason to
preclude authorization to restart'' Sequoyah Unit 2.
   ``There is nothing unusual about the commission's consideration
of a restart while investigations are ongoing,'' Zech added.
   On Capitol Hill, TVA Chairman Marvin Runyon told the House
Public Works subcommittee on investigations that ``tremendous
progress is being made in our nuclear recovery efforts ... led by
Steve White.''
   ``TVA is about ready to turn its nuclear corner,'' said Runyon.
   Runyon said the TVA hopes to have a second Sequoyah reactor,
Unit 1, ready for restart within six months.
   The Sequoyah facilities and three reactors at the Browns Ferry
plant, near Athens, Ala., were closed in 1985 for safety
improvements. After a management shakeup, construction of four
other reactors was slowed down and plans for nine others were
canceled. The TVA still was left with $15 billion in long-term
debts for the nuclear program.
   Runyon said the first of the Browns Ferry plants should be ready
for restart sometime next year.
   ``We're not going to rush this process,'' said Runyon. ``We're
proceeding deliberately, and we're putting public safety above all
else. No one reactor will be restarted unless we are conpletely
confident, and the NRC is fully satisfied, that it can be operated
safely and efficiently for a good, long time.''
</TEXT>
