<1ST_LINE>r w AM-RanchoSeco 1stLd-Writethru a0704 03-22 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rancho Seco, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0704,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NRC Conditionally Authorizes Restart Of Nuclear Plant</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS last graf to restore dropped name of NRC Chairman.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission on Tuesday
conditionally authorized a restart of the Rancho Seco nuclear power
plant near Sacramento, Calif., after a 27-month shutdown which
triggered a management shakeup and hundreds of plant modifications.
   The commission, in a 5-0 vote, stipulated that one remaining
equipment problem _ excessive vibration in emergency diesel
generators _ must be resolved to the satisfaction of the NRC's
staff before the restart can begin.
   Even if the generator problem is handled swiftly, Rancho Seco
still faces an uncertain future. Area voters are scheduled to
decide on the day of the California primary, June 7, whether the
913-megawatt facility should be closed permanently.
   The reactor is the sole nuclear plant owned by the Sacramento
Municipal Utility District, but it represents about 55 percent of
the utility's generating capacity and is directly responsible for
1,000 jobs and $75 million in wages. Indirectly, as many as 3,000
jobs and $150 million in wages are affected.
   The plant, which has long history of problems, was shut down in
December 1985 because of a power loss in its control system,
leading to severe overcooling of the reactor. The NRC subsequently
required major overhauls of the equipment, as well as deep changes
in management and operator training programs.
   Carl Andognini, SMUD's chief nuclear officer, and Ann Taylor, a
board member of the utility, told the commission the plant is ready
for restart, except for the diesel problem, and pledged that safety
would always remain the paramount concern in future operations.
   Taylor said ``there's tremendous support for the plant, out
there in the community.''
   But Ed Smeloff, another board member, said he thought Rancho
Seco should be closed permanently, even though ``I do believe it
can be operated safely.''
   Smeloff said he thought the dangers were economic, arguing that
the utility is too small to support an expensive nuclear plant with
an uncertain potential for future production. ``Rancho Seco
represents a $200 million per year risk,'' he said. ``We are not a
large enough utility to support that kind of risk.''
   One of the questions facing the voters is whether the plant
should remain open provided it meets certain production goals. NRC
Chairman Lando Zech chided the SMUD board for wording the issue
that way, saying ``you should have emphasized safety on the ballot.
It gives the commission some concern about the judgment of the
board.''
</TEXT>
