<1ST_LINE>u w AM-SpaceBudget     03-22 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Space Budget,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NASA Says It Needs $11.5 Billion To Achieve Space Leadership</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Almost a billion dollars must be allocated to
the space station next year or America will have to abandon plans
to build the orbiting platform, NASA Administrator James C.
Fletcher said Tuesday.
   A substantial cut in the space station budget, added to delays
caused by cuts in earlier years, will make it useless for the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration to continue efforts
to build the station, he said.
   ``This is year is crucial,'' Fletcher told the Senate
subcommittee on science, technology and space. ``Otherwise, we've
got to just forget it and start over at a later date.''
   But senators attending the hearing warned Fletcher that would be
extremely difficult to get NASA its entire requested budget in a
year when federal dollars are tight because of deficit-cutting
efforts. Seeral pressed him on how much of a reduction could be
tolerated in the space station program, but Fletcher said the
requested budget was the ``rock bottom'' that NASA needs.
   Fletcher said a severe cut in the station budget last year
caused a full year's delay, and another cut in fiscal year 1989,
which begins Oct. 1, would make it ``a waste of the taxpayers
dollars'' to continue the underfunded program.
   NASA's 1989 budget calls for a total of $967.4 million for the
space station. Plans call for the station to be assembled in orbit
and for crews to start living in the orbiting laboratory in the
middle of the next decade.
   The station funds are part of a $11.5 billion appropriation
request by NASA that would include money for space shuttle
missions, advanced shuttle rockets, aeronautical research and a
study of the technology that will be needed one day to send
astronauts back to the moon and possibly to Mars.
   The budget request, which was approved by President Reagan, is a
24 pecent increase over NASA's current spending blueprint.
   Fletcher said that unless Congress passes the entire space
budget, there is no way for the U.S. to maintain world leadership
in space.
   ``The entire future of the civil space program rides at risk on
this budget,'' he said. ``This is a crucial year ... It will make
or break the civil space program.''
   Fletcher said the budget is the final boost needed for NASA's
recovery from the 1986 Challenger disaster, in which a space
shuttle was destroyed and seven astronauts killed. The shuttle
fleet has been grounded since while the space agency corrected
flawed equipment that caused the accident.
   NASA tentatively plans to resume shuttle flights in August. Two
are planned for this year, seven in 1989 and 10 in 1990.
   ``Without this increase, NASA will be in serious trouble,''
Fletcher said. ``A major cut would be equivalent to the Challenger
disaster itself.''
</TEXT>
