<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StolenArchives 1stLd-Writethru a0756 03-22 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stolen Archives, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0756,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial Begins For Scholar Accused Of Selling Stolen Lincoln Letters</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 6th graf, `Mount told...' to CORRECT spelling to
Haughey, sted Houghey.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A scholar abused research privileges at the
Library of Congress and National Archives to steal and try to sell
letters signed by Abraham Lincoln, Winston Churchill and other
historic figures, a prosecutor said Tuesday.
   Charles Merrill Mount also defaced some letters between Lincoln
and Civil War generals to remove government markings that would
have alerted a rare documents dealer to the fact they were stolen,
Assistant U.S. Attorney Martin Murphy said in his opening statement
at Mount's trial.
   But Mount's attorney, Charles McGinty, argued Mount had legally
collected the documents and shoddy record-keeping led the Library
of Congress and National Archives to believe the letters were part
of their collections.
   McGinty said the government would offer no evidence showing
Mount stole the documents, a point Murphy conceded.
   Mount, 59, a Washington-based author of several artists'
biographies, tearfully denied the allegations, but predicted he
would be convicted.
   Mount told reporters outside court that associates in Ireland,
including Prime Minister Charles Haughey, had seen the documents
when Mount lived in Ireland during the 1960s. But Mount said a
government freeze on his assets prevented him from bringing
witnesses to the United States to testify on his behalf.
   ``Without witnesses, I'm going to be convicted,'' he said.
   Mount is charged with two counts of interstate transportation of
stolen property and faces up to 10 years in prison and a $10,000
fine if convicted. His trial is expected to last three weeks.
   Mount was arrested in August when he tried to sell a 158-page
collection of Civil War documents to Goodspeed's Book Store for
$64,600. A month earlier, the store paid Mount $20,000 for 23
letters signed by 19th-century painter James McNeill Whistler, a
Churchill letter and one by Henry James.
   The Whistler letters, brought to Boston in a plastic bag, were
stolen from the Library of Congress last July, Murphy told the jury.
   The Civil War collection disappeared from the National Archives
within a week before Mount's Aug. 5 letter to Goodspeed's offering
to sell the documents, Murphy said. Mount spent the last five days
of July viewing the collection, Murphy said.
   McGinty asked the jury to note testimony about keeping records
at the Library of Congress and National Archives and how government
records were stored before the archives opened in the 1930s.
   He said thousands of historic records were lost and stolen after
the Civil War because they were kept in basements, attics, and even
the White House garage.
   Records at the institutions show they should have possession of
numerous documents that actually are in private collections,
McGinty said.
</TEXT>
