<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HealthCosts-Bowen     03-22 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Health Costs-Bowen,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bowen Says Hospitals Engaging In `Medical Arms Race'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government's top health officer said
Tuesday that hospitals have engaged in a kind of medical arms race
that assures neither quality care nor good value for the dollar.
   ``Sometimes you can save money and also improve care, like
concentrating certain procedures in hospitals that specialize in
them,'' said Health and Human Services Secretary Otis R. Bowen.
``This not only leads to better results for the patient, it also
allows us to benefit from economies of scale.''
   Bowen's remarks to a conference of the Health Care Quality
Alliance followed a report by the 28-member coalition that
cautioned against emphasizing cost control to the point that the
``quality of care _ and quality of life _ are adversely affected.''
   The health secretary acknowledged that the government is
concerned about rising costs in the Medicare and Medicaid programs,
but said, ``We won't accomplish anything if we sacrifice quality
for lower costs.''
   ``One reason today's health care is so expensive is that the
financing of that care is little more than a collection of
disincentives to practice cost-effective medicine,'' he said.
   Bowen contended that ``hospitals, in order to attract doctors
and their patients, have bought and often duplicated the latest in
medical hardware in a kind of medical arms race.''
   Another reason for concern, he said, is that government tax
policies which do not tax employer-paid health insurance coverage
like some other fringe benefits ``have encouraged employers and
unions to bargain for ever-greater first-dollar coverage in health
insurance plans.''
   ``Compounding this folly,'' Bowen continued, ``most insurance
plans cover expensive high-tech procedures and slight preventive
services. And all of this has made patients and their families all
but oblivious to costs, since they pay so little out of pocket.''
   Turning to Medicare, he said creation of the program 23 years
ago ``created a powerful incentive for the health care industry to
develop the technology to treat the chronic, degenerative diseases
that afflict the aging.''
   Bowen said he was not suggesting those procedures are bad. ``On
the contrary,'' he said, ``They have improved the quality of life
for Americans of all ages.''
   ``Still to be decided is how much is too much. ... How much
heroic medical care and how many procedures to keep a dying patient
alive are desirable for the patient, the family and, not least of
all, for society at large? When is such care merely prolonging the
act of dying rather than contributing to longer life, or at least
some type of quality to it?''
   Bowen, a physician whose first wife died of cancer and whose
mother recently died in a nursing home, said: ``Sometimes our
high-tech capability lures us into pursuing expensive answers when
less costly ones are available. Our veneration of technology has
become a cultural blindspot that sometimes keeps us from pursuing
practical solutions to our problems.''
   The theme of the conference was ``Balancing Health Care Costs,
Quality, and Access: The Challenge for the Next Administration.''
   The alliance membership includes the American Medical
Association, the Alzheimer's Disease and Related Disorders
Association, the Arthritis Foundation, the American Cancer Society,
the American Academy of Pediatrics and the National Council on the
Aging.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
