<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Mideast 1stLd-Writethru a0647 03-22 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Mideast, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0647,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Diplomat Says Shultz May Go to Mideast in Two Weeks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 4 grafs recast to show Shultz likely to travel to Middle
East, but no firm decision; picks up at pvs 3rd grasf, ``State
Department.''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz will
probably travel to the Middle East within two weeks if Israel
agrees to further discussions on his regional peace plan, an
Israeli diplomat said Tuesday.
   Asher Naim, the information minister at the Israeli Embassy,
said he expects Israel's cabinet will vote to keep alive the Shultz
peace initiative when the issue is debated.
   ``Apparently, Secretary Shultz will be in the Middle East ... in
two weeks time again,'' he told reporters at the National Press
Club.
   Israel will not reject the U.S. peace proposals, Naim said,
``and if the government indeed decides a neutral way _ that means
you continue negotiations _ then probably Secretary Shultz will go
to the Middle East.''
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said Tuesday that
Shultz had not yet decided to return to the Mideast, where he
conducted a diplomatic shuttle last month.
   Another State Department official, who spoke only on condition
he not be named, said Shultz probably would make his decision by
the end of this week after being briefed by presidential envoy
Philip Habib about his tour of four Arab capitals. Habib visited
Jordan, Egypt, and Saudi Arabia this week, and is due back by
Thursday following a stop in Morocco.
   Habib will bring with him reactions from the Arab leaders to
Shultz's plan, which calls for Israeli-Arab talks to begin May 1 on
Palestinian self-rule, and for the next phase to start by Dec. 1 to
determine the future of the Israeli-occupied territories. So far,
Syria is the only party to have rejected the plan.
   Shultz's plans also may be shaped by his talks this week in
Washington with Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze
about the U.S. peace plan, which envisions international
sponsorship for the Arab-Israeli negotiations, the official said. A
group of U.S. and Soviet negotiators were scheduled to discuss the
Mideast on Wednesday, he said.
   Naim, addressing reporters at the National Press Club, said
Shultz would be coming back to the region because the Israeli
government will not reject his plan, despite internal divisions.
``They won't vote `no.' They'll probably decide to continue
negotiating about the plan,'' he said.
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, who visited Washington
last week, rejects the international auspices proposed by Shultz
for the talks. His rival, Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, has
accepted the plan.
   President Reagan, in an unusually blunt statement, warned Shamir
against rejecting the plan and said the United States would not
change its proposals to suit Shamir's reservations.
   But Naim hinted at one possible avenue for continued
negotiations with Israel over the Shultz plan. ``There are some
suggestions to cushion Israel's fears about an international
conference,'' he said.
   Naim was referring to proposed guarantees by the United States
that an international conference would not have any power to impose
solutions on Israel. Other U.S. officials have suggested these
guarantees would be included in a memorandum of understanding
between Israel and the United States.
   Redman said the United States also might promise Israel that the
guarantees would be binding on future administrations.
   ``We really have the sense that if we can get this thing moving,
that there really is no difficulty in having it move right across
the boundaries of one administraiton to another,'' he said.
</TEXT>
