<2ND_LINE>AM-Gore,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore Says Drug Fight Should Be Top Foreign Policy Aim</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRAVERSE CITY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Sen. Albert Gore Jr. told
students at a campaign stop Tuesday that combating illegal drugs
would take precedence in foreign policy if he is elected president.
   Gore told a crowded gathering at Traverse City High School that
he would use the military to stop the flow of drugs into the United
States.
   He said the nation's drug problem reflected ``a spiritual crisis
... an absence of hope.''
   ``We have to have the courage to say there's nothing more
important in our foreign policy than stopping'' illegal drugs, Gore
told the students. ``I'll change that and put the war on drugs at
the top of our foreign policy agenda.''
   He commented while campaigning in Michigan, where polls show him
trailing badly just four days before the state's Democratic
presidential caucuses.
   Earlier in the day, Gore canceled a speech at the University of
Wisconsin in Madison to return to Washington to cast a vote to
override President Reagan's veto of a civil rights bill.
   He also stopped in Harrisburg, Pa., where he met with Gov.
Robert P. Casey, who is neutral in the presidential race, and
received the endorsement of state legislative leaders.
   Gore said he was ``a little bit'' surprised at Vice President
George Bush's decision to go along with Reagan's civil rights veto.
   He added, ``When push comes to shove the vice president never
disagrees with President Reagan. I don't remember a time in eight
years when he has been willing to express any disagreement with the
president.
   ``He really has not carved out an identity of his own in this
election,'' Gore said.
   In Harrisburg, he called Pennsylvania ``an excellent opportunity
for a Gore victory.'' In Michigan, he said he expected to ``do
significantly better than expected.''
   Gore is running far behind in polls in Michigan, and he is
competing in the state without campaigning intensively. His
campaign has been airing radio commercials featuring an endorsement
by singer Johnny Cash, but has not aired television ads.
   He is running television commercials in Wisconsin, a state where
he figures to have a greater opportunity to demonstrate broad
appeal outside his native South. Gore is scheduled to speak to the
state Legislature in Madison, Wisc., on Wednesday.
   In Traverse City, Gore spoke to an overflow crowd of about 700
students at an event held after school had ended for the day. The
auditorium was filled with hand-lettered posters, such as one
saying, ``Al's your pal.''
   With him was the state House speaker Gary Owen, a Gore backer,
and the mayor of Traverse City, Bryan Crough, who also endorsed him.
   Gore's comments on drugs were in response to questions from
students. He pointed to the alleged involvement in massive drug
smuggling by Panama strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega. He has
repeatedly accused the Reagan administration of having continued
support for Noriega even after it had evidence of drug involvement.
</TEXT>
