<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-SalvadorElections     03-22 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Salvador Elections,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressman Says U.S. Should Strengthen Ties With Rightist
Salvadoran Party</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Salvador-Assess</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States should establish stronger
ties with the rightest party that won convincing victories in
municipal and legislative elections in El Salvador, a congressman
who monitored the weekend elections said Tuesday.
   Sunday's elections, which had a 70 percent voter turnout despite
threats of violence by leftist guerrillas, proved that the
Republican Nationalist Alliance will be a major force in El
Salvador, said Rep. John G. Rowland, R-Conn. The party, known by
its Spanish acronym Arena, won a majority of the elections over the
moderate Christian Democrat party of President Jose Napoleon Duarte.
   ``We really need to concentrate on working with the Arena
political party,'' Rowland told reporters at a news briefing.
   ``We need to get more involved. We have invested there millions
and millions of dollars in foreign aid. It's the only country
that's had any democratic reform of significance over the last few
years. It would be a shame to see the whole thing fall apart,'' he
said.
   Rowland pointed to Arena's strong electoral support across a
wide cross-section of Salvadoran society and efforts by the party
to moderate its views. And he noted the low profile taken by former
army Maj. Robert d'Aubuisson, the party's controversial founder who
has been accused of links to Salvadoran death squads.
   ``My impression is that Arena is not as nearly as right ... as
we had originally suspected. There's tremendous support among the
people,'' Rowland said. ``There are some bad apples, of course,
within their party, but our information suggests that maybe they're
not the crazies that you might suspect.''
   Rowland was one of six House members who monitored the elections.
   ``Our observations concluded that it was a fair and open
election,'' he said.
</TEXT>
