<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TrooperTrial     03-22 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trooper Trial,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Recommends Life Without Parole For Former Trooper</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SELMA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury Tuesday recommended a former state
trooper be sentenced to life in prison without parole for murdering
his trooper girlfriend, the first woman state trooper in the nation
slain while on duty.
   Circuit Judge J.C. Norton will not be bound by the jury's
recommendation when he sentences Joe Duncan, who was accused of
killing Elizabeth Cobb to collect $350,000 in life insurance.
   No date for sentencing was set immediately.
   Ten members of the Dallas County jury voted for life
imprisonment without parole, while two voted that Duncan should die
in the electric chair. The jury convicted Duncan of capital murder
Monday night after about three hours of deliberation.
   In a sentencing hearing Tuesday, Duncan's daughter pleaded that
his life be spared. ``He was _ he is _ the best father you could
have,'' 14-year-old Tanya Duncan said.
   Duncan, 33, was convicted of shooting Miss Cobb, 31, in the head
at close range Oct. 11. Her body was found the next day behind the
wheel of her patrol car, which was parked behind a rural church.
   At the time, the FBI described Miss Cobb as the first female
state trooper in the nation slain while on duty.
   Prosecutors charged that Duncan killed Miss Cobb for a $250,000
life insurance policy that paid an extra $100,000 if she died in
the line of duty. The slaying occurred 10 days after the policy
went into effect on the rookie trooper, with Duncan as beneficiary.
   Defense attorney Henry Pitts said the trial's most decisive
factor was evidence showing Duncan gave investigators conflicting
accounts before his arrest.
   Jurors saw a videotape that showed Duncan denying he knew
anything about Miss Cobb's death, and a second tape in which he
told investigators he found the slain trooper's body shortly after
she was killed. Duncan said he didn't tell anyone of finding her
body for fear he would be accused of the crime.
</TEXT>
