<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ProfessionalFund-Raisers     03-22 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Professional Fund-Raisers,0598</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Court To Study State's Disclosure Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Carolina's attorney general is
preparing to ask the U.S. Supreme Court to uphold a state law
requiring professional fund-raisers for charities to tell potential
donors how the money will be used.
   The nation's highest court is scheduled to hear arguments
Wednesday on North Carolina's petition to reverse lower-court
rulings, which struck down the 1985 law as a violation of the First
Amendment's freedom of speech guarantee.
   Both sides agree that the outcome of the case could have a
nationwide impact on the professional fund-raising industry, which
Attorney General Lacy Thornburg called a
``multi-multimillion-dollar business,'' and on smaller charities
that lack personnel to raise money.
   ``It's really a question of survival,'' said Errol Copilevitz, a
Kansas City attorney representing the National Federation of the
Blind of North Carolina Inc. and the Optimist Club of North
Raleigh, N.C., which filed a lawsuit in 1985 challenging the law.
   About 75 charities have filed a friend-of-the-court brief
opposing the statute. Many are represented by Independent Sector,
an umbrella group including such organizations as the American Red
Cross and the American Cancer Society, Copilevitz said Tuesday.
   Thornburg said Maine, Connecticut, Indiana and West Virginia had
filed briefs in support of North Carolina's law.
   The most controversial provision requires professional
fund-raisers to tell people they solicit what portion of the money
will be spent on the charitable cause and how much will be used to
cover expenses.
   ``The purpose of the law is to promote honesty through
disclosure ... in very much the same way that banks and other
institutions are required to tell, for example, what their interest
rate is going to be,'' Thornburg said at a news conference.
   A study of fund-raising campaigns conducted in North Carolina by
professionals on behalf of charities between 1980 and 1984 showed
that, on average, only 13 percent of gross receipts were returned
to the charities, he said.
   The law presumes that whenever a professional group retains 35
percent or more of the gross receipts, it has reaped an excess
profit, Thornburg said.
   The Solicitations Licensing Branch of the state Department of
Human Resources is empowered to increase the charity's share if it
finds excessive profit for the fund-raisers.
   If allowed to stand, the law would bolster public confidence in
charities, Thornburg said. ``We feel that if a donor knows in
advance what portion of the funds are going back to the charity,
then they will much more freely give.''
   But Wayne Shevlin, president of the Raleigh chapter of the
National Federation of the Blind of North Carolina Inc., disagreed.
   ``If the first thing you have to say is how much is going for
expenses, most people ... are going to hang up before you've had a
chance to go through the spiel,'' Shevlin said.
   The law might drive out of business many small- and medium-sized
charities, he said.
   Copilevitz said most potential donors who want information on
how the money will be spent ask for it. Many states _ including
North Carolina _ require professional and amateur fund-raising
groups to provide such details on request, he said.
   Most states regulate fund solicitation, he said, but North
Carolina's law goes far beyond any other.
   U.S. District Judge Earl Britt struck down the measure as
unconstitutional on May 14, 1986, a finding upheld by the 4th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals in Richmond, Va., on April 23, 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880322-0211 </DOCNO>
