<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PLOMission-Suit 1stLd-Writethru a0829 03-22 0586</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PLO Mission-Suit, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0829,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>United States Sues to Close PLO's UN Mission</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with PLO reaction from U.N. and
Middle East. Picks up 6th graf pvs, `Former U.S...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department sued Tuesday to force the
Palestine Liberation Organization to close its mission to the
United Nations, and the PLO envoy defiantly responded that he could
live on the street as a refugee.
   The government sought a federal court order barring the PLO;
Zehdi Labib Terzi, head of the PLO's observer mission; and five
other PLO officials or employees from continuing to operate the
mission or any PLO office in Manhattan or at any other location.
   The action is required under the 1987 Anti-Terrorism Act, which
found the PLO and its affiliates were a terrorist organization
responsible for numerous violent incidents, including the murder of
an American citizen during the hijacking of the cruise ship Achille
Lauro in 1985.
   Terzi said he would have no comment on the PLO's possible legal
response until he reads the complaint.
   ``The only asset we have in this country is the building we live
in,'' he told reporters. ``Maybe they want me to live on the
street, but this would not be the first time the Palestinians
become refugees.''
   He called efforts to freeze PLO funds ``financial terrorism to
strangle us.''
   Earlier Tuesday, he had said, ``If they force me to leave, I
will have to move to the United Nations'' on international
territory, out of reach of U.S. marshals. In 1973, PLO Chief Yasser
Arafat spent a night at the United Nations because he could not
stay on U.S. territory.
   In Amman, Jordan, PLO foreign affairs spokesman Farouk Kaddoumi
said Tuesday before the suit was filed,:``We will keep the office
open until the American police seal it off. Then we will go to the
United Nations and live there.
   ``This will become a continuous headache to the U.S.
administration,'' said Kaddoumi.
   Former U.S. Attorney General Ramsey Clark, the PLO's legal
counsel, was not available for comment, his office said Tuesday.
Clark did not immediately return messages left at the office.
   Clark has said, however, that he would seek to have the federal
complaint dismissed on grounds that U.S. courts lack jurisdiction
in the matter involving an international treaty, in this instance
between the United States and the United Nations.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar said he would have to
wait until the U.N. General Assembly adopts a resolution Wednesday
before commenting on possible legal action.
   The 159-member General Assembly is to vote on a resolution
supporting the PLO's right to operate and deploring U.S. moves to
shut the mission. The draft of the resolution calls on the
secretary-general to take measures to allow the PLO to carry out
its official functions as a U.N. invitee.
   In a separate action last September, the State Department
ordered the closing of the PLO's information office in Washington.
That was before Congress passed the Anti-Terrorism Act, which
President Reagan signed on Dec. 22. The law took effect Monday.
   Under the law, Congress determined that ``the PLO and its
affiliates are a terrorist organization and a threat to the
interests of the United States, its allies and to international law
and should not benefit from operating in the United States.''
   Earlier this month, Secretary of State George Shultz called the
act ``one of the dumber things that the Congress has done lately.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
