<DOCNO> AP880322-0213 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 2110EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PrisonSuit     03-22 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prison Suit,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawsuit Challenges Kentucky Federal Prison Unit for Women</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawsuit filed Tuesday alleges that an
underground prison facility for women in Lexington, Ky., was
designed specifically to house political activists and that inmates
are subjected to inhumane treatment.
   Civil liberties groups filed the suit in U.S. District Court
here against nine federal officials, including Attorney General
Edwin Meese III. It seeks the immediate transfer of the inmates
from the high-security facility to the general population of a
federal women's prison.
   The Lexington Control Unit opened in November 1986, now houses
five inmates and contains 16 basement cells constructed beneath the
federal prison at Lexington. The U.S. Bureau of Prisons said last
October it will phase out the unit, the only high-security unit for
women in the federal prison system.
   ``The primary purpose for the creation of the unit was to
confine prisoners whose political associations and affiliations
were determined to pose a security threat,'' said the suit,
alleging violation of the women's constitutional rights. ``All the
women in the unit are suffering psychological and physical harm as
a direct consequence of their isolated confinement in this
underground segregation unit.''
   A new medium- and high-security facility for women will be
opened in June in Marianna, Fla., and the phaseout in Lexington
will be completed shortly thereafter, said Bureau of Prisons
spokeswoman Kathryn Morse. She declined to comment on the suit.
   The ``small basement facility'' has ``virtually no natural
light'' and is illuminated 24 hours a day by fluorescent lights,
said the suit, prepared by the National Prison Project of the
American Civil Liberties Union and other attorneys.
   The women, the suit said, are monitored continuously by staff
and video cameras, have no opportunity to participate in any of the
activities available to the general prison population and are
subjected to random strip searches.
   ``We believe the women's lives are in danger,'' said Susan
Waysdorf, a spokeswoman for civil libertarians supporting the suit.
``They're beginning to experience signs of behavior modification,
general disorientation, vision problems, loss of appetite,
sleeplessnes.''
   Among the inmates are Silvia Baraldini, convicted of
racketeering and conspiracy in aiding a $1.6 million Brink's
armored car heist in Nyack, N.Y., that left a guard and two police
officers dead. Another inmate at Lexington is Susan Rosenberg,
linked by law enforcement officers to the same bungled Brink's
robbery.
   Baraldini, serving a 43-year term, was transferred to Lexington
after refusing to be interviewed by an FBI agent, the suit said.
   Rosenberg, serving a 58-year term for possession of weapons and
explosives in connection with a 1985 police raid in New Jersey, was
told that she would be confined to the unit until she changes her
political beliefs, the suit alleges.
   When civil liberties groups began to expose Lexington as a
``political prison, federal officials hurriedly brought in two
other women serving long sentences,'' a coalition of prominent
civil libertarians said in a statement about the Lexington unit.
   One of the women brought in later, Sylvia Brown, serving a
27-year term for violating probation and escaping from a federal
prison, was told that her release from the unit would depend on her
lack of interaction with the political activists, the suit added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880322-0214 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 2115EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Reagan-Politics     03-22 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Politics,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Hits Practice of Gerrymandering</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan harshly criticized the
process of gerrymandering on Tuesday, complaining that Republicans
are getting short-shrift treatment in the redrawing of
congressional boundary lines..
   ``I promise you this: As far as the president of the United
States is concerned, he's not going to be sitting around his garden
sniffing roses in 1988,'' Reagan told a group of Republican elected
officials.
   ``I'm going to be out on the campaign trail, telling the
American people the truth about how the electoral process has been
twisted and distorted,'' he said.
   Reagan noted that reapportionment is scheduled in 1991, and said
that ``having Republicans in state and local offices is the only
hope we have of getting a fair deal. And that's what we're asking
for -  an end to the anti-democratic and un-American practice of
gerrymandering congressional districts.''
   Gerrymandering is the political process by which congressional
district lines are redrawn in such a fashion as to benefit the
party in power, whether Democratic or Republican.
   Reagan said there were 367 congressional races contested by both
major political parties in 1984. In these contests, the president
said, Republicans won half a million votes more than Democrats, but
the Democrats won 31 more seats.
   In his remarks, Reagan said that ``gerrymandering has become a
national scandal. The Democratic-controlled state legislatures have
so rigged the electoral process that the will of the people cannot
be heard. They vote Republican but elect Democrats.''
   The president maintained that ``the congressional map is a
horror show of grotesque, contorted shapes. District lines jump
back and forth over mountain ranges, cross large bodies of water,
send out little tentacles to absorb special communities and ensure
safe seats.''
   Reagan said that while Republican Party Chairman Frank
Fahrenkopf has challenged Democratic gerrymandering in courts,
``ultimately, it's in the state legislatures that the battle for
fairness must be won. And that's why Republicans are going to have
to campaign with all our heart and soul for Republican state
legislative candidates.''
   Reagan has steadfastly refused to take sides in the competition
for the Republican Party nomination to succeed him, but has
indicated he will campaign actively for the nominee.
   In his talk Tuesday, the president signaled that he would hit
the campaign trail for an array of other causes, including his plan
to speak out against the practice of gerrymandering.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880322-0215 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 1926EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua-Talks 1stLd-Writethru a0767 03-22 0815</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0767,0839</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sandinistas, Contras Near Agreement On Truce In Nicaraguan War</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with top Nicaraguan negotiator
says agreement expected Wednesday. PICKS up 4th graf pvs, Victor
Hugo ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Staffing</HEAD>
<HEAD>By BRYNA BRENNAN</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAPOA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaragua's defense minister, Gen.
Humberto Ortega, said at the end of a second day of peace talks
between Sandinista and Contra rebel negotiators that he expected a
``concrete agreement'' on Wednesday.
   He declined to elaborate, telling a news conference, ``Obviously
we aren't able to go into details.''
   Earlier Tuesday both sides said they had exchanged proposals,
which agree on major points, for an extended cease-fire accompanied
by amnesty and release of political prisoners.
   Contra leader Adolfo Calero told reporters, ``We worked hard
during the day. We clarified (points that coincide) and we are
working on differences.''
   ``It was a fruitful day and tomorrow could be even better.''
   Calero described the second round of talks as ``direct and
frank.''
   The two sides began three days of meetings Monday at this town
on the Costa Rican border, trying to end a civil war that President
Daniel Ortega says has cost 26,500 lives since 1981. Both sides
suspended battlefield action during the talks.
   The Sandinista delegation proposed a 30-day truce that could be
extended to three months, during which the U.S.-supported Contras
would lay down their weapons and join a ``national reconciliation
dialogue.''
   Victor Hugo Tinoco, the deputy foreign minister, announced the
proposal at a news conference. For every rebel who stops fighting,
he said, the leftist government will free one of the 3,300
political prisoners it considers eligible for release.
   Most prisoners are former members of the National Guard, as the
army was called under the late President Anastasio Somoza, whom the
Sandinista revolution overthrew in July 1979.
   Contrary to previous Sandinista demands, Tinoco said rebels who
put down their arms would be free from prosecution without applying
for amnesty and could take party in Nicaraguan political life.
   They would be permitted to operate uncensored newspapers,
magazines and radio stations, but television would remain a
government monopoly.
   Contra proposals, as outlined to reporters by spokesman Bosco
Matamoros, call for a 45-day truce beginning on Good Friday, April
1. Rebel fighters would move to cease-fire zones and a permanent
truce would be negotiated by Sandinista and Contra leaders.
   Matamoros said the Contras demand ``total and unconditional
amnesty'' when the cease-fire begins, so anyone who had left
Nicaragua for political reasons could ``rejoin the political,
economic and social process without any conditions.''
   Contra leaders also want to join a national dialogue between the
Sandinistas and their internal political opponents.
   An agreement signed Monday night by President Ortega, the
defense minister's brother, and leaders of eight opposition
political parties has a significant effect on that Contra demand.
   It says the parties pledge to discuss ``internal political
issues exclusively with the government'' and the ``government will
discuss exclusively with rebel groups'' all matters involving a
cease-fire.
   According to Matamoros, other Contra demands include immediate,
total amnesty, freedom for all political prisoners and an end to
mandatory military service.
   Tinoco said: ``At the moment at which a cease-fire is signed,
whether it be for 30, 60 or 90 days, according to what the
counterrevolution wants, at that moment the leadership of the
Nicaraguan Resistance (Contras) will be able to rejoin civic and
political life and even participate in the national dialogue that
seeks a reconciliation of all Nicaraguans.''
   Both sides propose international monitoring of the cease-fire.
The Sandinistas would have a 15-member international commission
including representatives of the United Nations, Organization of
American States, Contadora and its support group.
   Contadora is made up of Mexico, Venezuela, Colombia and Panama,
and began trying to negotiate peace in Central America several
years ago. The support group is Argentina, Brazil, Uruguay and Peru.
   The battlefield truce appeared on Tuesday to be holding. It was
the first agreed suspension of fighting since truce for Christmas
and New Year's during which some fighting was reported.
   Alfredo Cesar, a former Sandinista who leads the Contra
delegation, called the exchange of proposals ``a step ahead.'' On
Monday night, he told reporters: ``Neither side seeks a military
victory over the other.''
   Both cease-fire and reconciliation talks are required under the
peace plan signed Aug. 7 by the five Central American presidents.
It also calls for greater democracy in the region and an end to
both foreign aid to insurgents and the use of one country's
territory for attacks on another.
   Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo, Nicaragua's Roman Catholic
primate, is attending the talks as one of two observers.
   He acted as mediator in four previous cease-fire conferences in
which the sides did not meet face-to-face. They were held outside
Nicaragua and ended without agreement.
   The other observer is Joao Baena Soarez, general secretary of
the Organization of American States.
</TEXT>
