<HEAD>New Campaign Ads In Michigan Feature Bill Cosby, Coleman Young</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The battle for first place in the Michigan
caucuses will heat up the airwaves Thursday as Jesse Jackson goes
on television with an ad featuring Bill Cosby and Michael Dukakis
counters with a radio ad featuring Detroit Mayor Coleman Young.
   Jackson's campaign is spending about $90,000 in the last 48
hours before the Saturday voting across the state, said spokeswoman
Pam Smith.
   One of the major parts of the $70,000 television buy will be an
ad featuring an endorsment by Cosby, the popular television star.
The ad was run first before the Iowa caucuses and was run across
the South before Super Tuesday.
   Smith said the Jackson television buy will be divided equally
between Detroit television and other markets across Michigan. The
$20,000 radio buy will be spread across the state she said.
   Dukakis' campaign, which has already been on the air in
Michigan, will start running an ad featuring the endorsement of the
Massachusetts governor by Young, Detroit's longtime mayor. Bob
Boorstein, a Dukakis aide, said the radio ad will air on radio
stations around the metropolitan area through Saturday.
   Dukakis has been running a biographical television ad for the
last week in Michigan. Boorstein said the campaign added an ad
emphasizing Dukakis' executive experience _ contrasting that to the
legislative experience of his rivals.
</TEXT>
