<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Dropouts-Drivers     03-22 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dropouts-Drivers,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lieutenant Governor Urges Withholding Driver's Licenses For
Dropouts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Carolina should encourage students to
finish high school by denying driver's licenses to people under the
age of 18 who drop out, the lieutenant governor said Tuesday.
   Lt. Gov. Bob Jordan, a Democrat who plans to run against
Republican Gov. Jim Martin in the Nov. 8 general election, held a
series of news conferences across the state to introduce a package
aimed at reducing the state's dropout rate.
   Jordan is expected to win the Democratic nomination in the May 3
primary. Martin has no opposition.
   A similar bill failed during the 1987 legislative session, but
Jordan said he was confident he could steer the measure through the
Democrat-dominated General Assembly.
   Jordan said Martin had made no proposals to reduce the dropout
rate although during his term nearly 100,000 youngsters _ one
student in four _ have left school without a diploma.
   Martin told reporters Jordan's proposal was reasonable and
interesting but said he did not know whether it would work.
   Jordan said that if elected he would set a goal of halving the
rate by 1992.
   The driver's license provision would give young people an
incentive to remain in school, Jordan said. Under the proposed law,
dropouts would have to wait until their 18th birthday to get a
license, while those still in school could take the license test at
age 16.
   ``The state of North Carolina should do what a lot of parents
do,'' he said. ``When their kids don't study or don't do well in
school, they take away some privileges. Some parents take away
their car keys.''
   Jordan's package also includes hiring more guidance counselors
and additional technical training.
</TEXT>
