<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 2126EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-IAPA-Haiti     03-22 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-IAPA-Haiti,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conditions for Haitian press improved, but concerns remain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Press conditions in
Haiti improved after the Duvalier dictatorship fell, but a
restrictive code and government intimidation still cause concern,
the Inter-American Press Association said Tuesday.
   An IAPA delegation said that after President Jean-Claude
Duvalier fled to exile in France in 1986, ending 29 years of harsh
rule by the Duvalier family, radio stations and newspapers
flourished.
   Local newspapers resumed political commentary. Bans were lifted
on newspapers published abroad by exiles. Radio stations _ the main
source of news in a country where illiteracy approaches 80 percent
_ rehired staff members who had been deported or hounded into exile.
   ``When Jean-Claude Duvalier fled Haiti in February 1986, the
media, like Haitians in general, assumed that they had democracy
and acted accordingly,'' Harold Hoyte, managing director of the
Barbados Nation, told the IAPA.
   ``Haitian publishers, radio and TV station directors, opposition
leaders and officials all agree that there was, in fact, almost
total freedom,'' said Hoyte, who traveled to Haiti on March 17-18
and spoke with newly elected President Leslie Manigat and many
others.
   The sense of journalistic freedom changed when the provisional
government, a military-led junta, issued a press code in July 1986.
It required journalists to have university degrees, declare news
sources, and be accredited annually.
   Haitian reporters told the delegation the code raised concern.
They also expressed concern about recent communiques from the
Information Ministry and armed forces cautioning the news media
about publishing or broadcasting reports from abroad that might be
perceived as negative to the image of Haiti or its leaders.
   ``Managers of newspapers, radio and television stations were
almost unanimous that there is now self-censorship of certain news,
and an awareness that to offend the army is to risk new
repression,'' Hoyte said.
   He said Manigat supports the press code and ``brushed aside the
delegation's arguments that the best press law would be no press
law at all.''
   In general, Hoyte said, ``the delegation was satisfied that
conditions for the press in Haiti are much better than those under
the Duvalier dictatorship, but also notes with concern the
atmosphere of intimidation and mistrust, and the prospect of a new
press law which will maintain some of the present limitations.''
   Three delegation members stopped off in Port-au-Prince last week
before going on the Dominican Republic for the IAPA meeting. The
others besides Hoyte were Wilbur Landrey, foreign editor of the St.
Petersburg (Fla.) Times and chairman of the IAPA freedom of the
press committee, and IAPA President Ignacio Lozano, editor of La
Opinion in Los Angeles, Calif.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880322-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 2127EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Prosecutor-Threats     03-22 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prosecutor-Threats,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyer: Prosecutor Described Suspect In Allegedly Fabricated
Threats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecutor accused of fabricating death
threats against herself during extradition proceedings for two
Sikhs charged with terrorism gave FBI agents a description used to
make a sketch of a suspect, a lawyer for the Sikhs said Tuesday.
   The FBI showed the sketch to several New Jersey Sikhs during an
investigation of the threats against special Assistant U.S.
Attorney Judy G. Russell, and one was ordered to appear before a
federal grand jury, said lawyer Ronald Kuby.
   Kuby represents Sukhminder Singh. He and Ranjit Singh Gill are
accused of terrorism in India.
   A federal magistrate ruled in February that Gill and Singh could
be extradited. The hearings were conducted amid tight security
partly prompted by the threats to Ms. Russell and an anonymous
letter sent to the magistrate, Ronald J. Hedges.
   In a hearing before Hedges on Monday, U.S. Attorney Samuel A.
Alito Jr. said there was evidence that Ms. Russell may have
manufactured the threats.
   Laboratory tests found the same typewriter was used to address
the envelopes and to fill out Ms. Russell's application to the
Justice Department in 1983. The typewriter was found in her home
along with three similar letters in envelopes, as well as materials
apparently used to make the letters out of words cut from
newspapers and magazines, the prosecutor said.
   Ms. Russell, who left the U.S. attorney's office before the
hearings began but handled the case as a special assistant, is in a
private hospital. Her attorney, Robert J. Fettweis, has declined to
comment.
   Federal authorities have said they would request a new
extradition hearing to avoid the appearance of impropriety, and
were considering how much of the proceedings should be repeated.
   Kuby said Tuesday he wanted all pretrial arguments repeated
before a new magistrate and possibly outside of New Jersey.
   At Monday's hearing, Alito said the allegations about Ms.
Russell have no bearing on the case's final outcome.
   During the investigation into the threats, Kuby said, one of his
clients, Amarvir ``Sonny'' Singh, was ordered to appear before a
Newark grand jury investigating the threats.
   ``They didn't question him, they just viewed him'' to see if he
matched the sketch, Kuby said. Amarvir Singh was later told by
investigators not to return for a lineup, Kuby said.
   The lawyer said agents told Sikhs they interviewed that the
sketch was based on Ms. Russell's description of a man who shouted
a threat at her in a shopping mall.
   First Assistant U.S. Attorney Michael Chertoff said he would not
comment on the shouted threat because it was not on the public
record. FBI spokesman Michael Mines said he would not comment on a
continuing investigation.
   Jagjit Singh Mangat, president of the New York-based Sikh
Cultural Society, said FBI agents apologized to those who were
questioned about the alleged threats.
   The allegations ``damaged the Sikh community quite a bit,''
Mangat said. ``Everybody is looking at us as a terrorist, but we
are not.''
   Justice Department officials outside of the U.S. attorney's
office in Newark are investigating the Russell case, and have the
power to pursue an indictment, Chertoff said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880322-0222 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 2129EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i CentralAmerica-Glance     03-22 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>Central America-Glance,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Central America At-a-Glance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are Tuesday's major developments in Central America:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   PANAMA CITY _ Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega's opponents scorned an
offer to negotiate his resignation and kept Panama shut down with a
general strike intended to force him out. An estimated 90 percent
of business and industry was closed, and many government employees
stated home.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   SAPOA, Nicaragua _ Negotiators for the Sandinistas and Contra
rebels said they exchanged proposals that agree on major points and
envisage an extended cease-fire, amnesty and release of political
prisoners. They began three days of meetings Monday at this town on
the Costa Rican border. Defense Minister Humberto Ortega told
reporters he expected a ``concrete agreement'' would be reached
Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WASHINGTON _ President Reagan sought to revive his stalled
effort to aid the Contras and said congressional Democrats would be
at fault if the rebel movement ceased to exist for lack of
supplies. The last aid package ran out Feb. 29.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras _ A U.S. military spokesman said American
soldiers, sent to Honduras for emergency training after Nicaraguan
soldiers were accused of crossing the border last week to attack
Contras, will stay on to complete the maneuvers. ``Right now the
plans are to make it a 10- to 14-day exercise,'' Maj. Gary Hovatter
said.
</TEXT>
