<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 3rdLd-Writethru a0866 03-22 1018</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0866,990</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Civil Rights Bill Dominates Presidential Politics</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs, bgng: Later, Dukakis, with 2 grafs to
UPDATE with Dukakis endorsements</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential contenders Paul Simon and Albert Gore
Jr. broke off campaigning Tuesday long enough to return to their
Senate desks and vote to override President Reagan's veto of a
civil rights bill. Republican contender Bob Dole stayed away and
straddled the issue.
   With Saturday's Michigan caucuses looming as the next campaign
test for the Democrats, Rep. Richard Gephardt attacked Michael
Dukakis for a ``battlefield conversion'' on trade issues so
important to the automotive industry. Dukakis aides retorted that
the Massachusetts governor has long been in favor of trade
legislation, just not Gephardt's proposal.
   Jesse Jackson was in Michigan, too, turning his anti-drug
crusade into a slap at the Reagan administration's Central American
policy. ``The No. 1 threat to your lives today is drugs,'' he told
a high school audience in Lansing. ``We're not threatened by 3
million Sandinistas and if so, can't be saved from them by 15,000
Contras.''
   Dukakis, at the Massachusetts Statehouse in Boston, did change
his stance on one issue, agreeing Tuesday to support a ban on
furloughs for first-degree murderers after public pressure stemming
from the release of a murderer who raped a Maryland woman.
   ``I try to listen, I try to learn,'' said Dukakis, who
previously had called the furlough program for murderers essential
for maintaining order in the state's prisons.
   Later, Dukakis made a trip to Connecticut to pick up
endorsements from Sen. Christopher Dodd and Gov. William O'Neill.
O'Neill predicted Dukakis would do ``extremely well'' in next
week's primary.
   Sources said Dukakis also would win the backing on Wednesday of
New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, whose name crops up consistently in
speculation about a darkhorse emerging as the Democratic nominee in
a deadlocked convention.
   That would leave New York Gov. Mario Cuomo alone among the
prominent non-candidates who has yet to make an endorsement.
   An ABC News poll suggested a matchup between Dukakis and Vice
President George Bush in the general election could be a close
race. The network Tuesday night its nationwide poll of 1,007 people
gave Dukakis 48 percent and Bush 47 percent. The margin of error
was 3.5 percent, ABC said.
   Bush was in Washington during the day, and the only other GOP
hopeful, Pat Robertson, was cutting his staff to avoid exceeding a
federal spending limit. Aide Connie Snapp said the payroll has been
cut from a maximum of 230 to about 100, and another 30 or 40 aides
may be released later in the month.
   Reagan's veto of the civil rights bill and the
Democratic-controlled Congress' attempt to override dominated the
political news during the day. The Senate voted 75-24 to overturn
the president's veto, more than the two-thirds majority needed. The
House also voted to override, 292-133.
   Simon, who is hoping to win the Wisconsin primary on April 5,
said he sponsored the legislation in 1984 when it was first
introduced.
   ``This is something that ought to appeal to the basic good
instincts of every member of the Senate and the House,'' he said.
He said the issue involved is, ``Are we going to make real the
dream of equality in the Constitution?''
   Gore returned to Washington from Harrisburg, Pa., after
collecting endorsements from several legislative leaders. He also
met with Gov. Robert Casey, but came away without an endorsement.
   Gore used the civil rights bill to attack Bush, the prohibitive
front-runner for the Republican nomination. Gore said Bush, who
announced Monday that he supported Reagan's veto of the measure,
always sides with the president, ``even when the proposals are
unfathomably dumb.''
   ``When push comes to shove the vice president never disagrees
with President Reagan,'' he said, adding that Bush didn't disagree
with selling arms to Iran for hostages or in keeping Panama
strongman Manuel Noriega on the CIA payroll despite evidence of
drug involvement.
   Bush's top campaign spokesman, Pete Teeley, dismissed
suggestions that Bush would begin looking for an issue to disagree
with Reagan on, just to prove his independence.
   ``The fact is, six months ago everybody was writing that George
Bush had to disagree with the president in order to get the
nomination. Everyone now sees that that was a myth,'' the spokesman
said.
   Far, far behind in the Republican presidential race, Dole said
he stayed in Wisconsin rather than return for the Senate vote
because ``I wasn't needed.''
   He said he was personally opposed to the president's veto. But
asked on a Milwaukee radio station call-in program, he said, ``But
if it were the deciding vote, I would side with the president.''
   Dole, who was attacked by Bush earlier in the campaign for not
taking firm stands on issues such as arms control and tax
increases, placed a formal statement in the Senate record that did
not take a precise stand.
   In part it said, ``I have always supported legislation to
overturn Grove City to restore the broad civil rights coverage that
existed prior to that case. ... At the same time, I recognize that
(the bill) is not a perfect bill. I am not fully satisfied with
it... But the fact remains that the administration and its
congressional allies had the opportunity to offer amendments and
they were voted down.''
   Dole was absent when the bill passed the Senate originally in
January.
   The legislation stems from a 1984 Supreme Court ruling that says
an organization receiving federal aid must follow
anti-discrimination rules only for the program that receives the
aid, and not for the entire organization or institution. The
legislation would erase that distinction.
   Gephardt's repeated jabs at Dukakis centered on the trade issue
that is central to his own campaign. The Missouri congressman is
the sponsor of legislation calling for retaliation against unfair
trading practices. Dukakis opposes the Gephardt provision but
declared a few days ago that he favors a different proposal backed
by Sen. Don Riegle _ the Michigan senator who bestowed his
endorsement on Monday.
   ``We're getting some battlefield conversions,'' Gephardt said.
</TEXT>
