<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Nicaragua     03-22 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Nicaragua,0547</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nicaragua Says U.S. Plotting Invasion, Honduras Rejects U.N.
Observers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaragua told the Security Council
Tuesday the United States is plotting an invasion of that Central
American nation.
   Honduras, meanwhile, rejected Nicaragua's call for U.N.
observers to visit the Honduran-Nicaraguan border, where there was
fighting last week between soldiers of the leftist Sandinista
government and U.S.-backed Contra rebels.
   Nicaraguan envoy Rita Delia Casco, said of the alleged U.S. plot:
   ``The danger is not past. Indeed, it is growing. America plans
to provide a Central American Gulf of Tonkin incident to serve as a
pretext for direct invasion and escalation of intimidation and
threats.''
   The United States sent 3,200 soldiers to Honduras last week at
the request of the Honduran president, who accused Nicaraguan
soldiers of penetrating Honduran territory while chasing the
rebels. President Reagan said the U.S. move was to show support of
Honduras and as a warning to Nicaragua.
   Ms. Casco, director of the Foreign Ministry's department of
international organizations, said the situation ``points to the
possibility of imminent imperialist military action on a broad
scale.''
   The Gulf of Tonkin incident occurred when Washington said North
Vietnamese boats attacked two U.S. destroyers in that waterway on
Aug. 2, 1964. Congress passed the Gulf of Tonkin Resolution five
days later and the United States began a military buildup in South
Vietnam that led to major American involvement in the Vietnam War.
   A four-member U.N. team was leaving Tuesday night to inspect the
Nicaraguan side of the border with Honduras.
   U.N. spokesman Francois Giuliani told reporters that Honduras
turned down a U.N. offer to send observers to that country.
   Honduran Ambassador Jorge Ramon Hernandez told the council a
U.N. team was not necessary because the five Central American
presidents, in a regional peace plan signed last August, had set up
an executive committee to verify compliance with the accord.
   Hernandez said Sandinista troops invaded Honduras and his nation
had the right to self-defense.
   ``Our military response has been limited so far and the
international assistance we are asking for basically has a
deterrent nature,'' he said.
   Honduran jets raided Nicaraguan positions last week in the Bocay
region, which straddles the border between the two countries. No
injuries were reported.
   On Sunday Honduran officials said the Nicaraguans were
withdrawing and the U.S. troops would leave the country soon. Maj.
Gary Hovatter, a U.S. military spokesman in Honduras, said Tuesday
that the American troops were conducting training exercises that
could last from 10 to 14 days.
   U.S. Ambassador Herbert S. Okun, the deputy permanent
representative at the U.N., told the council that Nicaragua had
launched a massive attack against the rebels, who have base camps
in Honduras.
   ``The Sandinistas committed aggression against Honduras,'' he
said. ``It was not the other way around.''
   Okun said the Sandinistas retreated into Nicaragua without
crushing the rebels because Honduras reacted forcefully and the
United States demonstrated its determination to help Honduras.
   He said stability will return to Central America only when
Nicaragua complies with the regional peace plan and gives up ``its
self-appointed right to subvert neighboring democracies and to
launch premeditated attacks.''
</TEXT>
