<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BrawleyMarch     03-22 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brawley March,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Demonstrators, Counter-Demonstrators Face Off in Brawley Protests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Demonstrators protesting against the
state grand jury in the Tawana Brawley case met
counter-demonstrators for the first time on Tuesday, while at least
two protesters scuffled with police.
   There were no arrests.
   Roughly 100 marchers led by the Rev. Al Sharpton and Brawley
family lawyer C. Vernon Mason gathered outside chanting, ``Governor
Cuomo, haven't you heard? This is not Johannesburg.'' That group
was predominantly black.
   About 75 whites, who at first watched silently, began to shout
back. ``Get Tawana to testify. We care too,'' some of them said.
   There was no scuffling between the two groups.
   Miss Brawley, a black 16-year-old, claims she was kidnapped and
sexually assaulted by at least six white men during four days in
November. Mason and another attorney, Alton Maddox Jr., have
advised their client not to cooperate with investigators.
   Sharpton's group had promised to disrupt grand jury proceedings
in the case. About 50 people from New York City joined as many
local residents Tuesday morning for a march from the Mid-Hudson
Bridge.
   Later, members of Sharpton's group attempted to push through a
line of police who stood shoulder to shoulder in front of the doors
of a state armory, where the grand jury has been meeting. At least
two protesters struggled with police and were taken into a van, but
were released and allowed to return.
   ``If it comes necessary for arrests to be made, we'll make
them,'' Police Chief Stewart Bowles said. ``I'd rather not.''
   Despite temperatures which hovered near 30 degrees, Sharpton
said his group would stay all night or even several days until the
grand jury was disbanded. Some 15 to 20 protesters remained at the
scene at midevening.
   A spokesman for Attorney General Robert Abrams would not say if
the grand jury was meeting Tuesday, but there was no sign of grand
jury activity.
   Gov. Mario Cuomo selected Abrams to investigate and, if
necessary, prosecute the case.
   At one time, Sharpton, Maddox and Mason had insisted that Abrams
personally handle the case. They have since demanded a special
prosecutor, but Cuomo has refused.
   Maddox says Abrams has violated the law by disclosing certain
facts about the grand jury, such as the instructions it received,
its purpose for forming and its makup. He said state law requires
that grand jury proceedings be secret.
</TEXT>
