<HEAD>Shamir Returns From U.S., Mobbed By Supporters</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with soldier hurt. PICKS up 4th
graf pvs, `Returning from ...' Minor editing thereafter to TRIM;
SUBS last graf, `In another ...' with 2 grafs to CLARIFY ministry
spokesman's comment on firebombers.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOCELYN NOVECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Israelis mobbed Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir on his return from a U.S. visit Tuesday and cheered
him for his firm opposition to an American peace plan. In the
occupied lands, violence continued.
   The army said troops shot and killed a Palestinian man in a
clash Monday night, bringing the Arab death toll in 15 weeks of
protests in the occupied territories to 107, according to U.N.
figures. The Israeli army has suffered one fatality.
   At least three more protesters were wounded in clashes, and a
Palestinian who allegedly collaborated with Israeli authorities was
shot and killed by fellow Arabs, Palestinian reports said.
   An Israeli soldier was taken to a hospital after being hit in
the chest with a rock during a demonstration Tuesday in the Gaza
Strip refugee camp of Deir El Balah, an army spokesman said.
   Returning from a week-long visit that included talks with
President Reagan and Secretary of State George P. Shultz, Shamir
said U.S. officials had set no deadlines for Israel to accept the
plan.
   ``No one demanded anything from us,'' he told reporters at Tel
Aviv's Ben Gurion airport. ``It all depends on us.''
   Shamir also hinted Shultz was considering a return to the Middle
East in another attempt to defuse Israeli-Palestinian tensions.
   Asher Naim, the information minister at the Israeli Embassy in
Washington, said Shultz will travel to the Middle East in two weeks
to continue negotiating for acceptance of his regional peace plan.
State Department spokesman Charles Redman said Tuesday that Shultz
had not yet decided to return.
   Naim also said Israel's Cabinet probably would vote to keep
alive the Shultz peace initiative when it debates the issue in two
weeks.
   Entering Jerusalem, Shamir's car was mobbed by thousands of
delighted supporters, who danced, sang and waved banners saying:
``Shamir remains strong.''
   ``These good wishes went with me wherever I went,'' Shamir told
the crowd, mostly members of his right-wing Likud bloc and Jewish
settlers. ``No one dared force on me decrees that lovers of the
land of Israel could not accept.''
   Shamir used harsh words to restate his objections to the Shultz
plan.
   ``These proposals, in our opinion, will not bring peace closer,
and the peace may even be harmed if (our) disagreements are not
taken into consideration,'' he said.
   Shamir has repeatedly objected to a major component of the U.S.
plan _ an international forum that would launch peace talks between
Israel and its Arab neighbors. He fears the forum would be hostile
to Israel and force concessions from territories occupied in the
1967 Middle East war.
   Shultz's plan also calls for three years of self-rule for the
1.5 million Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, with
talks on an overall settlement to begin in December.
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, who heads the centrist Labor
Party and has supported the Shultz plan, toured the Gaza Strip on
Tuesday and discussed granting autonomy to its 650,000 mostly
impoverished residents before implementing autonomy in the West
Bank.
   ``It would be a scandal and a mistake to just get up and leave
Gaza,'' Peres told reporters. ``But if we could reach an
arrangement of autonomy ... with Jordan which would enable us to
live on terms of security with Gaza, I'm for that.''
   The death toll rose as the body of a Palestinian was found in
the hills of Tubas, a West Bank village 50 miles north of Jerusalem.
   An army spokesman confirmed troops shot the man Monday night
when their patrol was attacked by protesters hurling rocks, metal
bars and bottles.
   In Gaza, the body of a Palestinian man was found in an orchard
in the village of Beit Hanoun, Israel radio said. The man's skull
had been crushed. A military spokesman denied army involvement in
the death, but villagers said the man was beaten to death by troops.
   A third Palestinian died when he was shot from a passing car in
southern Gaza by assailants assumed to be Arabs, the army said.
Palestinian journalists said the man, Naim Abu Lafyeh, was killed
for collaborating with authorities.
   Troops also shot and wounded a resident of Khan Younis refugee
camp when he attacked an officer with a metal pole, Israel radio
said. Officials at Ahli Arab hospital said they admitted two
Palestinians suffering injuries inflicted by troops.
   In the West Bank, members of two Arab councils resigned Tuesday
a day after an underground leaflet called for Israeli-appointed
municipal officials to leave their jobs, the Arab-owned Palestine
Press Service said.
   In another development, a ministry spokesman said Defense
Minister Yitzhak Rabin told a parliamentary committee he authorized
civilians to shoot at firebomb throwers if their lives were
endangered and shooting was the only way out.
   State-run radio said earlier that Israelis were allowed to shoot
if the assailant was not standing in a crowd.
</TEXT>
