<HEAD>Deadly Colombian Volcano Shows Signs of Life</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANIZALES, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The volcano that killed about 23,000
people in a 1985 eruption showed signs of activity Tuesday, and
officials warned residents in the surrounding region, the Volcano
Institute of Manizales said.
   Officials at the institute sounded a preventive alarm, but said
it was not necessary to evacuate people living near the Nevado del
Ruiz volcano.
   The volcano erupted Nov. 13, 1985, melting glacial ice on its
slopes and sending an avalance of mud which buried the nearby town
of Armero.
   Institute spokesman Alvaro Acevedo said seismographs
``registered abnormal seismic activity and the expulsion of
abundant ashes'' from the mountain, about 65 miles west of Bogota.
   But Acevedo said the situation is similar to other periods of
volcanic activity the institute has registered since the 1985
catastrophe.
   The volcano erupted on July 29, 1986 after tremors. There were
no injuries.
   The institute lies about 25 miles from the volcano.
</TEXT>
