<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Captives     03-22 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Captives,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Capture Three Soviets; Another Missing in Ethiopia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eritrean separatists have taken three Soviet
soldiers prisoner in Ethiopia and a fourth is missing, the
government announced Tuesday.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov said the four
were among 13 Soviet military advisers captured in Ethiopia last
week by forces fighting the leftist government to establish an
independent Eritrean state.
   Gerasimov told reporters at a news briefing that the Eritrean
People's Liberation Front recently ``has intensified combat
operations.''
   He said nine of the Soviets captured returned to their command
posts, three were identified by their captors as prisoners of war
and one remained missing.
   Ethiopia has strong political ties to the Soviet Union.
   Gerasimov had no details of the incident or the conditions in
which the Soviets are being held.
   Eritrea, a former Italian colony on the Red Sea, was
administered by Britain from World War II until 1952 when it was
federated with Ethiopia under a U.N. resolution. Ethiopia
incorporated it as a province in 1962, touching off a rebellion for
independence.
   Some Eritrean groups have signed an agreement to unite, but not
the Eritrean Popular Liberation Front, which is composed mainly of
urban-born Christians.
   According to the International Institute for Strategic Studies
Military Balance 1987-88 edition, there are an estimated 1,400
Soviet technicians and advisers in Ethiopia. An estimated 2,500
Cuban combat troops also are in Ethiopia supporting the Addis Ababa
government.
</TEXT>
