<HEAD>Philippine Cargo Vessel Capsizes, 11 Bodies Recovered</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese patrol boats recovered the bodies of 11
crew members Wednesday after a Philippine cargo vessel capsized in
rough waters off the Pacific coast of northern Japan, officials
said.
   One crewman was rescued after the Tuesday night incident, and
patrol boats and helicopters were searching for 10 other seamen,
said Michiaki Katsumata, spokesman for the Maritime Safety Agency's
regional office in Shiogama, 190 miles northeast of Tokyo.
   Katsumata said Feddrico Sandaga, 60, was picked up near the
6,812-ton Captain Trader, which ran aground in 20-foot water and
then capsized about two miles northeast of Shiogama in Miyagi
Prefecture.
   Katsumata said officials are still attempting to identify bodies
of the 11 victims and to establish the cause of the accident.
   The Captain Trader, owned by a shipping company in Manila, was
headed for Shiogama from Hakodate in Hokkaido island with 4,000
tons of pig iron when it ran aground, Katsumata said.
