<DOCNO> AP880322-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 2317EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gorbachev     03-22 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gorbachev,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Chief Says It Absurd to Blame Moscow For Nicaragua Conflict</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev said Tuesday it's absurd to
blame Moscow for Nicaraguan conflicts and the Soviet Union has no
military-political plans for Central America.
   ``We are not reckless adventurers,'' the Soviet leader said.
   Gorbachev also said his economic and social reforms have brought
an ``upsurge of ideological clashes'' in his own country that are
still going on.
   His remarks came as Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze
conferred in Washington with Secretary of State George P. Shultz on
issues including the superpower dispute over Nicaragua.
   Shultz wants Moscow to stop military aid to Nicaragua's leftist
Sandinista government, while Shevardnadze voiced ``serious
concern'' about U.S. policies in Central America. The United States
backs Nicasraguan rebels, known as Contras.
   Assistant Secretary of State Rozanne L. Ridgway and State
Department spokesman Charles E. Redman accused the Soviets on
Monday of furnishing an unceasing supply of weapons to the
Sandinistas.
   Gorbachev, the general secretary of the Soviet Communist Party,
outlined the Soviet position on Central America at a Kremlin
meeting Tuesday with Uruguay's president, Julio Sanguinetti, the
official Tass news agency reported.
   Tass quoted Gorbachev as saying, ``We will never understand how
Nicaragua can threaten the United States and the Western hemisphere
in general; we will never accept the absurd claim that the `hand of
Moscow' is the cause of the conflict and an obstacle to resolving
it.''
   The Soviet leader said that ``the U.S.S.R. does not have any
military-political plans in respect to that region and this theme
has never even cropped up in our relations with the Nicaraguan
leadership,'' according to Tass.
   ``Why should we need this?'' Gorbachev said. ``To provoke the
United States or somebody else in Latin America? We are not
reckless adventurers.''
   Gorbachev said the Soviets never supplied arms to leftist rebels
in El Salvador and Guatemala.
   He made no specific mention of U.S. charges of arms deliveries
to the Nicaraguans.
   Gorbachev also referred in his conversation with Sanguinetti to
domestic affairs, saying the economic and social reforms he
introduced have brought ideological clashes.''
   He said that those disputes ``have not yet subsided because
people want to know fully why things that had come into being in
extraordinary, extreme circumstances were retained also in normal
conditions.''
   Tass did not specify what Gorbachev was referring to. He may
have been talking about the drive by some Armenians to annex the
predominantly Armenian region of Nagorno-Karabakh, which has been
part of neighboring Azerbaijan since 1923.
   Gorbachev said he expects the Shultz-Shevardnadze negotiations
will help set the agenda for his fourth summit meeting with
President Reagan, which both sides have said will take place in
Moscow in late spring or early summer.
   ``The talks ... will show if there is a real possibility to
prepare a treaty on strategic (long-range nuclear) offensive arms
in time for President Reagan's visit to Moscow, whether it will be
possible to reach agreement on questions of the Afghan and Middle
East settlement and on other pressing issues,'' Gorbachev was
quoted as saying.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
