<2ND_LINE>AM-Chambers, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0758,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Widens Request on Medical Testimony</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with jury rehearing testimony of
two medical examiners, dismissed for day, picking up 7th graf `The
jury...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The jury in the Robert Chambers Jr. trial,
deliberating the so-called ``preppie murder'' case for a sixth day,
focused Tuesday on testimony regarding pinpoint hemorrhaging in
Jennifer Levin's eyelids.
   The jurors, after being rebuffed in their request for medical
testimony about the specific amount of time a person's neck must be
squeezed in order for the person's eyelids to hemorrhage, widened
the request to all testimony regarding the hemorrhaging.
   State Supreme Court Justice Howard E. Bell agreed to allow
reading of testimony by prosecution witness Dr. Maria Landy,
assistant New York city medical examiner, and defense witness Dr.
Ronald Kornbluth, the Los Angeles medical examiner.
   Near the end of the day, the jury asked for a repeat of specific
parts of Ms. Landy's testimony, and, as lawyers argued over the
request, the jury was dismissed for the day.
   Earlier Tuesday, shortly after the jury began its sixth day of
deliberation, the panel was called into the courtroom. A court
reporter read this statement, which was agreed upon by the
prosecutors and the defense:
   ``The amount of time needed to cause the pinpoint hemorrhaging
in the lower eyelid was less than or equal to the time needed to
cause her death. There was no testimony from the doctors who
testified in this case that specified a specific minimum or maximum
period of time that it took to cause the hemorrhages as opposed to
the time it took to cause her death.''
   Chambers, 21, is accused of second-degree murder in the
18-year-old woman's death on Aug. 26, 1986.
   The jury, which got the case Thursday, could also convict
Chambers of the lesser crimes of first- or second-degree
manslaughter or criminally negligent homicide.
   The prosecution maintains he used her blouse to strangle her.
Chambers said in a statement to police that he killed her
accidentally when she hurt him during a rough sexual encounter.
   Chambers said the death occurred nearly instantaneously when he
reached up and pulled Miss Levin off him, flipping her to the
ground.
   The kind of hemorrhage mentioned by the jury often results from
strangulation. Medical experts who testified at the trial disagreed
about how long the pressure had been maintained in Miss Levin's
case.
</TEXT>
