<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Colombia-DrugCartel 2ndLd-Writethru a0884 03-22 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia-Drug Cartel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0884,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reputed Drug Kingpin Escapes After Shootout With Army</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: DELETE last graf pvs, Escobar Gaviria had ... which
erroneous. Ochoa, not Escobar Gaviria, was released from prison by
judge.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MEDELLIN, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pablo Escobar Gaviria, sought as a top
man in the notorious Medellin drug cartel, escaped arrest after a
shootout early Tuesday between his heavily armed bodyguards and
soldiers, the army's 4th Brigade said.
   It reported that at least one man, not identified but thought to
be one of Escobar Gaviria's personal guards, was injured. The army
would not elaborate.
   At least 25 bodyguards were arrested after the clash and a
variety of firearms and documents were seized, the army communique
said. The haul also was said to include communications equipment,
13 vehicles and ammunition.
   The army said Escobar Gaviria's wife, Maria Victoria, and her
sister were arrested elsewhere in Medellin carrying ``several
documents of interest.''
   Escobar Gaviria was indicted in 1986 on federal drug charges in
the United States. Another federal drug indictment in Florida last
month named Escobar Gaviria, Panamanian strongman Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega and 14 others.
   In its communique, the army said that after Escobar Gaviria was
located, patrols from the 4th Brigade, backed up by helicopters,
surrounded the wanted man's luxurious country estate at 5:45 a.m.
Tuesday. The estate is on Medellin's outskirts, 180 miles northwest
of the capital, Bogota.
   But the army said troops tripped a sophisticated alarm system of
lights and sirens, allowing Escobar Gaviria to escape in the
shootout that ensued between soldiers and his bodyguards.
   The Medellin cartel is considered the main cocaine trafficking
organization in the world. U.S. authorities have charged the cartel
is responsible for up to 80 percent of all the cocaine that reaches
the United States.
   Colombia's Justice Ministry in January ordered the arrest of
Escobar Gaviria and others named as cartel leaders for extradition
to the United States, the army said. Among those sought are Jorge
Ochoa, Juan David and Gonzalo Rodriguez.
   Troops immediately spread out in the small communities near the
country residence, but Escobar Gaviria eluded detection, the army
said.
</TEXT>
