<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Brazil-Constitution     03-22 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brazil-Constitution,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brazilian Lawmakers Vote To Maintain Presidential System Of
Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislators voted Tuesday to keep the
presidential system of federal government rather than switch to the
parliamentary structure with a prime minister. President Jose
Sarney called the action ``an important victory.''
   Sarney said the 344-212 vote by the lawmakers rewriting the
constitution was ``better for the country. Congress understood
that.''
   Later Tuesday, legislators approved a five-year term for
presidents, rejecting by 305-223 a proposal to set the term at four
years.
   The present presidential term is for six years, and Sarney was
installed in office in 1985.
   Sarney had opposed a change to the parliamentary system, saying
it would bring further economic and social chaos.
   Opponents argued that a parliamentary structure was an option
for the nation that emerged in 1985 from 21 years of military rule.
   ``Presidentialism doesn't exist and doesn't work anywhere but
the United States,'' said Sen. Affonso Arinos of the Liberal Front
Party. ``Military, authoritarian and dictatorial regimes emerged
mostly because of presidentialism in Brazil.''
   Leftist legislators opposed to Sarney backed the presidential
system. But they also demanded direct presidential elections this
year with Sarney stepping down in March 1989. Sarney said he would
leave office in 1990.
   ``We didn't want a queen of England, we want elections, direct
elections this year,'' said Rep. Jose Genoino of the leftist
Workers' Party.
   The lawmakers have been meeting since February 1986 to rewrite
the constitution.
   Sarney, 57, was elected vice president in a 1985 electoral
college election organized by the outgoing military regime. But
President-elect Tancredo Neves died before inauguration in March
1985 and Sarney took power as the nation's first civilian president
since a 1964 military coup.
   Brazilians have not voted directly for the presidency since 1960.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
