<1ST_LINE>a i AM-Argentina-English Adv30   03-22 0934</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina-English, Adv 30,0965</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv30</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, March 30 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Argentines May Dislike the English but They Love Their Language</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDALL HACKLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>QUILMES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Argentines may have fallen out with
the English over the Falkland Islands, but the upper-crust still
likes the way they talk.
   That is evident on the quaintly British campus of St. George's
College in Quilmes where Argentine children are still being sent to
learn English with the proper accent and prepare to go on to
Cambridge or Oxford.
   For as much as $7,800 a year in tuition, the 330 boys and girls
who attend the only British-style boarding school in Argentina are
assured as fine an education as if they lived in England, said
headmaster Graham Sims.
   Ninety instructors from Britain teach children aged 3 through 18
the fundamentals as well as computer programming, chemistry,
advanced mathematics and English literature.
   English at St. George's is the most common classroom language,
although Argentina's Education Ministry requires that bilingual
schools teach some courses in Spanish.
   The school operates on British discipline.
   ``We are very strict and that means the boys and girls are not
allowed any physical contact in school. Holding hands is out,''
Sims said in an interview. ``We've all got to lead disciplined
lives. If not we become pretty hopeless human beings.''
   St. George's is in Quilmes, a city of 100,000 people 12 miles
south of Buenos Aires. Once a popular residential area for the
British who earlier this century built most of Argentina's
railways, it is most noted now for a brewery and the school.
   Dotting the 62-acre campus are a chapel, rugby fields, gardens,
two swimming pools, a horse-riding academy and dormitories where
students are required to place their folded clothes and towels on
racks in the bathrooms.
   The only inkling this is not Britain is when schoolchildren
break into Spanish after class or when Argentina's flag is raised
each morning outside the administration building.
   ``It really is a little piece of Britain in Argentina,'' said
Ray McKay, counselor at the Lincoln School in northern Buenos
Aires, the only American school in Argentina. ``The student body is
almost all Argentines from wealthy families who want their kids to
speak English.''
   Lincoln has 550 students, most of them children of U.S. Embassy
personnel, diplomats and businessmen in Argentina. Its schedule
follows the U.S. system, with summer vacation from June through
August. The English-style and Argentine schools have their vacation
from January to March, the Southern Hemisphere summer.
   St. George's, founded in 1898, is considered one of the four top
schools in Argentina for learning English.
   ``We offer a 24-hour-a-day education experience,'' said Peter
Stoyle, director of studies at St. George's. Wakeup calls are at
6:30 a.m. and lights are out across campus by 10 p.m., which is the
normal dining hour in Argentina.
   Student Magdalena Winter, 15, hopes someday to become a diplomat.
   ``Most people here believe we're getting a very good education
so we learn to put up with things that maybe we don't always
like,'' she said.
   Three other top British-style schools, St. Andrew's, St.
Catherine's and Northlands, are in the northern suburbs of Buenos
Aires, but they do not offer boarding.
   St. Andrew's is observing the 150th anniversary of its founding
by Scottish settlers. With 1,900 students, St. Andrew's is the
largest of the British-tradition schools and oldest of the
bilingual schools in Argentina.
   One of its headmasters, Watson Hutton, was credited with
introducing soccer to Argentina at the turn of the century.
   ``Without him there'd be no (Diego) Maradona,'' said headmaster
Kevan Prior, referring to the star of Argentina's 1986 World Cup
champions.
   St. Andrew's has been coed since 1980.
   ``We have a particular ethos, particular spirit, something the
parents of Argentine upper middle-class children choose,'' Prior
said.
   Tuition is $1,600 to $2,400 a year.
   Northlands School near St. Andrew's is considered the top girls
school in Argentina. Headmistress Jehane Taylor takes pains to
separate her school from anything British.
   ``This is an Argentine school with no funds from England that
happens to teach English,'' she said.
   Sensitivities over anything British comes from problems
regarding the Britain's Falkland Islands in the South Atlantic, off
Argentina. The Argentines have claimed them since 1833 and here
they are called the Malvinas. Argentina invaded the Falklands in
April 1982 and were driven off by British forces three months later.
   ``During the Falklands these British-style schools got lots of
phone treats, some of them obscene,'' said McKay of the American
school. ``Some kids were pulled out by their parents and there were
some classroom tiffs over the so-called imperialist British.
   ``So it's really kind of remarkable now that so many Argentines
send their kids to these schools. I suppose it's kind of the snob
thing to do.''
   St. Catherine's School for girls, like St. George's, offers the
international baccalaurete program for its 1,100 students. The
program allows students to enter colleges in the United States at a
second-year level or qualify for advanced study in England.
   A St. Catherine's coordinator, Marie Philpotts, described the
school as ``British to a certain extent.'' Tuition ranges from
$1,050 to $1,600 a year compared to $1,000 to $2,000 a year at
Nortlands.
   Mrs. Taylor, head of Northlands, said the tradition of
Argentines sending their children to English-style schools goes
back several generations.
   The school, founded by a British governess in 1920, gives 985
students ``an Anglo-Saxon point of view and a Latin point of
view,'' giving students ``different ways of looking at knowledge,''
Mrs. Taylor said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>End for Adv Wed AMs, March 30</HEAD>
