<1ST_LINE>a a AM-ReligionToday Adv25   03-22 0822</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Religion Today, Adv 25,0850</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, March 25 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Ouster Of Baptist Liaison With Jews Opens Old Wound</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto NY90</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ouster by Southern Baptist officials of a
scholar for contending that God upholds his compact with Judaism
opens an old wound in Christian-Jewish relations.
   It also pointed to a lingering, but increasingly repudiated,
attitude in some church quarters.
   Historical church theories that God revoked his commitment to
Jews, replacing it with a pact with Christianity, figured for
centuries in anti-Jewish prejudice and persecution.
   However, many Protestant and Roman Catholic scholars have
rejected that notion, as have some denominations.
   ``If God's covenant has been broken with the Jews, it's
reasonable that other covenantal relationships might also be
broken,'' says the Rev. George J. Sheridan, who was removed from
his post.
   ``Therefore, we in the church would be an endangered species.''
   However, Sheridan contends that God doesn't go back on his
promises, either to the mother religion, Judaism, or to the
offspring of it, Christianity, and he cites Romans 11:
   ``Remember, it is not you (Christians) that support the root,
but the root that supports you ... and so all Israel will be saved
... For the gifts and call of God are irrevocable.''
   Sheridan, 46, of Union City, N.J., was dismissed after 13 years
of working with Jews as regional director of the interfaith witness
department of the Southern Baptist Home Mission Board.
   ``My point is that the covenant with the Jews was not
abrogated,'' he said in an interview, maintaining that they are
saved through God's mercy, just as are Christians, but without
accepting Jesus.
   Christians, unlike Jews, needed Jesus to draw them to the one,
same God, Sheridan said.
   A letter notified him he was relieved from his assignment Jan.
31 because of his ``theological position relative to evangelizing
the Jewish people'' _ something he opposed as unnecessary.
   It also offends Jews, implying their faith is useless.
   Sheridan's ouster ``strikes me like the Middle Ages,'' commented
Rabbi Leon Klenicki, director of the interfaith department of the
Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith.
   In Atlanta, the mission board's president, the Rev. Larry Lewis,
said Sheridan's view wasn't acceptable. The board lately came under
fundamentalist sway, as have most of the 14.6-million-member
denomination's agencies.
   Lewis said, ``The Bible teaches there is no other way to
salvation except through a personal faith in Jesus Christ.''
   Sheridan, with degrees from Southern Baptist Theological
Seminary in Louisville, Ky., and Princeton Theological Seminary in
Princeton, N.J., linked his ouster to the heresy of Marcionism.
   ``That's what this thing borders on,'' he said. ``The Marcion
heresy was that the God in Jewish Scripture (the Old Testament) is
different than the God of the gospels (New Testament).''
   Marcion, a second-century preacher whose views were condemned by
the church, rejected the Old Testament, which historic Christianity
accepts along with the New Testament.
   ``I believe in Jesus Christ,'' Sheridan said, ``that Jesus
Christ is God, but for me to believe that the God of Jesus Christ
is not the God of Jews rooted in their Scripture is the heresy of
two different gods.''
   Sheridan said that after a tense meeting with officials last
year, he wrote a letter at their request outlining his views, and
his dismissal followed. In it, he said in part:
   ``The Scriptures provide a chronicle of how God has taken the
initiative in concrete historical ways to save God's people...
   ``In the Bible the term `savior' properly is ascribed to
God...In the Christian gospel, God comes to the world in the person
of a man, Jesus...In the New Testament, the title `savior' is
applied sometimes to God and sometimes to Jesus Christ,''
emphasizing that he bears ``the authority of God.''
   ``This established that Jesus Christ is the revelation of God
who, as the Hebrew Scriptures teach, is the one and only `savior'
of the people of God. To distinguish between the God revealed in
the Hebrew Scriptures and the God revealed in Jesus Christ is, for
Christians, a heresy...
   ``God saves his people, the entire Bible asserts. This salvation
is not brought brought about by the goodness of the people, but by
the merciful initiative of God. Jesus Christ provides the way for
the nations to be engrafted into the people of God...
   ``I find in the entire Christian Bible no hint that God cancels
out lovingkindness freely dispensed or promised. In fact, we find
the gifts and the call of God are irrevocable.
   ``For this biblical reason...I believe that the Jews of today,
as ever, receive salvation through their having been chosen by God
in covenant with Abraham, Moses and the prophets.
   ``The election of the church is prefigured in this election of
Israel, and if the election of one is subjection to cancellation,
so, too, is the election of the other.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, March 25</NOTE>
