<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   03-22 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Adv00</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN WINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Savage'' (RCA) _ Eurythmics
   
   On ``Savage,'' the Eurythmics are misanthropic, caustic and a
bit paranoid. They're strong on attitude but weak on delivery.
   The record emphasizes a big beat, mostly via programmed drums
and bass lines that make for mechanical music. Worst is the opening
cut, ``Beethoven (I Love to Listen to).'' Add singer Annie Lennox's
dry delivery, and the resulting sounds have both the pulse and
personality of a locomotive.
   Lost in the thundering shuffle are the lyrics by Lennox and Dave
Stewart, which positively snarl on paper. Lennox spends much of the
record telling us that love is cheap and men merit no respect.
``Love is a temple, love is a shrine, buy some love at the five and
dime,'' she sings on the best song, ``You Have Placed a Chill In My
Heart.''
   Oddly, Lennox and Stewart ease up on the syncopation on the last
two cuts of the record, which closes with the upbeat ``Brand New
Day.'' After 11 songs filled with cynicism, it's hard to believe
the optimistic message is sincere. But maybe it presages more
subtlety and finesse on their next record.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Live _ The Road'' (MCA) _ The Kinks
   
   It's bad news when the best thing on an album titled ``Live _
The Road'' is a studio cut. But that's the case with the Kinks'
latest record.
   It opens with a new composition, Ray Davies' engaging,
autobiographical ``The Road.'' ``There's gas in my tank, and I've
still got a ways to go,'' the veteran rocker sings. On the rest of
the album, recorded in concert last summer, the Kinks play with the
verve of a driver intent on getting good mileage.
   There are stirring moments in the 50 minutes of music: ``Come
Dancing,'' sparked by Dave Davies' fluid guitar work; the
provocative ``Art Lover,'' which only Ray Davies could have
written; and the rocking ``Destroyer'' and ``Around the Dial.''
   But ``It,'' the album's other new song, and ``Cliches of the
World'' are too long and too ambitious. The other performances are
routine, with riffs and tempos that belong in a heavy metal cutout
bin.
   ``Live _ The Road'' is not a bad set, and the Kinks deserve
credit for reprising some of their lesser-known material from the
1980s (at one point they tease the audience with a false start of
``Lola''). But from such a well-respected band, it's a
disappointment.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
