<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, April 1-3 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Star Watch: George Burns _ Forever Young</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Burns paced the darkened backstage
of the Caesars Palace showroom, hummed softly and flicked ashes
from his ever-present cigar.
   ``I'm just making sure I can still walk,'' he dead-panned to a
couple sitting in the wings.
   Moments later, as the orchestra struck up ``Ain't Misbehavin',''
Burns sauntered on stage to a standing ovation, a rarity for the
opening of a Las Vegas show. He would receive two more before
exiting an hour later _ a sign of the respect audiences hold for
this man who was a vaudeville star in their grandparents' time.
   At 92, Burns shows no signs of slowing down. He's a regular at
the Palace on the Las Vegas Strip and at other Caesars properties
in Lake Tahoe, Nev., and Atlantic City, N.J. His pace would
satisfy, and slow, most performers half his age.
   However, Burns has just completed a new movie, ``18 Again,''
which opens April 9. And he's working on a new book about the one
true love of his life, Gracie Allen, his stage partner, confidante,
best friend and wife for 38 years until her death in 1964. The
book, ``Gracie: A Love Story,'' is due out in October.
   Irving Fein, Burns' longtime friend and manager for 14 years,
says the book will be ``a loving, warm story about Gracie Allen
that has never before been told.
   ``George will always have this special love for Gracie,'' Fein
said during Burns' recent appearance here. ``He goes to her grave
(in Los Angeles) once a month. He talks to her, tells her
everything he's doing. He'll say `I just got back from Vegas. We
did great.' Or `I just finished a movie. It's about me and my
grandson and how we switch places.'
   ``He'll spend a lot of time just standing there talking to her,
letting her know what's happening in his life. She's still a very
special part of his life.''
   Burns gives his long-time mate the credit for his success.
   ``If it wasn't for Gracie, I wouldn't be here,'' he said,
puffing on a cigar in his dressing room before a recent Caesars
show. He crossed the room to a bar, poured a cup of coffee, then
settled in a chair next to the piano.
   Morty Jacobs, his pianist of 18 years, began picking out tunes
Burns sang as a teen-ager three-quarters of a century ago.
   ``What key is that?'' Burns inquired of Jacobs. ``Take it half a
tone lower.''
   ``We'll do some lovin', then you'll ask for more,'' Burns sang,
tapping shiny patent leather shoes on the dressing room floor.
   Onstage, opening act Susan Anton was belting out a raucous
version of ``Old Time Rock and Roll,'' a signal for Burns to exit
his dressing room. He walked briskly back and forth in the darkened
area, stopping to talk to workers or softly humming some of the
songs he would sing.
   Miss Anton dedicated her final song, ``Forever Young,'' to
Burns. He took a long drag on his cigar, then entered to the
standing ovation.
   ``In 1981 I played God,'' he said, referring to the first of
three movies in which he played the deity. ``I was a nervous wreck.
We're both the same age, but we grew up in different neighborhoods.
   ``Why shouldn't I play God? Anything I do at my age is a miracle.
   ``I've written six books. That's pretty good for a guy who only
read two.''
   His formula for acting?
   ``If the director wants me to cry, I think of my sex life.
   ``If the director wants me to laugh, I think of my sex life.''
   About that sex life?
   ``I'd go out with women my age, but there are no women my age.''
   Another put-down: ``There isn't anything I can't do now that I
couldn't do when I was 18 _ which shows you how pathetic I was at
18.''
   Burns smokes 15 to 20 cigars and drinks several martinis a day.
   What do his doctors think of that?
   ``They're all dead.''
   Burns began in show business at the age of 8, quitting school to
form a group of child singers known as the Peewee Quartet. Born
Nathan Birnbaum to a poor family on New York's Lower East Side, he
had only to look to his 11 brothers and sisters for his own
ensemble.
   He bounced around the vaudeville circuit until he was 27. ``Then
people discovered I had a talent _ a big talent. I was married to
her for 38 years.
   ``Gracie didn't tell a joke, she explained it,'' Burns recalled
of nearly four decades as straight man for the zany comedian.
   Burns admits he was devastated _ personally and professionally _
by Miss Allen's death in 1964. A decade later, in August 1974,
Burns underwent a triple heart bypass. At age 78, he was the oldest
bypass patient in history at that time.
   Four months after his surgery, Burns' longtime friend, Jack
Benny died. Benny had been scheduled to star in the movie ``The
Sunshine Boys.'' Burns was tabbed to take his place, won an Academy
Award for best supporting actor, and was on his way to his second
time around.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, April 1-3 and Thereafter</NOTE>
