<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Thorogood Adv01-03   03-22 0720</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Thorogood, Adv 01-03,0739</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Adv01-03</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, April 1-3 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: Thorogood and Co. Bring Bar Band to Arena Rock</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the past decade, George Thorogood has gone
from playing hole-in-the-wall saloons to headlining stadiums. But
the whiskey-voiced rocker figures his career holds a few more
roadhouse bars before he hits the retirement home.
   ``I can't wait until I become a has-been _ a has-been that never
was, actually,'' he said with a cackle. ``I can't wait till that
happens, because I know I can make a living playing bars. And have
a lot of fun _ a great time.''
   Which is, he says, what his band The Destroyers are having now
on their national tour _ although Thorogood makes no bones about
saying they'd rather play Stubb's Barbecue, a small Texas blues
bar, than Madison Square Garden.
   ``We started out, and still are, a bar band,'' said Thorogood,
whose career has kept alive the sound of Muddy Waters, Howlin' Wolf
and other blues legends. ``It's just that the bars are a little
bigger these days.''
   Thorogood and company are to blame for that. Since 1977, they've
cranked out a series of successful albums and singles, starting
with a remake of Hank Williams' ``Who Do You Love?'' on their debut
album and stretching to the current LP ``Born to Be Bad.''
   Despite his success, Thorogood has not catered to Top 40 radio,
studiously avoided studio tricks and stayed about as far from the
mainstream as any contemporary band can.
   ``Even if I tried, I'm not going to be able to get out of this
style of playing,'' Thorogood said during a Manhattan stop in the
tour. ``There might be a different hook here or there, but
basically it's going to be your two-, three-chord rock or your
slow, tough-guy blues.
   ``I don't want to change that, and I couldn't if I wanted o,
because I have tried _ I have sat down and tried to play other
styles of stuff, and it was a disaster.''
   With that in mind, Thorogood and band included some classic
covers on the new album: Elmore James' ``Shake Your Money Maker,''
Chuck Berry's ``You Can't Catch Me'' and Hank Snow's ``I'm Movin'
On.''
   Thorogood also wrote several songs in the same vein for ``Born
to Be Bad'' _ songs which, he stressed, carry no deeper message
than ``let's all have a good time.''
   ``I figure, I'm not operating on anybody's skull here. It's not
brain surgery, man,'' said Thorogood. ``It's just two chords. And
people are supposed to dance to it and laugh at it, and two hours
later forget about it. That's what entertainment is.''
   Thorogood was introduced to the blues scene in his native
Delaware, an area he quickly admits was no roots-rock hotbed.
   ``I was so foolish staying in the Philadelphia area, because
it's not a blues area,'' he said. ``If I had my wits about me, I
would have gone to San Francisco or Chicago, where people know this
sound their whole lives.''
   But no matter where he he grew up, Thorogood believes it was
inevitable he'd end up listening to Muddy Waters and Chuck Berry.
   ``I think the things you're supposed to hear in your life will
come to you. You don't go finding them; they come to you,'' he
said. ``So it just came to me a little later.''
   Once Thorogood heard the music, he began taking it to audiences
with the zeal of a Bible Belt preacher delivering the good word.
   The band is constantly on the road: In 1981, they went on a
``50-50 Tour'' in which they played in all 50 states on 50
consecutive dates.
   And while they have moved up from bars to arenas, Thorogood
figures that sooner or later he'll be back on the roadhouse circuit
playing for barroom crowds, enjoying his golden years with a cold
beer and some hot licks.
   ``I always thought, wow, wouldn't it be great if I did `Bad to
the Bone' and I was 60, and I had on a gut on me like (Jackie)
Gleason, and I walked out there with a T-shirt that said something
like, `Sex Machine.'''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, April 1-3</NOTE>
