<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc.'s time under bankruptcy court
protection may be drawing nearer a close as the last shareholder
votes are counted on a proposed financial reorganization plan.
   At a hearing beginning today in White Plains, N.Y., U.S.
Bankruptcy Court Judge Howard Schwartzberg is expected to announce
the result of that balloting and listen to final comments by
parties to the case.
   The judge then must decide whether or not to confirm the plan,
enabling Texaco to step from under court protection under Chapter
11 of the federal bankruptcy code.
   Texaco filed for protection from its creditors last April to
avoid having to post a multibillion-dollar bond while appealing a
$10.3 billion judgment held against it by Pennzoil Co.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government says it posted a $23.9
billion deficit in February after a $16.1 billion surplus the
previous month.
   The Treasury Department said Monday that for the first five
months of the current budget year, the government has run up a
deficit of $89.7 billion, 4.9 percent lower than the red ink
incurred in the same period a year ago.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investment in plant and equipment by U.S.
business is likely to increase about 8.8 percent this year but only
0.5 percent in 1989, according to a new survey.
   Manufacturers are likely to lead the way this year with a 12.5
percent increase in investment, but trail in 1989 with a 2.9
percent decrease, Data Resources Inc. of Lexington, Mass., said in
a survey released Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Electric Co. has launched a
double-pronged attack in its bid for Roper Corp. by boosting its
tender offer to $507 million and filing lawsuits challenging
Roper's agreement to merge with Whirlpool Corp.
   GE's latest bid, up $9 a share to $54 for Roper's outstanding
stock, surpasses the $50-a-share sweetened bid Whirlpool made last
week for the appliance and lawn equipment maker.
   Roper said it is reviewing GE's new tender offer and plans to
hold a board meeting this week to determine the company's position
on the sweetened bid.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investment group that owns an 11 percent
stake in Kansas City Southern Industries Inc. is offering $60 a
share, or about $594 million, for the rest of the railroad
concern's common stock.
   Kansas City Southern, which also has interests in financial
services, said Monday its board would consider the all-cash
proposal soon.
   The company has nearly 11.1 million shares outstanding, and the
investment group led by Howard Kaskel claims it controls about 1.2
million shares.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   R.H. Macy & Co. Inc. has cleared some hurdles in
the path toward winning Federated Department Stores Inc. while its
rival, Campeau Corp. reconsidered its strategy following a major
court defeat.
   Macy announced Monday that the waiting period during which the
federal government could ask for information about the possible
antitrust implications of a Macy-Federated merger had expired with
no further requests. A request would extend the waiting period
automatically.
   Meanwhile, Campeau was trying to decide how to proceed following
a federal judge's determination that Federated's ``poison pill''
takeover defense could stand.
