<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 0030EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Roper Bjt   03-22 0654</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Roper, Bjt,0674</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Roper To Study Revised GE Bid On Heels Of GE Lawsuit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roper Corp., which resisted General Electric
Co.'s previous moves to snatch it from Whirlpool Corp., says it
will study GE's latest, sweetened $507 million buyout offer.
   The giant appliance maker's new offer for Roper came on Monday
just hours after GE filed suit challenging Roper's agreement to
merge with Whirlpool in a $470 million deal.
   GE on Monday increased its tender offer for Roper's outstanding
shares by $9 to $54 a share, topping Whirlpool's $50-a-share offer
in a bidding war that, according to some analysts, may have run its
course.
   ``The prices are pretty generous to what we on Wall Street would
call the intrinsic value of Roper,'' said Cornelius Sewell, an
analyst with Argus Research Corp.
   Roper rose $2.50 a share to close at $55.50 in composite New
York Stock Exchange trading, adding to Friday's $5.75 a share runup.
   In a statement issued after the stock market closed, Roper said
it was reviewing GE's new tender offer and planned a board meeting
later in the week to determine the company's position on the
sweetened bid.
   Whirlpool began the legal battle last week, suing GE on the
grounds the Fairfield, Conn.-based conglomerate tried to
``sabotage'' a Whirlpool-Roper merger with a competing bid.
   GE said Roper rebuffed a merger proposal last November, and
contended the Roper board authorized a $37.50-a-share merger with
Whirlpool after Whirlpool threatened to mount a hostile takeover
bid, according to Delaware State Court documents.
   GE, which on March 6 made its initial $45-a-share offer, alleged
Roper failed to ``test the price'' before agreeing to merge with
Whirlpool. GE also contended Roper concealed GE's interest in the
company when it advised shareholders to tender their stock to
Whirlpool.
   Roper also gave Benton Harbor, Mich.-based Whirlpool a so-called
``lockup option'' to purchase 1.6 million newly issued shares for
$37.50 each if their deal fell through, which would make any
subsequent Roper acquisition more expensive. GE is seeking to block
the issue and transfer of those shares.
   In a separate suit filed in U.S. District Court in Delaware, GE
claimed both Whirlpool and Roper failed to adequately disclose
terms of their merger agreement under Securities and Exchange
Commission laws and neglected to mention GE's interest in Roper.
   Whirlpool alleged in its suit last week that a GE executive
tried to persuade Roper to break its contract with Whirlpool. The
suit said GE ``intentionally, maliciously and unjustifiedly engaged
in a continuing course of conduct to sabotage'' the deal.
   Part of Whirlpool's lawsuit seeks $117 million in damages, or
the difference between its $50-a-share offer and original offer.
   GE vowed to ``vigorously defend itself'' against the charges and
is seeking to transfer the suit from U.S. District Court in Grand
Rapids, Mich., to federal court in Delaware.
   Roper, headquartered in Augusta, Ga., last week endorsed
Whirlpool's sweetened bid. Robert Cook, Roper's president and chief
executive officer, said then that the company ``has a strong desire
to see this combination successfully completed,'' although he had
no further comment when contacted Monday.
   David Whitwam, Whirlpool's president and chief executive, stated
Monday that his company remains committed to pursuing its attempts
to block GE and acquire Roper.
   Analysts say a Roper-Whirlpool merger would move Whirlpool ahead
of GE as the nation's leading appliance maker. For GE, acquiring
the appliance and lawn equipment maker would enhance its supplier
relationship with Sears, Roebuck & Co. and give it a valuable share
of the gas stove market.
   Analysts estimate that roughly two-thirds of Roper's sales come
from its agreement to supply Sears with its kitchen appliance and
lawn equipment products.
   GE's bid stems from its decision last year to expand its market
share by selling gas stoves. Rather than manufacture the gas
stoves, GE now purchases them from four companies, including Roper,
said GE spokesman Jack Batty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
