<DOCNO> AP880322-0263 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 0048EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Federated Bjt   03-22 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Federated, Bjt,0605</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Macy Irons Out Some Wrinkles While Campeau Plans Strategy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Still smarting from a major courtroom defeat
last week, Campeau Corp. says it is working on other options in its
battle to acquire Federated Department Stores Inc.
   Campeau got another legal setback on Monday and faces further
courtroom entanglements over its attempt to acquire Federated,
which has accepted a rival offer from R.H. Macy & Co. Inc.
   A federal judge on Monday rebuffed Campeau's proposal to extend
its $6.18 billion tender offer so it would expire simultaneously
with Macy's offer, if he removed Federated's ``poison pill''
takeover defense.
   Judge Leonard Sand, in a closed-door session, said the poison
pill would remain in place at least until Federated makes a final
recommendation to its shareholders, said Campeau spokeswoman Nancy
Raeside.
   In a key ruling on Friday, the judge had denied Campeau's
request to block the use of Federated's poison pill, which Campeau
says will prevent it from completing any takeover of Federated.
   The defense makes a takeover prohibitively expensive by allowing
Federated shareholders to buy more of the company's stock at a
steep discount.
   Margaret Nicolaides, a Campeau spokeswoman, said the
Toronto-based developer was ``definitely working on other
options.'' She said she could not elaborate on what those options
were.
   However, there were reports that Campeau was considering
sweetening its bid or proposing a friendly merger. Neither tactic
has met with success in the past during the company's months-long
quest for Federated.
   In another matter, Judge Sand scheduled a Wednesday hearing over
a Macy complaint that Campeau made false statements in full-page
advertisements in Thursday editions of the New York Times and Wall
Street Journal.
   Separately, Macy announced that the waiting period during which
the federal government could ask for information about the possible
antitrust implications of a Macy-Federated merger had expired with
no further requests. A request would extend the waiting period
automatically.
   The retailer also confirmed it had agreed to sell 11 of
Federated's 14 Abraham & Straus stores if it wins the takeover
fight. The agreement, reached with New York state Attorney General
Robert Abrams over the weekend, calls for Macy to divest New
York-area A&S stores because they are in direct competition with
Macy branches.
   In Georgia, where Macy stores would compete with Federated's
Rich's chain, Attorney General Michael Bowers said the state will
not oppose a Macy-Federated combination. But analysts speculate
that Macy might sell the Rich's stores anyway.
   Macy is conducting a $6.3 billion tender offer for Federated
under an agreement with Federated management.
   Macy is offering $77.35 a share in cash for 70.43 million
Federated shares, for a total of $5.4 billion. Macy would exchange
shares in the merged company, Macy's-Federated Inc., and issue
convertible debt securities for the remainder of Federated's 89.5
million outstanding shares. Analysts have estimated the total value
of the offer at $6.3 billion.
   Federated stock rose 62{ cents to $66.87{ in New York Stock
Exchange composite trading Monday.
   Campeau's bid is a two-step, all-cash package that would be
worth $68 a share, or $6.18 billion. It is offering $75 each for
70.5 million Federated shares, and proposes to acquire the
remaining stock for $44 cash per share in a subsequent merger.
   Macy's offer expires at midnight EST April 4. The Campeau offer
must remain open at least until midnight Friday, pending a
Securities and Exchange Commission ruling on whether Campeau must
submit documents on its financing for the takeover.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880322-0264 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 0049EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EasternAirlines Bjt   03-22 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Eastern Airlines, Bjt,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Pleased With Sanctions Against Eastern Airlines</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Time of filing of stay unknown, top prospects uncertain. Also
moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The union trying to prevent Eastern Airlines
from selling its lucrative East Coast air shuttle says it is happy
with penalties a federal judge has levied on the carrier, but the
company says it plans to appeal the sanctions.
   U.S. District Judge John H. Pratt on Monday said he would fine
Eastern $10,000 per day if the airline commits any future
violations of a court order that had blocked the shuttle deal.
   Pratt also ordered Eastern to halt all efforts to get government
permission to go through with the sale. And he said the airline's
top officials would have to write to all 32,000 Eastern employees,
informing them that the carrier had flouted an earlier court order
and promising that no further violations would occur.
   ``He imposed most of the sanctions we asked for,'' Edgar N.
James, a lawyer for the International Association of Machinists and
Aerospace Workers said. ``There weren't any surprises, but it's
pretty strong.''
   But company officials insisted their court fight was not over.
   ``Eastern continues to believe strongly that we have not
violated any court orders,'' the company said in a written
statement read by spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak from the airline's
headquarters in Miami.
   John J. Gallagher, Eastern's attorney, said the airline would go
to court today to appeal the penalty and the original finding of
contempt.
   Pratt found Eastern in contempt on March 10 for violating an
order he had issued July 2. That order had forbidden the company
from changing working conditions of the 12,000 mechanics and other
ground workers represented by the machinists.
   Eastern, owned by Texas Air Corp., announced Feb. 5 that it
would sell its shuttle to a newly created Texas Air subsidiary for
$225 million. The shuttle flies between Washington, New York and
Boston.
   Frank Lorenzo, chief executive of Texas Air and Eastern, has
argued that financially ailing Eastern needed the cash. But union
leaders have insisted the move was aimed at stripping labor of
power at the carrier by transferring thousands of workers to
another corporate entity within Texas Air.
   The machinists' union had asked Pratt to force a court
appearance by Lorenzo to discuss the shuttle deal. But in his
ruling Monday, Pratt said Lorenzo could send another corporate
representative.
   The union had also asked Pratt to fine Eastern $20,000 daily for
future violations of the judge's orders. The judge instead ruled
the airline would face $10,000-a-day fines for violations committed
after April 5.
   Pratt did not grant a union request that the airline restore the
jobs of all Eastern employees who quit because of the announcement
that the shuttle would be sold.
   In 1986, Texas Air, also the corporate parent of Continental
Airlines, took over Eastern, a large carrier that lost $182 million
last year.
   Since that time, Lorenzo has sought wage concessions from unions
and has tried selling several of Eastern's most profitable assets
to other Texas Air subsidiaries that he also controls. Unions
representing Eastern employees have waged well-publicized fights to
thwart him.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880322-0265 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 0050EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-KCSouthern Bjt   03-22 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-KC Southern, Bjt,0581</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investor Group Offers $60 a Share for Kansas City Southern
Industries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investor Howard Kaskel, who says his plans to
boost shareholder values have been rebufffed repeatedly by Kansas
City Southern Industries Inc., is moving to take over the company.
   An investment group led by Kaskel said Monday it was offering
$60 cash a share, or about $594 million, for the 89 percent of the
railroad concern's common stock that it does not already own.
   The New York investor, in a letter to the company's management,
also indicated he would attempt to place his own slate of directors
on the Kansas City Southern board if it rejected or failed to act
on the buyout offer by April 4.
   Kansas City Southern, which also has interests in financial
services, said its board would consider the all-cash proposal soon
at a special meeting.
   The company has nearly 11.1 million shares outstanding, and the
Kaskel group claims it controls about 1.2 million shares.
   In New York Stock Exchange trading, Kansas City Southern jumped
$8.75 a share to $55 on Monday.
   Kaskel outlined the merger proposal in a letter to Landon H.
Rowland, president and chief executive of Kansas City Southern, and
requested an opportunity to negotiate ``all aspects of the offer,
including price.''
   He said completing the proposal was subject to reaching a
definitive agreement, approval by the requisite number of directors
and stockholders and satisfaction of all regulatory requirements.
   Kaskel said he had made various proposals to company management
over the past eight months on ways to maximize shareholder values.
   ``Unfortunately, you have rejected each of my suggestions,''
Kaskel wrote.
   In addition, he said he found it ``dismaying'' that the board
erected obstacles ``designed to entrench itself and to prevent
stockholders from realizing a full return on their investment.''
   Among these steps, Kaskel cited the recent issuance of about 1.4
million shares, or almost 15 percent of the company's
then-outstanding common stock, to employee stock ownership plans at
$49 a share.
   ``This could only have been motivated by the board's desire to
place substantial voting power in its hands as a means of
opposing'' proposals that may be brought before its shareholders,
the letter read.
   Kaskel also cited Kansas City Southern's continued efforts to
acquire the Southern Pacific Railroad despite Southern Pacific's
``binding agreement for its sale to the Denver Rio Grande.''
   Other than Rowland's announcement that the board of directors
would consider the offer at a special meeting, Kansas City Southern
indicated it had no further comment until the board had an
opportunity to study the offer.
   Kansas City Southern owns the Kansas City Southern Railroad,
which operates on about 1,500 miles of track in Missouri, Arkansas,
Oklahoma, Kansas, Louisiana and Texas.
   It also owns 87 percent of DST Systems Inc., a Kansas City-based
concern that provides data systems and record-keeping services for
mutual funds, insurance companies and other financial services
providers.
   The company also owns 80 percent of Janus Capital Corp., a
Denver-based concern that provides investment advice and had about
$915 million in funds under management at the end of February,
according to Kansas City Southern's vice president and secretary,
Albert Mauro.
   For the fiscal year ended Dec. 31, Kansas City Southern reported
a profit of $17.7 million, or $1.82 a share, on revenue of $507.6
million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880322-0266 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 0051EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Koppers     03-22 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Koppers,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beazer Willing To Acquire Part of Koppers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British investor pursuing a hostile
takeover of Koppers Co. says he is willing to acquire only the
company's core construction materials business _ which the company
already has said it may sell as a defensive measure.
   Brian C. Beazer, who along with the investment firm Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. has offered to acquire Koppers for $56 a share,
or $1.6 billion, made his offer in a letter to Koppers chairman
Charles R. Pullin on Saturday.
   In the letter, the bidders raised their offer to $56 a share
from the initial $45 a share bid rejected by Koppers, which also
manufactures chemicals.
   Beazer, chairman of the British construction company Beazer PLC,
said previously he would sell the chemicals business if he gained
control of Koppers. His new offer remains open until April 1.
   Koppers has stated that under a defensive recapitalization plan
it is contemplating, it might sell part or all of the construction
materials business to third parties.
   Selling the businesses to Beazer might save the rest of Koppers,
but ``I don't know how bright a move that would be,'' said
securities analyst Gregory Drahuschak of Butcher & Singer in
Pittsburgh. ``It's the lion's share of the company's earnings and
revenue.''
   The construction materials and paving services businesses are on
solid footing after five years of retrenchment at Koppers, he said.
The company reported 1987 earnings of $10.8 million on revenue of
$1.5 billion.
   ``The real persistent grower for the corporation has been the
construction materials business,'' said Robert Kanters, analyst for
Legg Mason Wood Walker Inc. in Pittsburgh. ``The chemicals
business, they feel, is able to do some sustainable growth, but
it's been kind of a more volatile business in recent years.''
   Koppers stock rose $3.75 a share to $57.50 on Monday on the New
York Stock Exchange.
   Beazer proposed meeting Pullin as early as Sunday, but no
meeting was held and none has been planned, Koppers spokesman
Robert O'Gara said Monday.
   O'Gara declined further comment beyond Sunday's announcement
that management would study Beazer's latest proposals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
