<HEAD>Bank Of America Signs Cooperation Agreement With China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bank of America has signed a business
cooperation agreement with the People's Republic of China, and says
it is the first U.S. bank to make such an arrangement.
   The deal was signed in Hong Kong with China Trust and Investment
Corporation for Foreign Economic Relations and Trade, or FOTIC, a
government-owned agency supervising all of China's major trading
enterprises, Bank of America spokesman Jim Mitchell said Monday.
   Under the agreement, Bank of America and FOTIC will cooperate in
several types of business: joint ventures, barter trade, trade
finance, leasing, foreign exchange and the raising and utilization
of funds.
   Bank of America senior vice president Stephen Hunt, the bank's
Hong Kong area manager, signed the agreement with FOTIC's deputy
general manager, Wan Wen-li.
</TEXT>
