<2ND_LINE>PM-Best Western-Asia,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Best Western Plans Push into Asia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Best Western is trying to become Best
Eastern as well.
   The Phoenix-based hotel company says it is undertaking a global
expansion that it hopes will extend its reach to Japan, China and
10 other Asian nations.
   Best Western International Inc. already has affiliate lodging
properties in 33 countries in North America, Europe, the Middle
East and the South Pacific.
   By April, a Hong Kong office will be opened by Carlton Hotels
International of Canada, which will act as recruiting agent for
Best Western in 11 countries, including China. The other countries
are the Phillipines, Taiwan, Brunei, Thailand, Indonesia, Malaysia,
Singapore, Hong Kong, Macao and South Korea.
   Ron Evans, Best Western chief executive officer, said the
company conservatively plans to have links to at least 20 more
hotels within three years through the venture with Carlton and that
company's overseas connections.
   Carlton already is involved in joint venture projects with the
government in China and its development arm is active throughout
Southeast Asia.
   Best Western separately will seek out new member properties in
Japan.
   The efforts are part of a master plan to have Best Western
operations in 50 countries by 1992, increasing its member
properties from some 3,300 to about 4,200.
   The chain also will seek properties in South America, Greece,
Turkey and some African countries.
   Best Western enters the relationship with Carlton already having
made an initial entry into the region by opening a Best Western
Garden Hotel in Singapore last year.
   Evans said Best Western's properties in Asia ``will reflect the
local traditions and ambience, the local architecture.''
   ``That's why foreign countries like Best Western,'' he said.
``We are not converting (foreignn properties) to a cookie-cutter
image. They keep their cultural traditions. We are there only to
enhance their bottom lines.''
</TEXT>
