<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Japan-Markets     03-22 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar and Stocks Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell 1.28 yen on Tokyo foreign exchange
markets today and the leading stock index fell more than 123 points
following declines on markets in London and New York.
   Traders in Tokyo blamed fears over the increasing U.S. trade
deficit and increasing interest rates in the United States for the
declines.
   The dollar opened at 126.96 yen, down 1.39 yen from its close
Friday, when it gained 0.92 yen. Monday was a Japanese national
holiday. In today's trading, the dollar ranged between 126.80 yen
and 127.16 yen before closing at 127.07 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average,
which gained 93.97 points Friday, closed at 25,842.75 points, down
123.51 points, or 0.48 percent.
   Stephen Jennings, a trader for Kleinwort Benson in Tokyo, said
the yen will continue to strengthen based on worries over the U.S.
trade deficit and increasing interest rates as reflected in bond
market increases from 8.5 percent to 8.72 percent.
   He predicted the yen will continue to strengthen and could hit
115 to the dollar by the end of the year if the present trends
continue.
   ``We just don't expect the trade deficit to improve in the
United States,'' he said. ``We expect the decline to begin in the
second half of this year.''
   The dollar's sharp decline in early trading today followed
similar declines on overseas markets Monday, said a currency dealer
at Mitsubishi Bank in Tokyo. The dollar closed down 0.90 yen in New
York and down 1.40 yen in London in Monday's trading.
   ``Tokyo was looking at what was happening in foreign markets and
that caused the dollar to fall below 127 yen,'' said the dealer,
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   He said the Bank of Japan intervened slightly to support the
U.S. currency.
</TEXT>
