<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0004,0472</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with February durable goods
report. Picks up 2nd graf pvs, Separately, the ...
^Durable Goods Orders Fell Sharply Last Month</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders to U.S. factories for ``big ticket'' durable goods
continued to fall sharply in February, the government reported
today.
   The Commerce Department said orders for durable goods, items
expected to last at least three years, totaled a seasonally
adjusted $111.4 billion last month, a 1.8 percent decline which was
identical to the drop in January.
   It was the first time since the spring of 1986 that durable
goods orders had been down for two consecutive months.
   The back-to-back drops surprised analysts, who had been
predicting that orders would turn up again in February following a
January decline which was blamed on volatility in the aircraft
sector.
   Separately, the Treasury Department said Monday the federal
government ran a $23.9 billion budget deficit in February,
following a rare surplus the previous month.
   The $16.1 billion January surplus occurred because that month's
Social Security checks were mailed early and counted in the
December spending figures.
   For the first five months of the current budget year, the
government has run up a deficit of $89.7 billion, 4.9 percent lower
than the deficit incurred in the same period a year ago, according
to Treasury calculations.
   On Wall Street, analysts blamed inflation fears and lingering
post-crash anxiety for the broad decline in stock prices.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell sharply at the
opening and remaining lower throughout the session, closing down
20.23 points at 2,067.14. Broader market indices also fell.
   On the bond market, analysts said prices slipped and interest
rates edged up in light trading that reflected continued
uncertainty about the outlook for inflation and the economy.
   The Treasury's closely watched 30-year bond fell \ point, or
about $2.50 for every $1,000 in face value, as its yield rose to
8.70 percent from 8.67 percent late Friday.
   Foreign exchange trading also was quiet, with the dollar
responding to declines in stocks and bonds by dropping against all
major currencies except the Canadian dollar.
   Oil futures prices rallied, with crude piercing the $17-a-barrel
level before sliding back in late trading following a statement by
Saudi King Fahd on prices and production.
   Fahd suggested that cheating on production quotas and prices by
some members of the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries encouraged further weakness in prices.
   That punctured the rally on the New York Mercantile Exchange,
where contracts for April delivery of West Texas Intemediate, the
benchmark U.S. crude oil, closed at $16.49 per barrel, down 9 cents
from Friday. The April contract had been up as much as 45 cents
during the day.
</TEXT>
