<2ND_LINE>PM-Resorts Interntional, 1st Ld-Writethru,0590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Merv Griffin Boosts Resorts International Bid</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: grafs 1-9 new to UPDATE with Griffin raising bid to $295
million, edits to conform; picks up 8th graf pvs: The non-public
...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Merv Griffin today boosted his bid to acquire
Resorts International Inc. to $295 million while also waging a
court fight to help him win control of the hotel-casino company.
   Griffin Co., the entertainer-businessman's private investment
company, said in a statement today that it decided to increase its
initial bid of $225 million, or $35-a-share, after reviewing
``appraisals regarding the value of Resorts.''
   Based on 6.43 million Class A and Class B shares outstanding,
Griffin's latest bid for both classes of stock is valued at about
$46 a share.
   Separately, Griffin said Monday it filed a $500 million federal
lawsuit in New York against real estate developer Donald Trump and
Resorts' directors, claiming breach of fiduciary duty to
shareholders, among other things.
   Trump, who has voting control of Resorts and is the company's
chairman, sued Griffin last week, accusing the entertainer of
interfering with Trump's contractual agreement to acquire complete
control over Resorts.
   Since making its initial offer Thursday, the Griffin Co. has
indicated it may raise the price if justified by non-public
information from Resorts, a hotel-casino concern with operations in
Atlantic City, N.J. and the Bahamas. Griffin said Trump made that
information available late last week.
   Trump, who is making his own $22-per-share bid for the Resorts
stock he doesn't already own, said he won't boost his offer and has
maintained that he will not sell his shares to Griffin.
   Resorts' board said it decided not to pursue Griffin's initial
bid because, in light of Trump's rejection, the issue was moot.
   Griffin said in a statement today that he would not approve any
deal between Resorts and Trump ``unless class A shareholders
receive a premium over my prior $35-a-share offer.''
   The non-public documents were contained in a Securities and
Exchange Commission filing Trump made on Friday to supplement his
tender offer for Resorts.
   Trump's tender offer, which had been scheduled to expire Monday,
was extended until 12:01 a.m. EST on April 1.
   Griffin's president, Michael Nigris, said the documents included
a $1.3 billion appraisal of Resorts' properties, including a
when-completed value for its luxurious but troubled Taj Mahal
hotel-casino in Atlantic City.
   The appraiser further said it was prepared to support a bank
mortgage loan of $550 million guaranteed by Resorts, Nigris said.
   ``Based on those numbers, we may be able to sweeten our $225
million bid,'' Nigris said Monday.
   The $550 million mortgage is the amount Trump has said will be
needed to complete the Taj Mahal. When Resorts began work on the
project in 1984, it estimated the total price at $535 million. That
figure has since soared to $938.5 million based on Trump's
estimates.
   Trump became involved with Resorts last year when the company
ran into financial difficulties with the proposed 42-floor,
1,250-room Taj Mahal. He bought up most of Resorts' Class B common
stock, which carries 100 votes per share, thus giving him 88
percent voting control.
   He also pledged to help arrange financing for the costly Taj
Mahal project and, in exchange, was granted a five-year operating
contract for Resorts properties valued at about $100 million.
   Resorts has 752,000 Class B shares. It has 5.7 million Class A
shares that carry one vote each.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
