<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Griffin-Trump 1stLd-Writethru   03-22 0843</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Griffin-Trump, 1st Ld-Writethru,0867</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Griffin vs. Trump: Courtly Crooner Battles Brash Builder Over
Resorts</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: INSERTS 1 graf after 3rd graf to UPDATE with Griffin
increasing bid, picks up 4th graf pvs: Both contestants ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>Laserphotos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER GILLOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In this corner: affable, courtly and somewhat
portly Mervyn Edward Griffin, the singer and talk show host who in
recent years has emerged as a wily and successful businessman.
   And in the far corner: brash New York real estate developer
Donald J. Trump, best known for building designer-label
skyscrapers, owning casinos and having more than a modest dose of
braggadocio.
   Late last week, Griffin and Trump squared off over control of
Resorts International Inc., the New Jersey-based hotel-casino
concern that Trump has been offering to acquire for $22 per share,
or about to acquire. Griffin last week offered $35 per share, or
$225 million for the Atlantic City-based company, which also has
operations in the Bahamas.
   The battle escalated today when Griffin increased his bid to
$295 million, which values both Class A and Class B Resorts shares
at about $46 each.
   Both contestants among America's wealthiest men. Trump is listed
by Forbes magazine as worth at least $850 million, and personally
claims $3 billion in wealth. Forbes lists Griffin as worth $300
million.
   For 23 years, Griffin served as host of the popular ``Merv
Griffin Show,'' one of TV's longest-running series, winning 10 Emmy
Awards in the process.
   In 1986, he sold privately-held Merv Griffin Enterprises _
producer of the ``Merv Griffin Show'' and two of his other
successful creations, ``Wheel of Fortune'' and ``Jeopardy'' _ to
Coca-Cola Co. for a reported $250 million. But he remains chairman
of the company, and there is speculation he may take over as host
of ``Wheel of Fortune'' when host Pat Sajak leaves to do his own
show.
   Unlike many entertainers who squander their money through bad
investments and mismanagement, the 63-year-old Griffin has earned a
reputation in Hollywood as a shrewd businessman.
   He has parlayed his entertainment fortune into a business empire
that includes radio stations, a major closed-circuit television
operation widely used at racetracks, and extensive real estate
holdings in Beverly Hills and Northern California.
   Griffin, whose hobbies are music, tennis and good food, lives
stylishly, but not ostentatiously, in a 10,000-square-foot Beverly
Hills mansion near the homes of MCA Inc. Chairman Lew Wasserman and
investor Marvin Davis.
   By contrast, the 42-year-old Trump, who in a decade transformed
himself from a local landlord into a national real estate mogul,
has worked hard to make his name synonymous with ostentation.
   He routinely travels in one of his fleet of five helicopters.
When William Bricker was ousted as chief executive of Dallas-based
Diamond Shamrock Corp. amid criticism over his imperial lifestyle,
Trump purchased his luxurious Boeing 727 private jet.
   His primary home is a $10 million triplex penthouse atop his
glitzy Trump Tower in midtown Manhattan. For relaxation, he
retreats to his 118-room mansion in West Palm Beach, Fla., or his
15-bedroom Georgian manor in Greenwich, Conn.
   ``I can't afford for things not to be the best,'' Trump has
said, contending the glamour attached to his name _ and the
buildings that bear his name _ allows him to attract prices of
$1,700 per square foot for some of his New York condos.
   With a massive war chest to spend, Trump was attracted by the
lure of profits in takeover speculation. In the past year, he
bought stakes in Allegis Corp., Holiday Corp. and Bally Mfg. Co.,
and raked in about $122 million in profits when he later sold the
stock to the company or rival suitors.
   Earlier this year, Trump said he was considering buying up to
24.9 percent of entertainment conglomerate MCA, the parent of
Universal Studios which is frequently mentioned as a takeover
target. But nothing has come of it.
   Likewise, nothing has come of his indications in January that he
might buy up to 15 percent of Federated Department Stores Inc. _
which later became the takeover target of Campeau Corp.
   But when Griffin decided to battle Trump for Resorts, the fight
generally was expected to be short and victorious for Trump.
   Griffin is offering more money, but Trump holds 88 percent of
Resorts' voting power through his ownership of nearly all of its
Class B common stock, which carries 100 votes per share.
   Trump has insisted he will oppose Griffin's proposal, and for
that reason Resorts' board decided it was moot to pursue the issue
with the entertainer.
   But Griffin has persisted. On Monday, he slapped Trump and
Resorts' directors with a $500 million lawsuit, accusing them,
among other things, of breach of fiduciary duty.
   That action came after Trump on Friday filed a $250 million suit
against Griffin and his allies, claiming fraud, stock market
manipulation and interference with Trump's contractual arrangements
with Resorts.
   Meanwhile, some holders of Resorts' 5.7 million Class A shares
who had earlier indicated they would support Trump's $22-per-share
offer now are having second thoughts, their lawyers say.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
