<2ND_LINE>^PM-Natural Gas,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Bars States From Regulating Interstate Gas Company
Securities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A unanimous Supreme Court today ruled that
states are barred from regulating the way interstate natural gas
companies issue securities to finance their operations.
   The court, ruling in a dispute between the Michigan Public
Service Commission and a Detroit-based pipeline, said the Federal
Energy Regulatory Commission has sole authority to regulate such
financing.
   Justice Harry A. Blackmun, writing for the court, said the state
authority sought by the Michigan agency is pre-empted by the
federal Natural Gas Act of 1938.
   A federal appeals court previously had ruled against the
Michigan authorities.
   Michigan law required pipeline companies to get advance approval
from the state Public Service Commission before issuing securities.
   The law was passed to assure that the securities were being
issued for a legal purpose _ one related to the more efficient
delivery of natural gas.
   The regulatory law was challenged in 1984 by American Natural
Resources, which operates a pipeline system carrying natural gas to
distribution customers in Michigan, Illinois, Indiana, Iowa,
Kansas, Missouri, Ohio, Tennessee and Wisconsin.
   According to court documents, the ANR has plans to issue $150
million in securities to help finance projects costing about $560
million.
   Blackmun said the 0 21.90  +.09
