<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet11am     03-22 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 11am,0361</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks turned mixed today, strengthened by
higher bond prices and takeover-related buying, but restrained by
investor reluctance to participate in a market still suffering
post-crash uncertainty.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 1.16 points to
2,068.30 by 11 a.m. on Wall Street.
   Among broader market indicators, the New York Stock Exchange's
composite index of all listed issues rose 0.10 to 151.57. The
American Stock Exchange's market value index rose 0.20 to 298.38.
   Gaining issues barely outnumbered losers on the NYSE, with 613
up, 558 down and 527 unchanged. Volume totaled 45.5 million shares
after 90 minutes.
   Rising prices in the bond market injected some optimism on Wall
Street because they dampened anxiety over inflation and higher
interest rates. Bonds were buoyed by lower oil prices and a
government report that showed a surprising drop in factory orders
for durable goods in February.
   Some stocks also were boosted by rumored and actual takeovers,
reflecting a stunning increase in merger activity over the past
several weeks.
   Nevertheless, stockbrokers said the relatively low volume of
trading and the lack of any significant economic signals showed
that many investors remain reluctant to re-enter the market in the
aftermath of the October crash.
   ``People still are wounded,'' said Philip C. Puccio, manager of
institutional trading at Dillon Read & Co. ``Those wounds have not
scarred over yet. There's fear we could be looking at another
downdraft.''
   Among the most active issues, Lucky Stores shot up 14\ to 46{
after rival chain American Stores announced a $45-a-share tender
offer for the company. Kansas City Southern, target of a
$60-a-share takeover attempt by a New York investor group, advanced
2~ to 57~.
   On Monday the Dow Jones industrials dropped 20.23 to 2,067.14.
Losing issues outnumbered gainers by about 2-to-1 on the New York
Stock Exchange, with 1,042 down, 502 up and 444 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 128.83 million shares against 245.75
million shares the previous session. It was the lowest level since
a 111.58 million-share day Dec. 29.
</TEXT>
