<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 1131EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Robins     03-22 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Robins,0586</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robins To File Another Reorganization Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A.H. Robins Co. says it will submit another
amended reorganization plan as the result of a court hearing on the
adequacy of the company's disclosure statement.
   U.S. District Judge Robert R. Merhige Jr. and U.S. Bankruptcy
Judge Blackwell N. Shelley conducted the hearing Monday, listening
to a series of objections to the disclosure statement.
   The document is the basis by which women with Dalkon Shield
injury claims and other creditors of Robins will decide how to vote
on the company's reorganization plan.
   Robins spokesman Roscoe E. Puckett Jr. said Monday evening that
as a result of the hearing, the company ``will submit a sixth
amended and restated plan of reorganization incorporating certain
changes,'' mostly in the wording of the statement. The new plan
will be filed in bankruptcy court by March 28, he said.
   Merhige set an April 25 deadline for mailing the plan of
reorganization to Dalkon Shield claimants and the company's other
creditors for a vote. The votes must be received by July 11 and a
confirmation hearing will be July 18, Puckett said.
   Merhige also said he hoped to choose by April 11 the five
trustees who will administer the nearly $2.5 billion compensation
fund for Dalkon Shield victims.
   The U.S. Supreme Court, in a related action Monday, let stand a
ruling against a $15 million emergency fund to help women who
became infertile from using the intrauterine device, which Robins
sold in the early 1970s. The Supreme Court also refused to review a
ruling that placed on hold several lawsuits against the insurer of
the IUD.
   Robins has been in Chapter 11 bankruptcy proceedings since
August 1985. The Richmond-based maker of pharmaceuticals sought
court protection from creditors as lawsuits mounted against the
birth control device.
   Joseph F. McDowell III, a Manchester, N.H., attorney for 35
users of the IUD, told Merhige and Shelley the disclosure statement
should not go out because it appeared to give a discharge from
liability to not only Robins but to its insurer, corporate
directors and members of the Robins' family.
   Attorneys for Robins and the Aetna Casualty & Surety Co. that
insured the Dalkon Shield said claimants voting to ratify the
reorganization plan are not prevented from subsequently going to
court. McDowell's objection was overruled.
   An attorney for the Internal Revenue Service challenged an
arrangement for Robins to repay the federal tax agency's priority
claim over a six-year period.
   ``We're being asked to make a $62 million unsecured loan at
prime interest,'' said Stuart Gibson, an IRS tax lawyer.
   Merhige, however, overruled the objection. ``It's your own
fault,'' the judge told Gibson. ``I asked you to settle it ... and
you couldn't do it.''
   In Washington, the Supreme Court upheld the 4th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals' decision to reject the $15 million emergency
fund, which Merhige had approved as a means of helping women still
of child-bearing age to regain fertility through special surgery.
   The emergency fund was challenged by Robins' stockholders as
giving preferential treatment to a select group of claims while the
final reorganization was pending.
   The high court's decision not to review the stay of lawsuits
against Aetna upheld Merhige and the 4th Circuit. The appeals court
said the suits brought by women in Kansas and New Hampshire
inevitably would pull in Robins and thus would detract from the
ongoing bankruptcy proceedings.
</TEXT>
