<2ND_LINE>BC-Ford-Korea,0140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford Will Export Continentals, Sables to South Korea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. said it will begin exporting its
Lincoln Continental and Mercury Sable cars this spring to South
Korea, where they will sell for about three times their U.S. prices.
   South Korea dropped a ban on car imports last year, but tariffs,
taxes and fees remain in place.
   Ford said Monday that the Continentals and Sables will sell in
South Korea for about $42,000 and $75,000, respectively. In the
United States, Sables sell for about $14,000 to $16,000 while
Continentals fetch between $25,000 and $30,000 per car.
   General Motors Corp. also has begun a small-scale program to
ship luxury cars to South Korea. GM said its Buicks and Cadillacs
also will sell for about three times their U.S. prices.
</TEXT>
