<DOCNO> AP880322-0287 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 1232EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Scotus-Taxes     03-22 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Taxes,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Court Rejects IRS Attempt to Impose Stiffer Taxes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today rejected the Internal
Revenue Service's attempt to impose stiffer taxes when individuals
or business partnerships form corporations to obtain financing.
   By an 8-0 vote, the court said real estate developers in
Kentucky should not be subjected to a heavier tax burden because
they formed corporations for the sole purpose of borrowing money.
   Jesse C. Bollinger, either individually or in partnership with
others, developed eight apartment complexes in the Lexington, Ky.,
area beginning in 1968.
   To obtain construction-financing loans, Bollinger formed
corporations to borrow the money at 8 percent interest. Kentucky's
usury law at the time limited the interest non-corporate borrowers
could be charged to 7 percent, and lenders were not willing to
finance Bollinger's projects at that rate.
   When Bollinger and his partners sought to claim business losses
connected with the apartment projects on their individual federal
income taxes, the IRS disallowed it.
   The tax agency said the losses must be attributed to the
corporations, deemed to be the true owners of the apartment
complexes. That designation worked to the tax disadvantage of
Bollinger and his partners.
   A federal appeals court ruled against the IRS, and today's
decision upheld that ruling.
   Writing for the court, Justice Antonin Scalia said the
corporations had been formed for a legitimate, non-manipulative
purpose.
   ``It seems to us that ... tax-avoiding manipulation (is)
adequately avoided when ... the corporation is acting as agent for
its shareholders with respect to a particular asset (the apartment
complexes) is set forth in a written agreement at the time the
asset is acquired,'' Scalia said.
   He also noted that the corporations at issue in this case
functioned ``as agent and not principal with respect to the asset
for all purposes, and the corporation is held out as the agent and
not principal in all dealings with third parties relating to the
asset.''
   The case is Commissioner, IRS vs. Bollinger, 86-1672.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880322-0288 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 1252EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Europe-Takeover     03-22 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Europe-Takeover,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>De Benedetti Wins 3.53 Percent More of Societe Generale in Public
Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italian investor Carlo De Benedetti has
increased his holdings in Societe Generale de Belgique SA by 3.53
percent, but it was not known if his alliance held a majority stake
in Belgium's largest holding company, officials said Tuesday.
   An official at De Benedetti's French investment company Cerus
SA, who asked not to be named, did not know whether the public
offer gave De Benedetti and his allies control of the company.
   This alliance claimed to control 47.01 percent of Societe
Generale's shares before Tuesday. The newly purchased shares would
apparently raise this to 50.54 percent. But the Cerus official said
the 47.01 percent might have included some shares from the public
offer.
   On March 10, a Franco-Belgian alliance opposing De Benedetti
claimed to control 50.7 percent of Societe Generale.
   Tuesday's announcement was the latest twist in one of Europe's
biggest and most complex takeover battles. It failed to provide
definite clues about the outcome, more than two months after De
Benedetti first announced his bid for 166-year-old Societe Generale.
   On March 10, De Benedetti called for shareholders meeting, which
should make it clear which side has a majority. The meeting is set
for April 14.
   Meanwhile, a court case was still pending on a Societe Generale
capital increase to fend off De Benedetti. The ruling in that case
might still dramatically change the stakes each side claims to hold.
   Cerus, the investment firm through which De Benedetti was vying
for control of Societe Generale, said Tuesday it had obtained 1.087
million additional shares, or 3.53 percent of the company's total
share capital, including warrants.
   Cerus launched a public offer for the extra shares on Feb. 15.
The bid was to have expired March 4 but has since been extended.
   The offer was designed to acquire 2.1 million shares, or about 7
percent of the share capital of Societe Generale.
   Cerus offered 8,000 francs, or $228, for ordinary shares in the
last stage of its public offer.
   Reacting to Tuesday's announcement, the management of Societe
Generale, which opposes De Benedetti, said there were no defections
from the Franco-Belgian alliance to Cerus' camp.
   De Benedetti wants to turn Societe Generale into the platform of
a pan-European holding company while the Franco-Belgian group wants
to keep the company firmly entrenched in the Belgian economic
fabric.
   On Tuesday, Societe Generale announced its net profit in 1987
fell 22.1 percent to stand at 4.138 billion francs. Societe
Generale has a stake in over 1,200 companies world-wide and the
government has stressed the company is vital for its investment
strategy, technological development and its relations with its
former colony Zaire.
   The De Benedetti group consists of Cerus, the U.S. investment
bank Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., the Swiss bank Companie de Banque
et d'Investissements and the food giant Nestle SA, two Belgian
partners and several smaller allies.
   The Franco-Belgian alliance is anchored around the French
investment firm Companie Financiere de Suez and Belgium's biggest
insurer, Groupe AG SA and includes several other partners.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
