<1ST_LINE>r f BC-FirestoneMeeting     03-22 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Firestone Meeting,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firestone Shareholders Shorten Name</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHANIE NANO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shareholders attending what could be
Firestone Tire & Rubber Co.'s last annual meeting Tuesday voted to
shorten the company's name but had little to say about Bridgestone
Corp.'s bid for the tire maker.
   About 900 people attended the half-hour meeting, where
shareholders voted to change the company's name to Firestone, Inc.
   Shareholders asked only two questions about Bridgestone's offer
to pay $80 a share, or $2.6 billion, for Firestone's outstanding
shares. Stockholders will meet again April 25 to vote on the tender
offer.
   Bridgestone's bid, which was accepted by Firestone's board,
exceeds a $1.86 billion offer from Italian tire maker Pirelli S.p.A.
   After the meeting, Firestone Chairman John J. Nevin met briefly
with reporters and discussed Firestone's talks with Bridgestone and
Pirelli. Firestone and Bridgestone had planned a 75 percent joint
venture until Pirelli made its unsolicited, $58-a-share bid for all
of Firestone's 32 million outstanding shares.
   Nevin said he told both Bridgestone and Pirelli in negotiations
that Firestone was holding talks with a third firm that he declined
to identify.
   Nevin speculated that Bridgestone was able to make its tender
offer quickly because of its prior knowledge of Firestone.
Bridgestone purchased a plant from Firestone in 1983.
   ``I don't want to speculate on what Bridgestone would have done
under other circumstances. But I think all of the background that
Bridgestone had acquired in discussions with us earlier certainly
made it much more possible for Bridgestone to move quickly in a
two-week period,'' said Nevin.
   ``I think that had we announced in mid-February that the board
of directors had decided to enter into a joint venture with Pirelli
rather than Bridgestone, I think it was improbable that Bridgestone
then would have made an unsolicited tender offer ... This was by no
means an unfriendly action on Bridgestone's part,'' Nevin said.
   He reiterated that he has no plans to buy back from Bridgestone
any of Firestone's non-tire businesses, including its 1,500
MasterCare car repair operations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
