<HEAD>OPEC President's News Conference Postponed Indefinitely</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC President Rilwanu Lukman postponed
indefinitely a scheduled news conference that was expected to have
focused on stabilizing sagging oil prices, the Guardian newspaper
said.
   Last week Nigerian petroleum ministry officials said Lukman
would announce Tuesday new measures to bring stability to the
market.
   But the ministry said the news conference had been called off,
according to the newspaper. No new date was given.
   Lukman has accused the Western news media of trying to
destabilize the oil market to bring down prices, adding OPEC would
not be driven into taking emergency measures to stop the fall of
oil prices.
   He also has vowed the cartel would stand firm on its decision to
produce 15.60 million barrels of oil a day. A barrel of oil is
equivalent to 42 gallons.
</TEXT>
