<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     03-22 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0401</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks were mixed today in another slow trading
session that brokers attributed to underlying investor reluctance
to participate because of post-crash uncertainty.
   ``We're right on the top of the fence and don't know which way
we're going to fall,'' said Robert O'Toole, manager of
over-the-counter trading at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, confined to a
narrow range through most of the session, was up 3.15 points to
2,070.29 by 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Among broader market indicators, the New York Stock Exchange's
composite index of all listed issues rose 0.25 to 151.72. The
American Stock Exchange's market value index rose 0.75 to 298.93.
   Gaining issues narrowly led declines on the NYSE, with 768 up,
648 down and 511 unchanged. Volume totaled a sluggish 97.84 million
shares with two hours of business left.
   Stocks were helped somewhat by a surprising drop in factory
orders for durable goods in February. The report by the Commerce
Department suggested to some strategists that the economy isn't as
strong as previously believed, thereby raising the possibility that
interest rates won't creep up.
   Some stocks also were boosted by rumored and actual takeovers,
reflecting a stunning increase in merger activity over the past
several weeks.
   Nevertheless, stockbrokers said the relatively low volume of
trading and the lack of any significant economic signals showed
that many investors remain reluctant to re-enter the market in the
aftermath of the October crash.
   ``People still are wounded,'' said Philip C. Puccio, manager of
institutional trading at Dillon Read & Co. ``Those wounds have not
scarred over yet. There's fear we could be looking at another
downdraft.''
   Lucky Stores was the most active NYSE issue, jumping 14[ to 46]
in heavy trading after rival chain American Stores announced a
$45-a-share tender offer for the company.
   Speculation about a possible takeover also affected grocery
chain Kroger, which rose 1| to 36[. Speculative buying affected a
range of other companies including Pillsbury, up 1[ to 36[; USG, up
2} to 37|; and Himont, up 3\ to 44\.
   On the Amex, Resorts International Class A shares rose 3| to 32\
after entertainer Merv Griffin boosted his offer for the company in
a takeover battle with developer Donald Trump.
</TEXT>
