<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru f0026 03-22 0201</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0026,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Narrowly Mixed</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with trading activity, closing
index; No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices closed narrowly mixed Tuesday on the
London Stock Exchange, with many stocks depressed by continued thin
trading in the opening days of an extended trading account period.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was down 5.7
points, or 0.3 percent, at 1,835.4 at the close, its worst level
for the day.
   Volume was barely changed at 357.1 million shares, compared with
357.3 million on Monday.
   Shares opened lower following a sharp decline on Wall Street on
Monday, and an attempted rally in mid-morning quickly ran out of
steam. A feeble opening in New York on Tuesday further dampened
sentiment in London afternoon trading.
   Dealers said there was little institutional business as many
investors kept to the sidelines in the early days of the extended
trading account, which runs for three weeks instead of the usual
two to include the Easter holiday weekend. The account began last
Friday afternoon.
   The London exchange divides trading into either two-week or
three-week periods for accounting purposes. Trades generally must
be completed within 10 days of a period ending.
</TEXT>
