<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher; Gold Prices Down</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: version for AMs will move by 5:30 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended slightly higher against most
major foreign currencies in European trading Tuesday. Gold prices
fell.
   Most of the day's activity occurred in cross trades that did not
involve the dollar. The pound and the yen gained against the West
German mark, while the French franc steadied against the mark on
expectations that President Francois Mitterand would announce that
he will run in next month's election.
   With attention focused elsewhere, ``nobody is too sure what to
do with the dollar,'' said Keith Dipple, chief trader at Banque
Francaise du Commerce Exterieur in London.
   Dealers said the yen remains strong because of expectations that
Japanese financial institutions will buy the currency at the end of
the Japanese fiscal year.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends as Europe's begins, the
dollar closed at 127.07 yen, down 1.28 yen from last Friday. The
Japanese markets were closed for a national holiday on Monday.
   Later in London, the dollar was quoted higher at 127.10 yen.
   In London, it cost $1.8300 to buy one pound, more expensive than
$1.8285 late Monday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday,
included: 1.6935 West German marks, up from 1.6880; 1.4015 Swiss
francs, up from 1.3970; 5.7540 French francs, up from 5.7380;
1.9015 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8970; 1,253.25 Italian lire, up
from 1,249.25, and 1.2468 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2494.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $448.75 a troy ounce,
compared with late Monday's $449.50. In Zurich, gold also was
lower, closing at a bid $448.50 down from $450.50 late Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $3.61 an ounce to close at a
bid $451.87.
   Silver bullion prices fell on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $6.46 a troy ounce, compared
with Monday's $6.47.
</TEXT>
