<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks turned narrowly higher today in another
slow trading session that brokers attributed to underlying investor
reluctance to participate in the market because of resilient
post-crash uncertainty.
   ``We're right on the top of the fence and don't know which way
we're going to fall,'' said Robert O'Toole, manager of
over-the-counter trading at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, confined to a
narrow range through most of the session, was up 2.16 points to
2,069.30 by 3 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Among broader market indicators, the New York Stock Exchange's
composite index of all listed issues rose 0.16 to 151.63. The
American Stock Exchange's market value index rose 0.44 to 298.62.
   Gaining issues barely outnumbered declines on the NYSE, with 772
up, 679 down and 502 unchanged. Volume totaled a sluggish 116.58
million shares with an hour of trading left.
