orders for durable goods in February. The report by the Commerce
Department suggested to some strategists that the economy isn't as
strong as previously believed, thereby raising the possibility that
interest rates won't creep up.
   Brokers said the market also received a boost by sharp increases
in borrowed shares sold on the NYSE and Amex in the month ended
last Tuesday. An increase in so-called short sales of stock often
is considered good for the market because it means these borrowed
shares eventually must be repurchased.
   Some stocks also rose because of rumored and actual takeovers,
reflecting a stunning increase in merger activity over the past
several weeks.
   Nevertheless, brokers said the relatively low volume of trading
and the lack of any significant economic signals showed that many
investors remain reluctant to re-enter the market in the aftermath
of the October crash.
   ``People still are wounded,'' said Philip C. Puccio, manager of
institutional trading at Dillon Read & Co. ``Those wounds have not
scarred over yet. There's fear we could be looking at another
downdraft.''
   Lucky Stores was the most active NYSE issue, jumping 14\ to 46{
on volume exceeding 3.4 million shares, after rival chain American
Stores announced a $45-a-share tender offer for the company.
   Speculative buying affected a range of other companies including
Pillsbury, up } to 45; USG, up 3| to 38{; and Himont, up 3~ to 44~.
   On the Amex, Resorts International Class A shares rose 3\ to 31~
after entertainer Merv Griffin boosted his offer for the company in
a takeover battle with developer Donald Trump.
