<HEAD>Wheat, Soybean Futures End Higher; Corn Slips</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat and soybean futures prices ended higher
while corn futures slipped slightly Tuesday at the Chicago Board of
Trade.
   The November-delivery contract for soybeans rose 7 cents to a
contract high of $6.66 a bushel.
   Wheat futures were supported by notions that India, still
suffering the effects of a recent drought, would be offered a
substantial amount of U.S. wheat under the Agriculture Department's
export bonus program.
   Corn prices, however, were pressured by news that Vermont Sen.
Patrick Leahy is moving ahead with legislation that would
ultimately put more corn on the market.
   On the close, wheat was 1 cent to 2} cents higher, with the
contract for delivery in March at $2.99 a bushel; corn was
unchanged to 1{ cents lower, with March at $2.00{ a bushel; oats
were { cent lower to 5 cents higher, with March at $1.95{ a bushel;
and soybeans were 2 cents to 3{ cents higher, with March at $6.29 a
bushel.
