<1ST_LINE>u f AM-FDA-Searle     03-22 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FDA-Searle,0206</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Searle Didn't Withhold Information on Copper-7, FDA Finds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There is no evidence G.D. Searle and Co.
withheld information from the Food and Drug Administration in
winning approval for its Copper-7 intrauterine contraceptive
device, an FDA spokeswoman said Tuesday.
   FDA officials met with Searle representatives last week to
discuss whether company documents recently unsealed in a Minnesota
court case challenging the IUD were available to the government
agency before it approved the device in 1974.
   ``The gist of our initial review is that we've had that
information all along, and that we got it when we initially began
reviewing'' Searle's application for approval of the IUD, said
spokewoman Susan Cruzan.
   ``There's no evidence they didn't give us all the necessary
inforatmion when we began our review,'' she said.
   The Searle IUD remains on the government approved list, but the
company stopped selling it in 1986, citing growing costs from court
suits.
   The company faces about 500 suits by women who claim that the
Copper-7 caused them to develop pelvic infections. The company has
won 14 of the 17 suits that have gone to trial and maintains that
the device was, and is, safe.
</TEXT>
