<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     03-22 0704</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0727</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Platinum Sugres for Second Day</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Platinum future prices surged a second straight day Tuesday at
the New York Mercantile Exchange as a ``whiff of inflation'' and
uneasiness about South Africa rippled through the markets.
   Platinum broke through a barrier at $510 a troy ounce, climbing
$7.70 to $8.30 higher with the contract for March delivery settling
at $510.40.
   On other markets, petroleum futures prices finished mostly
higher in volatile trading; wheat and soybean futures prices were
higher, but corn slipped slightly; and livestock and meat futures
prices were higher across the board.
   ``Platinum is a good indicator of inflationary sentiment,
because it's a precious metal and an industrial metal,'' said Jack
Barbanel, analyst with Gruntal & Co., New York. ``It's a hedge, but
it's also affected by fundamentals.
   ``Some of (Tuesday's) rise is the whiff of inflation some
traders are picking up on. But you can discount $3 or $4 of the $7
(advance) to South Africa,'' he added. ``We're beginning to seem
some political unrest and that makes people nervous.''
   South Africa provides nearly all of the West's platinum, which
has industrial applications as varied as X-ray scanning equipment
and catalytic converters for autos.
   A nationwide strike Monday marking the 28th anniversary of the
Sharpeville Massacre was honored by as many as 90 percent of the
workers in the Indian Ocean city of Port Elizabeth. Similar
protests were staged elsewhere despite increasingly tough
government measures.
   Gold did not join the runup, finishing 50 cents to $1.60 cents
lower with March at $448.70 a troy ounce on the New York Commodity
Exchange; silver was 1.5 cents to 1.8 cents higher, with March at
646.5 cents a troy ounce.
   Petroleum futures finished mixed after another volatile day New
York Mercantile Exchange.
   Reports that OPEC President Rilwanu Lukman would _ and then
would not _ hold a news conference to unveil price-stabilizing
measures brought wild swings Monday. The same reports pressured
Tuesday's opening and may have sparked a surge at the close.
   ``The same things that played havoc yesterday was responsible
for today's games as well,'' said Nauman Barakat, energy futures
analyst with Smith Barney Harris Upham & Co., New York.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 40 cents lower to 11 cents
higher, with April at $16.09 per 42-gallon barrel; heating oil was
30 cents to 95 cents higher, with April at 46.26 cents a gallon;
and unleaded gasoline was 21 cents to 47 cents higher, with April
at 46.32 cents a gallon.
   After Tuesday's close of business, the American Petroleum
Institute's weekly distillate report was generally construed as
slightly bearish for crude.
   Support for wheat and soybeans at the Chicago Board of Trade
came soon after the open when Monday's big player, C&D Commodities,
began buying again.
   C&D's buying didn't match Monday's levels _ the Chicago-based
house bought 20 million bushels of beans the previous day, compared
to just 4 million Tuesday. But it did helped trigger buying that
pushed the November contract for soybeans up 7 cents to equal a
contract high at $6.66 a bushel.
   Wheat settled 1{ cents to 3{ cents higher, with the contract for
delivery in March at $2.99 a bushel; corn was { cent to 1 cent
lower, with March at $2.00{ a bushel; oats were 2{ cent lower to 5
cents higher, with March at $1.95{ a bushel; and soybeans were 2
cents to 8\ cents higher, with March at $6.32 a bushel.
   A strong move toward frozen pork bellies helped both the
livestock and pork complexes advance at the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
   Live cattle settled .20 cent to .73 cent higher, with April at
74.25 cents a pound; feeder cattle was .25 cent to .50 cent higher,
with March at at 82.35 cents a pound; live hogs were .05 cent to
1.38 cents higher, with April at 46.57 cents a pound; and frozen
pork bellies were .23 cent to 1.45 cents higher, with March at
55.45 cents a pound.
   Stock-index futures climbed on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,
where the contract for June delivery of the Standard & Poors 500
index settled .05 point higher at 270.65. The underlying spot index
advanced .10 point. closing at 268.84.
</TEXT>
