<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Democrats-Trade 1stLd-Writethru f0199 03-22 0660</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Democrats-Trade, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0199,0680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gephardt, Dukakis Trade Charges on Trade</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Clears garble in 13th graf, On July; Also moved on general
newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Richard Gephardt charged Tuesday that
Michael Dukakis' support for tough trade legislation is just ``a
political ploy'' that will end after the Michigan caucuses are over.
   Dukakis, the Massachusetts governor, said his position on trade
has been consistent, and his staff released quotations from last
year indicating his support for major provisions of a Senate trade
bill.
   ``Who is for a tough trade policy? Who is going to be for a
tough trade policy after Michigan?'' Gephardt asked in a telephone
interview Tuesday. ``The answer is, Dick Gephardt is and will be.
Mike Dukakis hasn't been, isn't and won't be.''
   ``When he is on the East and West Coast, he wants to talk about
free trade. When he's in Michigan, he doesn't,'' Gephardt said.
   Gephardt's tough trade legislation, now in a conference
committee on Capitol Hill, has been the capstone of the Missouri
congressman's platform.
   Monday night, Dukakis endorsed trade legislation sponsored by
Michigan Sen. Donald Riegle, who in turn endorsed Dukakis. Gephardt
quickly accused Dukakis of having a ``battlefield conversion'' on
trade, saying the Riegle bill was the Senate version of the
Gephardt legislation.
   Dukakis and Jesse Jackson are tied for the lead in the polls on
Saturday's Michigan caucuses, with Gephardt a distant third.
Dukakis aides say that may be the reason for Gephardt's attacks.
   On Tuesday, Gephardt stepped up the attack, questioning the
sincerity of Dukakis' support for such legislation.
   ``I think he remains against it. I think it is a political
ploy,'' Gephardt said. ``By what he has done, he is trying to have
it both ways. ... Now that he is in Michigan and we are five days
out from the caucuses, he wants to fool the people of Michigan.''
   Dukakis said in Michigan late Monday that his position hasn't
changed.
   ``He has been a strong opponent of the Gephardt bill from the
begining, but has always been an advocate of leveling the (trade)
playing field,'' said Dukakis spokesman Leslie Dach.
   Dukakis' staff on Tuesday pointed to quotes from the
Massachusetts governor last year in favor of the Senate bill.
   On July 11, 1987, Dukakis said, ``I think the trade bill which
the Senate approved yesterday says if there is a consistent pattern
of unfair trade practices ... there I think we have to do
something.''
   ``I feel a lot better about the Senate bill'' than the Gephardt
trade legislation, Dukakis said on Aug. 4, 1987.
   Gephardt said Dukakis ``has said in the past you don't need new
legislation. ... He has been profoundly negative about everything I
have said about trade.''
   The congressman, too, provided quotes from Dukakis last year _
quotes he said back up his charge of a flip-flop.
   ``The president today has all the authority he needs to do
something about those unfair trade practices. We do not need more
laws or more amendments,'' Dukakis said at the Aug. 8 debate at
Drake University, according to Gephardt aides.
   In debates in Dallas and Atlanta, Dukakis told Gephardt, ``You
want a law. Dick, I want to act.''
   And earlier this year in Lansing, Mich., Gephardt aides said,
Dukakis said ``We do not need more legislation.''
   The Gephardt amemdment and the Riegle bill do differ, but both
try to strengthen potential retaliation against U.S. trading
partners for unfair practices. In general, the Riegle bill would
target specific industries in foreign countries which engage in
unfair practices. The Gephardt amendment would trigger retaliation
against another country for running a big surplus with this country
in part through unfair practices.
   ``Dukakis has always felt the president has had the authority to
act. The Riegle amendment ... gives the president a better way to
get there, but he can pretty much get there on his own now,''
Dukakis spokesman Dach said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
