<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Allis-Chalmers     03-22 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Allis-Chalmers,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Loss of $15.2 Million For Fourth Quarter Of '87</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allis-Chalmers Corp., a once-mighty industrial
giant that filed for bankruptcy reorganization last June, Tuesday
reported a net loss of $15.2 million, or $1.17 per share, for the
fourth quarter of 1987.
   The loss, on sales of $109.3 million, compared with a loss of
$5.8 million, or 52 cents per share, for the same period of 1986
when sales totaled $116.8 million.
   For the year, Allis-Chalmers reported a total loss of $29.3
million compared with a loss of $8.6 million in 1986. Sales in 1987
declined to $410 million from $510.3 million in 1986.
   Wendell F. Bueche, chairman and chief executive officer, said
the results reflected obligations from years before the company
scaled down by selling off many of its businesses. Once a major
producer of farm machinery, the company later diversified into
production of a wide range of other equipment.
   Bueche said the cost of health care benefits for retired
employees was disproportionate to the company's size, althoughthe
company has implemented a strategy aimed at reducing that expense.
</TEXT>
