<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 1839EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Scotus-Catalogs     03-22 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Catalogs,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Court Questions Catalog Tax Practices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A department store chain's attempt to avoid
paying taxes for merchandise catalogs received by its Louisiana
customers sparked skeptical questioning Tuesday in the Supreme
Court.
   Andrew Rinker Jr., representing New Orleans-based D.H. Holmes
Co., seemed to be having little success in arguing that his client
should not have to pay a Louisiana ``use tax'' on the catalogs'
value.
   Rinker spent nearly 30 minutes responding to the justices'
questions. By contrast, Shreveport, La., lawyer Robert G. Pugh
concluded his presentation for state tax officials in less than 10
minutes because he was asked so few questions.
   The court's decision is expected by July.
   Rinker, from New Orleans, contended that no tax should be
assessed because the catalogs are published in other states and
mailed directly to Louisiana residents.
   The state imposes a tax on all tangible personal property bought
or used within Louisiana.
   When Rinker argued that the department store chain actually had
paid for a service _ delivery of the catalogs _ and not for goods,
several justices seemed to disagree.
   ``Holmes put this whole operation into creation,'' said Chief
Justice William H. Rehnquist.
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor questioned whether delivery of the
catalogs, even through the U.S. mail, is ``an activity that can be
taxed.''
   She later seemed to answer her own question in the affirmative:
``Holmes caused the distribution in Louisiana. It ordered it. It
paid for it.''
   When Rinker contended that it is Holmes' customers, not Holmes,
who use the catalogs, Justice Byron R. White responded, ``Holmes is
having that use provided.''
   When Justice Thurgood Marshall asked, ``Could Holmes have made a
dollar in the state of Louisiana without the catalogs?'' Rinker
said many of the customers who frequent Holmes' 13 stores in
Louisiana did so long before catalogs were mailed out.
   ``Those are pretty old people,'' White quipped.
   Rinker acknowledged that the department store chain could be
subjected to the Louisiana tax if the catalogs are delivered to the
state and distributed from there. But he said the current set-up
precludes state tax liability.
   Pugh argued that the real taxable activity undertaken by Holmes
is ``maintaing a market in Louisiana for their sales.''
   D.H. Holmes Co. also operates stores in Mississippi, Alabama and
Florida but 82 percent of its catalogs are mailed to Louisiana
residents.
   The state tax imposed on Holmes is based on 82 percent of the
catalogs' value, and the validity of applying the tax to the
catalogs was upheld by state courts.
   The case is D.H. Holmes Co. vs. McNamara, 87-267.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
