<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CFTC-MerrillLynch     03-22 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CFTC-Merrill Lynch,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Merrill Lynch Agrees to Pay $150,000 Fine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Merrill Lynch & Co. Inc. and its futures
trading subsidiary agreed to pay a $150,000 fine to settle
administrative charges arising from alleged fraud committed by a
financial consultant in the firm's Dallas office, the Commodity
Futures Trading Commission said Tuesday.
   The consultant, Charles Dennis Scott of Arlington, Texas, was
charged by the agency with fraud resulting from illegally
allocating trades in cotton futures contracts among his own and his
customers' accounts.
   Merrill Lynch was charged with being liable for Scott's conduct
between December 1980 and August 1982, for failing to properly
supervise him and for failing to keep proper records.
   The firm also was charged with hindering the CFTC investigation
in 1983-84 by failing to promptly provide documents. According to
Dennis Klejna, CFTC enforcement director, the delay amounted to 18
months.
   The firm, its subsidiary and Scott all settled the charges
without admitting or denying them and were ordered to refrain from
future violations.
   Scott agreed to pay a $40,000 fine and accepted a suspension of
his registration for three weeks beginning on Wednesday. He also
agreed to a permanent ban on trading for his own account.
   Klejna said he could not release information on how many
customers were affected or the amount of the alleged fraud.
   Michael Geczi, a spokesman for Merrill Lynch, had no immediate
response to the CFTC announcement.
</TEXT>
