<FILEID>AP-NR-03-22-88 2033EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-LiabilityCrisis 2ndLd-Writethru f0268 03-22 0962</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Liability Crisis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0268,0987</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede AUSTIN, Texas</HEAD>
<HEAD>States Accuse Companies of Restricting Coverage</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with attorney general's comments in
California, where most suits filed, other details, reax, moving
list of plaintiffs lower. Changes byline; Also moved on general
newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight states on Tuesday filed suit accusing
dozens of insurance companies of conspiring to create the liability
insurance crisis, making coverage unavailable or too costly for
many governments and businesses.
   The companies' actions were ``a major contributor to the
insurance crisis that forced so many cities and businesses up
against the wall,'' California Attorney General John Van de Kamp
said at a news conference.
   ``It was the public and the consumer who paid the price for this
collusive exercise in corporate greed,'' he said.
   David Ostwald, a vice president of the Insurance Services
Office, a 1,400-member rate and policy advisory organization named
in the lawsuits, called the claims unfounded and denied the
existence of a conspiracy.
   The lawsuits filed in U.S. District Court here by seven states
accuses major U.S. and British insurance firms, reinsurers and
Ostwald's trade group of using secret agreements and internal
pressure several years ago in an effort to eliminate the most
common type of general liability policy, that covering any damage
that occurs during the policy term regardless of when the damage is
discovered.
   Reinsurers provide vital backup coverage for other insurers, Van
de Kamp said.
   The attorneys general of California, New York, West Virginia,
Wisconsin, Minnesota, Massachusetts and Alabama filed similar suits
in U.S. District Court in San Francisco, naming 32 insurance
companies, underwriters and associations.
   Van de Kamp said Arizona would sue in the same court Wednesday.
A separate lawsuit was filed in state court in Austin, Texas.
   ``These defendants have sucked the blood of our nation's
economic well-being,'' Texas Attorney General Jim Mattox said at a
news conference. Texas filed suit in state court because the state
``has one of the toughest, best antitrust laws in the nation,'' he
said.
   As a result of the conspiracy, California's suit said, property
damage insurance for local governments, non-profit agencies such as
child care centers, and various businesses suddenly became
unavailable or prohibitively expensive.
   In California and elsewhere, local governments cut back or
eliminated services, such as parks and police, because of insurance
expenses, Van de Kamp said. Many local government officials blamed
rising damage awards in injury suits and joined the insurance
industry in efforts to restrict the right to sue.
   The lawsuits claim the companies targeted for elimination
coverage for spills and other types of pollution incidents and
general liability for damage discovered after the life of a policy,
known as ``occurrence'' coverage.
   The companies instead favored more limited policies, covering
only losses that were suffered and claimed within the policy term,
excluding damage that was discovered later, the suits said.
   The lawsuits said four major insurance companies _ Hartford,
Allstate, Cigna and Aetna _ started a campaign in 1984 to curtail
coverage that was generally available in the industry.
   According to the suits, the companies got major U.S. and British
reinsurers, including underwriters at Lloyd's of London, to
threaten a boycott of any U.S. insurance company that provided the
broader coverage.
   Among other things, the plaintiffs seek to restructure the
Insurance Services Office by giving non-insurers a majority on its
board and making public its data on insurance coverage losses.
   Ostwald said from his office in New York City that pollution
insurance and ``occurrence'' coverage remained available, with some
restrictions.
   Pollution coverage was changed in response to expansive court
decisions, he said.
   ``It's simply incorrect to assert that an attempt was made to
impose this policy on the marketplace,'' he said, referring to the
alleged effort to scrap ``occurrence'' coverage.
   Insurance rates increased mainly because of ``a demonstrable
increase in claims losses and a drop in interest rates, slowing
down (insurers') investment income,'' he said.
   Steven Perelman, a spokesman for Aetna Casualty and Surety Co.,
a defendant in Texas and California, termed the action ``another
political move by political officeholders who have consistently
opposed any and all efforts to address the real problems of the
nation's liability system.''
   David Willis, spokesman for the Cigna Property and Casualty
Group, also named in both lawsuits, said, ``It's really an
ingrained condition of how we operate in all our jurisdictions that
we conform to whatever antitrust regulations exist. We do not
violate laws.''
   In addtion to ISO, the suit in Texas named eight companies that
served on the ISO executive committee: Aetna, Cigna, Fireman's Fund
Insurance Co., Hartford Fire Insurance Co., Liberty Mutual
Insurance Co., St. Paul Fire and Marine Insurance Co., The
Travelers Insurance Co. and USF&G Corp.
   Also named in Texas were the Reinsurance Association of America
and reinsurers Merrett Non-Marine Syndicate No. 799 and Robin A.G.
Jackson. Merrett is part of Lloyd's of London, and Jackson is its
underwriter.
   In California, the defendants are: ISO, Hartford; Allstate
Insurance Co.; Aetna; Cigna; Peter N. Miller; Robin A.G. Jackson;
Merrett Underwriting Agencies Mgt. Ltd.; Three Quays Underwriting
Ltd.; Janson, Green Ltd.; Edwards and Payne Management (U.A.) Ltd.;
C.J. Warrilow-Hine & Butcher Ltd.
   Also, J. Brian Hose & Others Ltd.; Harvey Bowring Ltd. _ Murray
Lawrence & Partners; K.F. Alder & Others (U.A.) Ltd.; D.P. Mann &
Others (U.A.) Ltd.; Unionamerica Insurance Co. Ltd.; CNA Re (U.K.)
Ltd.; Terra Nova Insurance Co. Ltd.; Excess Insurance Group Ltd.;
Kemper Reinsurance London Ltd.; Continental Reinsurance Co. (U.K.)
Ltd.
   Also Thomas A. Greene & Co. Inc.; Ballantyne, McKean & Sullivan
Ltd.; R.K. Carvill & Co. Ltd.; General Reinsurance Corp.;
Constitutional Reinsurance Corp.; Mercantile & General Reinsurance
Corp. of America; Prudential Reinsurance Corp.; North American
Reinsurance Corp.; Winterthur Swiss Insurance Co.; Reinsurance
Association of America.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
